/** Etymology data for lemma IDs in chunk 3 */
export const etymologyChunk3: Record<number, string> = {
  "1438": "حُصِّلَ and related words stem from the root ح-ص-ل, with the root verb حَصَلَ meaning \"it was produced, extracted, or came into being\" or \"it became realized or attained.\" حَصَّلَ means \"he obtained, acquired, or gathered something\" or \"he caused something to be brought forth or made clear.\" حُصِّلَ is a passive form meaning \"it was gathered,\" \"it was collected,\" or \"it was brought forth.\" The connection lies in bringing something into a clear, collected, or refined state, directly relating to the root’s emphasis on extraction, attainment, and realization.",
  "1439": "حُطَامٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ط-م, with the root verb حَطَمَ meaning \"he broke,\" \"he shattered,\" or \"he crushed.\" حُطَامٌ means \"debris,\" \"broken pieces,\" or \"stubble.\" This reflects the remnants of something that has been destroyed or crushed, directly connecting to the root's emphasis on breaking and destruction. The term symbolizes the fleeting and fragile nature of worldly possessions or life itself, highlighting themes of impermanence and the ultimate fate of material things.",
  "1440": "حُطَمَةٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ط-م, with the root verb حَطَمَ meaning \"he broke,\" \"he shattered,\" or \"he crushed.\" حُطَمَةٌ means \"crusher\" or \"that which crushes.\" In the Qur'an, it refers to a level of Hellfire that crushes and breaks down its inhabitants. This reflects the intense destructive force that annihilates, directly connecting to the root's emphasis on breaking and destruction. The term serves as a powerful warning about the consequences of moral failure, symbolizing ultimate ruin.",
  "1441": "حُفْرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ف-ر, with the root verb حَفَرَ meaning \"he dug,\" or \"he excavated.\" حُفْرَةٌ means \"pit,\" \"hole,\" or \"grave.\" This reflects the result of the action of digging, directly connecting to the root's emphasis on excavation. The term symbolizes depths or voids created by removing material, often associated with burial sites or traps, highlighting themes of vulnerability and the unseen beneath the surface.",
  "1442": "حُقُبٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ق-ب, with the root verb حَقِبَ meaning \"it was withheld,\" \"it became impeded,\" or \"it ceased or was delayed.\" حُقُبٌ means \"a long period of time,\" \"an age,\" or \"an extended duration.\" The connection lies in the idea of time continuing while something remains withheld, obstructed, or delayed, reflecting cycles of prolonged phases. This term conveys a sense of vast but finite stretches of time, often used in contexts emphasizing endurance, waiting, or extended periods before resolution or change.",
  "1443": "حُكَّامٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ك-م, with the root verb حَكَمَ meaning \"he judged\" or \"he governed.\" حُكَّامٌ means \"judges\" or \"rulers.\" The connection lies in the collective group of those who exercise judgment and governance, directly relating to the root's emphasis on authority and wisdom. This term highlights the role of leaders and judges in upholding justice and order in society, emphasizing the collective responsibility of governance.",
  "1444": "حُكْمٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ك-م, with the root verb حَكَمَ meaning \"he judged\" or \"he governed.\" حُكْمٌ means \"judgment,\" \"ruling,\" or \"decree.\" The connection lies in the outcome or result of judgment and governance, embodying the root's focus on decision-making and authority. This term signifies the act of making a decision or issuing a decree, emphasizing the importance of just rulings and the authority behind commands.",
  "1445": "حُلُمٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ل-م, with the root verb حَلَمَ meaning \"he dreamed\" or \"he attained puberty,\" and حَلُمَ meaning \"he was forbearing, patient, intelligent, and moderate.\" حُلُمٌ means \"dream,\" \"puberty,\" or \"intelligence.\" The root dimensions encompass maturity, rationality, and foresight, emphasizing intellectual growth and self-restraint. The connection lies in the transition from immaturity to awareness and control, whether through the maturation of intellect, the symbolic nature of dreams, or the physical and mental changes of puberty. حُلُمٌ reflects the interplay between imagination, intellect, and maturity, highlighting intelligence and patience as essential qualities in navigating life.",
  "1446": "حُلِيٌّ and related words stem from the root ح-ل-ي, with the root verb حَلِيَتْ meaning \"she acquired an ornament\" or \"she adorned herself.\" حُلِيٌّ means \"ornaments.\" The root dimensions include notions of decoration, embellishment, and enhancement, emphasizing the act of adorning or being adorned. The connection lies in the transformation that occurs through adornment, where adding ornaments enhances beauty and appeal. This reflects the root's emphasis on the aesthetic enhancement achieved through decoration, highlighting the cultural and personal significance of adornment in expressing identity and status.",
  "1447": "حُلُّوا and related words stem from the root ح-ل-ي, with the root verb حَلِيَتْ meaning \"she acquired an ornament\" or \"she adorned herself.\" حُلُّوا means \"they were adorned.\" The connection reflects the concept of beautification or enhancement, where individuals are adorned with something valuable or attractive. In various contexts, this term can indicate both physical and metaphorical adornment, highlighting the act of being graced or enhanced, such as being honored with blessings or virtues.",
  "1448": "حُلْقُومٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ل-ق, with the root verb حَلَقَ meaning \"he cut off entirely,\" and حَلَّقَ meaning \"he or it encircled\" or \"he drew a circle.\" حُلْقُومٌ means \"throat.\" The connection lies in the enclosed nature of the throat passage and its circular form, reflecting the root’s emphasis on circularity and enclosure. The phrase إِذَا بَلَغَتِ الْحُلْقُومَ (\"when the soul reaches the throat\") signifies the moment of death, where life is severed from the body. This reflects the meaning of cutting off entirely, highlighting the throat as vital in life for breathing and in death as the final point of departure.",
  "1449": "حُمِّلَ and related words stem from the root ح-م-ل, with the root verb حَمَلَ meaning \"he carried\" or \"he bore.\" حُمِّلَ is a passive form meaning \"he or it was made to carry\" or \"it was loaded upon him or it.\" The connection lies in being assigned a burden or responsibility by another. It implies obligation and possibly lack of choice, highlighting themes of duty and accountability.",
  "1450": "حُمْرٌ and related terms stem from the root ح-م-ر, with the root verb حَمَّرَ meaning \"he dyed red\" or \"he reddened.\" حُمْرٌ (plural of أَحْمَرُ) means \"red ones\" or \"reddish.\" The connection lies in its direct reference to objects or beings distinguished by the color red, emphasizing the root’s association with vividness, intensity, and distinctiveness.",
  "1451": "حُنَيْنٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ن-ن, with the root verb حَنَّ meaning \"he longed\" or \"he yearned.\" The root also conveys tenderness, compassion, and mercy. حُنَيْنٌ refers to a valley between Mecca and Taif, where the Battle of Hunayn took place, a significant moment in Islamic history. The Muslims, initially overconfident, faced a setback before turning to Allah (ﷻ) for support, ultimately achieving victory. The name حُنَيْنٌ evokes the yearning for Allah’s (ﷻ) aid and the humility that leads to His mercy, serving as a reminder of the tender compassion Allah (ﷻ) bestows on those who rely on Him sincerely.",
  "1452": "حُوبٌ and related words stem from the root ح-و-ب, with the root verb حَابَ meaning \"he committed a sin or a crime.\" حُوبٌ means \"sin,\" \"offense,\" or \"wrongdoing.\" The root reflects themes of deviation from moral or divine law, highlighting acts that breach ethical boundaries or harm others. It conveys a sense of wrongdoing that results in guilt or censure, encompassing both individual failings and broader societal transgressions. This word highlights the gravity of wrongdoing and its consequences.",
  "1453": "حُوتٌ and related words stem from the root ح-و-ت, with the root verb حَاتَ meaning \"he collected or gathered,\" or \"he encompassed or surrounded.\" حُوتٌ translates as \"fish\" or \"whale,\" referring to aquatic creatures of varying size and significance. The root conveys the idea of gathering or enclosing, much like how a fish moves within the boundaries of water or how a whale engulfs and contains its prey. This highlights the theme of enclosure and containment, emphasizing how creation itself exists within the limits set by Allah (ﷻ).",
  "1454": "حُورٌ and related words stem from the root ح-و-ر, with the root verb حَارَ meaning \"he returned or reverted.\" حُورٌ refers to \"fair ones\" or \"fair women,\" characterized by purity, radiance, and exceptional beauty. The root conveys themes of returning, purification, and clarity. This reflects how beauty in its most refined form is associated with purity and brightness, embodying an untainted and perfected state, much like how returning or reverting can signify restoration to an original, flawless condition.",
  "1455": "حِجَابٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ج-ب, with the root verb حَجَبَ meaning \"he prevented or precluded\" and \"he concealed or protected.\" حِجَابٌ means \"veil\" or \"screen,\" referring to something that both blocks or separates and shields or covers. The root conveys meanings of obstruction, restriction, and safeguarding. The connection lies in the dual role of a حِجَابٌ—it serves as a barrier that prevents or restricts access while also concealing and protecting what lies behind it. This highlights its function not only in modesty and separation but also in preservation and security, reinforcing the idea that purposeful veiling or screening can serve to uphold dignity, distinction, and honor.",
  "1456": "حِجَارَةٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ج-ر, with the root verb حَجَرَ meaning \"he prevented\" or \"he restrained.\" حِجَارَةٌ (plural of حَجَرٌ) means \"stones\" or \"rocks.\" The root dimensions encompass notions of restriction, enclosure, and safeguarding, with stones symbolizing natural barriers that prevent or limit movement. They embody firmness, solidity, and the capacity to obstruct, serving both as physical obstacles and as metaphors for resistance or unyielding strength. The connection lies in the dual role of stones as both protectors and hindrances, reflecting the root's core themes of prevention and restriction.",
  "1457": "حِجَجٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ج-ج, with the root verb حَجَّ meaning \"he performed pilgrimage\" or \"he overcame another in an argument, plea, proof, or testimony.\" حِجَجٌ means \"years\" or \"arguments,\" depending on context. The meaning of \"years\" is tied to pilgrimage, which marks time as a cycle of renewal. The root conveys movement, milestones, and unfolding events. Just as pilgrimage is a sacred journey, years represent life’s journey, bringing trials, growth, and accountability. In connection to argument and proof, years bear witness to truth, revealing outcomes and determining what endures.",
  "1458": "حِجٌّ and related words stem from the root ح-ج-ج, with the root verb حَجَّ meaning \"he went to or visited an object of reverence, veneration, respect, or honor\" or \"he performed pilgrimage.\" حِجٌّ means \"pilgrimage,\" referring to the sacred journey to the Kaaba. The root conveys purpose, intention, and sacred obligation. Pilgrimage is not merely physical travel but a spiritual commitment, embodying devotion, obedience, and the pursuit of divine closeness. It represents a journey of purification, fulfillment of duty, and a testament to faith through conscious effort and submission.",
  "1459": "حِجْرٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ج-ر, with the root verb حَجَرَ meaning \"he prevented\" or \"he restrained.\" حِجْرٌ means \"prohibition\" or \"sacred,\" reflecting themes of restriction, enclosure, and safeguarding. The connection lies in the concept of prevention and restraint, as حِجْرٌ represents a protected or forbidden space that limits access to maintain sanctity or safety. The root’s dimensions emphasize creating boundaries for protection. As \"أَصْحَابُ الْحِجْرِ\", it refers to the tribe of Thamud, who lived in a rocky region and carved homes from stone, illustrating the root's themes of restriction and enclosure in both their environment and fate.",
  "1460": "حِدَادٌ and related words stem from the root ح-د-د, with the root verb حَدَّ meaning \"he sharpened\" or \"he prevented, impeded, withheld, or restrained.\" حِدَادٌ refers to both \"mourning\" (a period marked by restrictions) and \"sharpness\" or \"harshness.\" The connection lies in the concept of restriction and severity—mourning imposes limits on actions, reflecting emotional restraint, while sharpness conveys intensity in behavior or speech. Just as a sharpened object cuts with precision, حِدَادٌ captures the piercing nature of grief or harsh words, highlighting the root’s theme of definition, severity, and imposed limits.",
  "1461": "حِذْرٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ذ-ر, with the root verb حَذِرَ meaning \"he was cautious\" or \"he was vigilant.\" حِذْرٌ means \"caution\" or \"wariness,\" similar to حَذَرٌ. The connection lies in the concept of being on guard against potential threats, reflecting the root's emphasis on vigilance. It highlights the continuous awareness needed to prevent harm.",
  "1462": "حِزْبٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ز-ب, with the root verb حَزَبَ meaning \"an event befell him,\" \"it became severe for him,\" or \"it pressed heavily upon him.\" حَزَّبَ means \"he collected, congregated, or assembled people,\" and حِزْبٌ means \"party,\" \"group,\" or \"faction,\" referring to a collective united by a common purpose. The connection lies in intensity and cohesion, as groups often form in response to shared challenges, pressures, or strong convictions.",
  "1463": "حِسَابٌ and related words stem from the root ح-س-ب, with the root verb حَسِبَ meaning \"he reckoned\" or \"he calculated.\" حِسَابٌ means \"account\" or \"reckoning,\" referring to the act of evaluating or accounting. The connection lies in the process of calculation, directly relating to the root's focus on reckoning. This root conveys themes of accountability, evaluation, and moral responsibility, often linked to the ultimate accounting of deeds on the Day of Judgment.",
  "1464": "حِطَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ط-ط, with the root verb حَطَّ meaning \"he lowered,\" \"he reduced,\" or \"he put down.\" حِطَّةٌ means \"forgiveness,\" \"remission,\" or \"a lowering (of burden),\" referring to the removal of sins or hardships. The connection lies in the reduction of burdens, directly relating to the root’s emphasis on diminishing weight or hardship. In the Qur'an, this term appears as a plea for relief, signifying a request for divine mercy and spiritual cleansing. It highlights the concept of lightening one's moral load, emphasizing Allah’s (ﷻ) generosity in alleviating human faults and granting redemption.",
  "1465": "حِفْظٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ف-ظ, with the root verb حَفِظَ meaning \"he guarded,\" \"he protected,\" or \"he preserved.\" حِفْظٌ means \"protection,\" \"guarding,\" \"preservation,\" or \"memorization.\" This reflects the concept of safeguarding something, directly connecting to the root's emphasis on protection and maintenance. The term encompasses both physical protection and the mental act of memorization, highlighting the importance of preserving both tangible and intangible assets.",
  "1466": "حِكْمَةٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ك-م, with the root verb حَكَمَ meaning \"he judged\" or \"he governed.\" حِكْمَةٌ means \"wisdom,\" referring to the ability to discern what is right and act justly. The root also encompasses meanings of restraining, controlling, ensuring firmness, and applying precision in decision-making, emphasizing sound authority and balance. The connection lies in the quality necessary for sound judgment, effective governance, and the restraint to avoid error, reflecting the root's focus on thoughtful decisions. This term captures deep understanding, knowledge, and the skillful application of principles, highlighting the indispensable role of wisdom in achieving justice, harmony, and success.",
  "1467": "حِلٌّ and related words stem from the root ح-ل-ل, with the root verb حَلَّ meaning \"he untied\" or \"he loosened.\" From this comes أَحَلَّ, meaning \"he made lawful,\" and تَحَلَّلَ, meaning \"he became free from restriction.\" حِلٌّ means \"permissible,\" \"allowed,\" or \"free from restriction,\" often used in contrast to إِحْرَامٌ (the state of consecration during pilgrimage). The connection lies in being unbound by specific prohibitions, marking a transition back to lawful engagement in previously restricted actions. This reflects the cyclical nature of sacred time and personal discipline, where restriction and release serve as reminders of divine boundaries and human responsibility.",
  "1468": "حِلْيَةٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ل-ي, with the root verb حَلِيَتْ meaning \"she acquired an ornament\" or \"she adorned herself.\" حِلْيَةٌ means \"ornament,\" emphasizing an individual object of beauty and its transformative effect. The word highlights adornment as a deliberate act of enhancing appearance or character, whether through physical decoration or the metaphorical refinement of virtues, reflecting the root’s focus on the purpose and function of beautification.",
  "1469": "حِمَارٌ and related terms stem from the root ح-م-ر, meaning \"donkey,\" an animal known for its endurance and ability to carry heavy burdens. The root encompasses meanings related to peeling, redness, disease, anger, and dullness, reflecting diverse physical, emotional, and metaphorical dimensions. In classical Arabic, حِمَارٌ is often used metaphorically to symbolize stubbornness, dullness, or ignorance, emphasizing its role as a beast of burden—strong and useful, yet lacking refinement or intellect.",
  "1470": "حِمْلٌ and related words stem from the root ح-م-ل, with the root verb حَمَلَ meaning \"he carried\" or \"he bore.\" حِمْلٌ means \"load\" or \"burden\" and is often used to refer specifically to the load carried by animals or a heavy responsibility. This is distinct from حَمْلٌ, which more commonly refers to the burden of pregnancy. The connection lies in the act of bearing a weight or load. حِمْلٌ can symbolize productivity, the weight of responsibilities, or the outcomes of one's efforts, emphasizing the concept of carrying or bearing significant matters.",
  "1471": "حِنْثٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ن-ث, with the root verb حَنِثَ meaning \"he broke an oath\" or \"he committed a sin.\" حِنْثٌ means \"sin,\" \"perjury,\" or \"the act of breaking an oath.\" The root conveys the idea of betrayal or failure in fulfilling a sacred commitment. It also extends to a broader dimension of moral failure, reflecting any act that deviates from uprightness or truth. This term highlights the significance of fulfilling obligations and the severe implications of transgressing divine or societal principles.",
  "1472": "حِوَلٌ and related words stem from the root ح-و-ل, with the root verb حَالَ meaning \"he or it changed or transformed,\" \"he or it moved or shifted,\" or \"he or it intervened or came between.\" حِوَلٌ means \"change,\" \"alteration,\" or \"transfer.\" The root conveys the idea of shifting away from an original state, whether through misalignment, transformation, or transition. This word emphasizes the condition of being altered or relocated, capturing the essence of movement and modification.",
  "1473": "حِيلَةٌ and related words stem from the root ح-و-ل, with the root verb حَالَ meaning \"he or it changed or transformed,\" \"he or it moved or shifted,\" or \"he or it intervened or came between.\" حِيلَةٌ means \"strategy,\" \"cunning,\" or \"device.\" The root reflects the ability to effect change through cleverness, resourcefulness, or ingenuity. The connection lies in the use of intellect and creativity to navigate challenges, solve problems, or achieve objectives.",
  "1474": "حِينٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ي-ن, with the root verb حَانَ meaning \"it was time,\" \"it became due,\" or \"it became imminent.\" حِينٌ means \"time,\" \"period,\" or \"moment.\" The root conveys themes of appointed moments, due occurrences, and the passage of time, emphasizing specific junctures within the continuum of existence. The connection lies in defining key moments or durations that are significant for actions, events, or outcomes, symbolizing the precision and inevitability of time’s role according to Allah's (ﷻ) will and decree.",
  "1475": "خَائِبِينَ and related words stem from the root خ-ي-ب, with the root verb خَابَ meaning \"he failed\" or \"he was disappointed.\" خَائِبِينَ means \"unsuccessful\" or \"disappointed,\" capturing the state of unmet expectations or unfulfilled hopes. The root conveys themes of loss, despair, and lack of achievement, often tied to the failure of intentions or plans. This word reflects the emotional and practical consequences of failure, serving as a reminder of the importance of reliance on Allah (ﷻ) and perseverance in the face of challenges.",
  "1476": "خَائِضِينَ and related words stem from the root خ-و-ض, with the root verb خَاضَ meaning \"he plunged into\" or \"he indulged in idle talk, or engaged in vain discourse.\" The root conveys themes of entering, passing through, or delving deeply into something, often recklessly or without purpose. خَائِضِينَ means \"ones who plunge into\" or \"vain talkers,\" referring to those who engage in speech or actions without direction or benefit. The connection to the root highlights how such immersion, whether in argument, distraction, or frivolous pursuits, often leads to heedlessness and deviation from meaningful engagement.",
  "1477": "خَائِفٌ and related words stem from the root خ-و-ف, with the root verb خَافَ meaning \"he feared.\" خَائِفٌ means \"one who fears,\" referring to a person experiencing fear or apprehension. The root revolves around fear, apprehension, and caution, encompassing both internal anxiety and outward cautious actions in response to perceived danger. خَائِفٌ highlights the state of being alert and wary, reflecting how fear influences both emotions and behavior.",
  "1478": "خَائِنَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-و-ن, with the root verb خَانَ meaning \"he betrayed.\" The root revolves around betrayal, dishonesty, unfaithfulness, and breach of trust, conveying a failure to uphold responsibility or acting deceitfully. خَائِنَةٌ means \"treachery\" or \"a treacherous woman,\" embodying the essence of betrayal. The connection to the root highlights the act of violating trust, whether through deception, disloyalty, or breaking commitments, emphasizing the destructive nature of treachery in relationships and responsibilities.",
  "1479": "خَابَ and related words stem from the root خ-ي-ب, and as the root verb, it means \"he failed\" or \"he was disappointed.\" The root revolves around failure, disappointment, and deprivation, conveying the idea of an expected success turning into loss. خَابَ signifies an unsuccessful outcome, leading to frustration, regret, or despair. The connection to the root highlights the feeling of being deprived of what was sought, emphasizing the contrast between hope and the reality of failure or unfulfilled expectations.",
  "1480": "خَاتَمٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ت-م, with the root verb خَتَمَ meaning \"he sealed\" or \"he concluded.\" خَاتَمٌ means \"seal,\" \"signet ring,\" or \"the final.\" The connection lies in the act of sealing something to indicate authenticity or closure. As in \"خَاتَمُ النَّبِيِّينَ\" (Seal of the Prophets), it signifies finality and completion, highlighting the culmination of prophethood with Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ).",
  "1481": "خادِعٌ and related words stem from the root خ-د-ع, with the root verb خَدَعَ meaning \"he deceived.\" خادِعٌ means \"deceiver\" or \"one who deceives.\" The root encompasses broader dimensions of cunning, trickery, and manipulation, often involving hidden intentions or a calculated effort to mislead. The connection lies in actively embodying the act of deception, where the deceiver strategically misleads others to achieve their goals, reflecting the root’s focus on subtlety and guile.",
  "1482": "خارِجٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ر-ج, with the root verb خَرَجَ meaning \"he went out\" or \"he exited.\" خارِجٌ means \"exiting,\" \"one who goes out,\" or \"external,\" and can also signify \"outside.\" The root conveys themes of departure and emergence. The connection lies in how خارِجٌ describes something or someone in the process of leaving or existing beyond a boundary, emphasizing the state of being outside, apart, or external to something else.",
  "1483": "خَازِنِينَ and related words stem from the root خ-ز-ن, with the root verb خَزَنَ meaning \"he stored, preserved, or guarded.\" خَازِنِينَ means \"keepers\" or \"managers,\" referring to those entrusted with the responsibility of guarding, managing, or overseeing stored resources. The root encompasses broader dimensions of preservation, protection, and careful management, often associated with maintaining valuable items or provisions securely. The connection lies in the role of safeguarding resources, emphasizing the root's focus on maintaining integrity, security, and accountability over what is stored.",
  "1484": "خَاسِئِينَ and related words stem from the root خ-س-أ, with the root verb خَسَأَ meaning \"he was abased or despised.\" خَاسِئِينَ means \"despised,\" \"rejected,\" or \"repelled,\" often reflecting a state of disgrace or exclusion. In certain contexts, it can also carry a gentler meaning of being diminished or turned back, highlighting human limitations and inability to achieve a desired outcome. The connection lies in the condition of being restrained or rendered incapable, whether through forceful rejection or natural limitation, emphasizing abasement or humbling. This term highlights themes of exclusion, failure, or diminished capability, reflecting the broader implications of the root.",
  "1485": "خَاسِرُونَ and related words stem from the root خ-س-ر, with the root verb خَسِرَ meaning \"he lost.\" خَاسِرُونَ means \"losers\" or \"ones who suffer loss.\" The root conveys themes of failure, deprivation, and ruin. This word embodies the state of loss, emphasizing personal defeat or disadvantage. It reflects not just material setbacks but also deeper consequences, such as being deprived of success or straying from the right path, reinforcing the idea of enduring failure.",
  "1486": "خاسِرَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-س-ر, with the root verb خَسِرَ meaning \"he lost.\" خاسِرَةٌ means \"one in a state of loss\" or \"one experiencing ruin.\" The root encompasses broader dimensions of deprivation, failure, and ruin, implying a significant downfall or disaster. The connection lies in vividly portraying the deep impact of loss, where it signifies the ultimate failure of those who reject truth or guidance. It reflects both an active state of losing and the enduring consequences of such loss.",
  "1487": "خَاشِعُونَ and related words stem from the root خ-ش-ع, with the root verb خَشَعَ meaning \"he was humble or submissive,\" or \"he was still or motionless.\" خَاشِعُونَ means \"ones who are humble\" or \"ones who are submissive.\" The root conveys humility, stillness, silence, and awe, reflecting a state of lowliness and deep reverence. The connection lies in how true humility is both outward and inward—just as stillness signifies surrender, being humble embodies submission of the heart and body. In spiritual contexts, it signifies profound humility before Allah (ﷻ), where one's demeanor reflects sincerity, devotion, and unwavering focus.",
  "1488": "خاصَّةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ص-ص, with the root verb خَصَّ meaning \"it was special, distinct, or distinguished from others,\" and خَصَّصَ meaning \"he distinguished, or singled out.\" خاصَّةٌ means \"special quality\" or \"particularity,\" referring to a unique attribute or property that does not exist, wholly or partly, in another. The root encompasses broader dimensions of exclusivity, specificity, and distinction, emphasizing the act of singling out something or someone for unique characteristics. The connection lies in highlighting exclusiveness or uniqueness, reflecting the root's focus on distinguishing one thing from another based on its defining traits.",
  "1489": "خَاضُوا and related words stem from the root خ-و-ض, with the root verb خَاضَ meaning \"he plunged into\" or \"he indulged in idle talk, or engaged in vain discourse.\" The root emphasizes plunging into or passing through something, often with recklessness or lack of purpose. خَاضُوا means \"they indulged\" or \"they engaged in,\" referring to a collective act of immersing themselves in speech or actions, often without thought or direction. The connection to the root highlights the sense of diving into matters heedlessly, whether in argument, distraction, or pursuits that lack meaning or benefit.",
  "1490": "خَاضِعِينَ and related words stem from the root خ-ض-ع, with the root verb خَضَعَ meaning \"he was submissive,\" \"he lowered his head or neck in humility or submission,\" or \"he bent himself.\" خَاضِعِينَ means \"those who are humbled\" or \"those who are submissive,\" describing individuals in a state of humility or surrender. The root emphasizes lowering oneself in deference or yielding to authority. The connection lies in the act of subduing pride, reflecting humility in worship, devotion, or interpersonal conduct, where reverence and submission take precedence.",
  "1491": "خاطَبَ and related words stem from the root خ-ط-ب, with the root verb خَطَبَ meaning \"he delivered a speech\" or \"he addressed an assembly or congregation.\" خاطَبَ means \"he addressed\" or \"he communicated\" with someone directly, emphasizing purposeful and reciprocal communication. The root conveys themes of public speaking, formal address, and proposing marriage, all involving intentional discourse. The connection highlights the role of dialogue in fostering understanding, strengthening relationships, and resolving conflicts through direct and meaningful communication.",
  "1492": "خَاطِئُونَ and related words stem from the root خ-ط-أ, with the root verb خَطِئَ meaning \"he committed a mistake\" or \"he sinned.\" خَاطِئُونَ means \"ones who sin\" or \"sinners,\" particularly emphasizing deliberate wrongdoing. The root conveys concepts related to making mistakes, committing errors, and engaging in wrongdoing. It encompasses both unintentional errors and intentional sins or offenses.The connection highlights the state of being in error due to intentional misdeeds, highlighting moral responsibility and the consequences of conscious transgression.",
  "1493": "خاطِئَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ط-أ, with the root verb خَطِئَ meaning \"he committed a mistake\" or \"he sinned.\" خاطِئَةٌ refers to \"a sinful woman\" or, as a noun, \"sin\" or \"error,\" emphasizing the person committing the sin, often implying intent but also encompassing unintentional mistakes. The root reflects themes of deviation and moral wrongdoing, highlighting both deliberate and accidental transgressions. The connection emphasizes personal accountability, the consequences of missteps, and the importance of repentance and striving for righteousness.",
  "1494": "خَافَ and related words stem from the root خ-و-ف, and as the root verb, it means \"he feared,\" encapsulating the emotion of fear or apprehension. The root revolves around fear, apprehension, and caution, conveying both internal anxiety and external caution in response to perceived danger. خَافَ highlights how fear influences thought and action, leading to vigilance, avoidance, or a heightened sense of awareness.",
  "1495": "خافِضَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ف-ض, with the root verb خَفَضَ meaning \"he lowered.\" خافِضَةٌ means \"one that lowers,\" \"that which brings down,\" or \"one that abases,\" emphasizing the act of reducing status, position, or strength. The root conveys humility, submission, and bringing something down, whether physically, metaphorically, or socially. In the Qur'an, it describes the Day of Judgment as an event that will lower some and elevate others, illustrating Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect justice, where worldly power and pride are overturned based on one’s deeds.",
  "1496": "خافِيَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ف-ي, with the root verb خَفِيَ meaning \"he or it was hidden or concealed\" or \"he or it became unapparent.\" خافِيَةٌ means \"a hidden thing\" or \"that which is concealed.\" The root conveys concealment, subtlety, and obscurity, referring to things not readily perceived. The connection lies in embodying the state of hiddenness, where something remains beyond immediate awareness. This signifies unseen truths or realities that require deeper insight, emphasizing the limitations of surface perception.",
  "1497": "خَالٌ and related words stem from the root خ-و-ل, with the root verb خَالَ meaning \"he ruled or governed\" or \"he managed or administered.\" The root revolves around bestowal, provision, stewardship, and privilege. It conveys the idea of giving wealth, dependents, or responsibility to someone, often as a favor or grant. خَالٌ means \"maternal uncle,\" signifying a familial relationship. The connection to the root highlights the traditional role of a maternal uncle as a figure of care, influence, or guidance within the extended family, reflecting themes of oversight and involvement.",
  "1498": "خَالَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-و-ل, with the root verb خَالَ meaning \"he ruled or governed\" or \"he managed or administered.\" The root revolves around bestowal, provision, stewardship, and privilege, conveying the idea of granting wealth, dependents, or responsibility to someone as a favor or trust. خَالَةٌ means \"maternal aunt,\" signifying a familial relationship. The connection to the root reflects the traditional role of a maternal aunt as a caregiver and supporter within the extended family, embodying themes of nurture, guidance, and entrusted responsibility.",
  "1499": "خَالِدُونَ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-د, with the root verb خَلَدَ meaning \"he remained\" or \"he lasted long.\" خَالِدُونَ means \"they remain\" or \"they remain forever,\" signifying continuity and permanence. The root encompasses themes of longevity, eternal existence, and unchanging states, whether in a physical or spiritual sense. This word is often associated with the eternal nature of the hereafter, describing the permanence of reward or punishment in the afterlife. This connection highlights the concept of timelessness, emphasizing the enduring reality of what lies beyond this transient world and the profound implications of one's deeds on their everlasting journey.",
  "1500": "خالِصٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ص, with the root verb خَلَصَ meaning \"he was pure\" or \"he became sincere.\" خالِصٌ means \"pure,\" \"sincere,\" or \"exclusive.\" The root conveys purity, sincerity, and separation from anything mixed or impure. The connection lies in the state of being unadulterated, whether in substance, intention, or devotion. This emphasizes the importance of wholehearted sincerity, particularly in faith and actions, where nothing should be tainted by ulterior motives.",
  "1501": "خالِصَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ص, with the root verb خَلَصَ meaning \"he was pure\" or \"he became sincere.\" خالِصَةٌ means \"sincerity\" or \"exclusive,\" emphasizing a state of being pure, unmixed, or free from external influences. The root conveys concepts related to purity, clarity, and freedom from impurity or difficulty. It encompasses actions of purifying, refining, rescuing, and delivering from harm. The connection highlights sincerity and exclusivity, where something is set apart or dedicated entirely to a purpose, free from impurities or distractions, reflecting true devotion and undivided focus.",
  "1502": "خَالِفِينَ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ف, with the root verb خَلَفَ meaning \"he came after\" or \"he succeeded.\" The root conveys succession, substitution, and contrast, where one follows or remains in place of another. خَالِفِينَ means \"those who lag behind\" or \"those who stay behind,\" emphasizing inaction or failure to advance when required. This highlights the consequences of hesitation and complacency, serving as a warning against neglecting duties and missing opportunities to fulfill responsibilities or contribute meaningfully.",
  "1503": "خَالِقٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ق, with the root verb خَلَقَ meaning \"he created,\" \"he shaped,\" or \"he formed.\" خَالِقٌ means \"creator,\" reflecting the act of bringing things into existence. ٱلْخَالِقُ, one of Allah's (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Creator,\" highlighting Allah’s (ﷻ) power to originate all things from nothing and to shape them with precision and wisdom. The root emphasizes creative power, artistry, and purposeful design, and it signifies Allah’s (ﷻ) mastery in crafting the universe with intricate order.",
  "1504": "خَالِيَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-و, with the root verb خَلا meaning \"he was alone,\" \"it became empty,\" \"he passed away or ceased to exist,\" or \"it was past or elapsed.\" The root conveys emptiness, solitude, separation, absence, relief, and the passage of time. خَالِيَةٌ means \"empty,\" \"desolate,\" or \"past,\" referring to a place, state, or time devoid of inhabitants or content. The connection to the root lies in the absence of presence or activity, reflecting solitude, abandonment, or something that once existed but has now vanished. It also signifies the passage of time, emphasizing the contrast between former fullness and present emptiness, capturing the inevitability of change and decline.",
  "1505": "خَامِدُونَ and related words stem from the root خ-م-د, with the root verb خَمَدَ meaning \"it was extinguished\" or \"he or it became silent or still.\" The root revolves around extinguishing, subsiding, stillness, and suppression, often referring to fire going out but also extending to the loss of energy, motion, or prominence. خَامِدُونَ means \"extinguished,\" \"extinct,\" \"lifeless,\" or \"silent and dead,\" describing a state of complete stillness or inactivity. This reflects the root’s concept of ceasing, where something that once burned brightly or moved with force has faded into silence or nonexistence.",
  "1506": "خامِسَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-م-س, with the root verb خَمَسَ meaning \"he took one-fifth.\" خامِسَةٌ is an ordinal number meaning \"fifth,\" indicating the position in a sequence related to the number five.",
  "1507": "خَانُوا and related words stem from the root خ-و-ن, with the root verb خَانَ meaning \"he betrayed.\" The root revolves around betrayal, dishonesty, unfaithfulness, and breach of trust, conveying a failure to uphold responsibility or acting deceitfully. خَانُوا means \"they betrayed,\" signifying a collective act of disloyalty or broken trust. The connection to the root highlights the severity of betrayal when committed by a group, emphasizing the impact of dishonesty and the consequences of violating trust on a broader scale.",
  "1508": "خَاوِيَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-و-ي, with the root verb خَوَى meaning \"it was empty, deserted, or desolate\" or \"it became hollow or empty.\" The root revolves around emptiness, hollowness, and abandonment, conveying a state of void or ruin. خَاوِيَةٌ means \"desolate,\" \"empty,\" or \"collapsed,\" describing both a place stripped of life and its people either gone or lifeless. The connection to the root highlights not only physical emptiness but also the absence of movement, presence, or vitality, capturing the image of a space or community once full but now left hollow and forsaken.",
  "1509": "خَبَالٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ب-ل, with the root verb خَبِلَ meaning \"he was corrupt,\" \"he was unsound\" or \"he was disordered.\" خَبَالٌ means \"corruptness\" or \"unsoundness\" or \"disordered state.\" The root conveys the idea of causing ruin or disorder, either physically or mentally, leading to impairment, foolishness, or unsoundness. The connection lies in the destructive effects of harmful actions. It serves as a warning against sowing discord or engaging in activities that lead to moral or societal decay.",
  "1510": "خَبَتْ and related words stem from the root خ-ب-و, with the root verb خَبَا meaning \"it was extinguished,\" often referring to fire. خَبَتْ is the feminine form. The root conveys themes of extinguishing, concealment, and fading from view. The connection lies in how something that was once active or visible becomes subdued—whether a fire dying out, something becoming hidden, or a person fading into obscurity. This word reflects the transition from presence to absence, emphasizing the stillness or disappearance that follows.",
  "1511": "خَبَرٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ب-ر, with the root verb خَبَرَ meaning \"he knew or had knowledge of,\" and أَخْبَرَ meaning \"he informed.\" خَبَرٌ means \"news,\" \"information,\" or \"report.\" The root conveys the idea of deep knowledge—acquiring information through testing, experience, or familiarity. The connection lies in how خَبَرٌ is not just passing information but something known with certainty or insight, reflecting a level of awareness that comes from experience and understanding.",
  "1512": "خَبُثَ and related words stem from the root خ-ب-ث, and as the root verb, it means \"he was filthy or impure,\" or \"he or it was of a corrupt nature.\" The root conveys themes of corruption, impurity, and moral or physical foulness, often contrasting with purity and goodness. خَبُثَ emphasizes a state of inner or outward corruption, affecting both its source and what it produces. Just as impurity taints whatever comes from it, corruption prevents benefit and leads to harm, whether in character, actions, or outcomes. What is corrupt lacks the ability to sustain goodness, much like barren or tainted land that cannot yield anything of value.",
  "1513": "خَبِيثٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ب-ث, with the root verb خَبُثَ meaning \"he was filthy or impure,\" or \"he or it was of a corrupt nature.\" خَبِيثٌ means \"evil\" or \"impure.\" The root conveys themes of corruption, impurity, and moral or physical foulness. The connection lies in how خَبِيثٌ extends beyond physical filth to encompass moral corruption, deceit, and harm. Just as impurity taints and degrades, evil and corruption pollute a person’s character or actions, making them harmful or offensive, whether in speech, behavior, or nature.",
  "1514": "خَبِيثَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ب-ث, with the root verb خَبُثَ meaning \"he was filthy or impure,\" or \"he or it was of a corrupt nature.\" خَبِيثَةٌ means \"evil woman\" or \"impure thing.\" The root conveys themes of corruption, impurity, and moral or physical foulness. The connection lies in how خَبِيثَةٌ represents something tainted—whether in character, nature, or effect—deviating from purity and goodness. Just as impurity spoils what was once clean, moral corruption and wickedness degrade a person or thing, making them harmful or undesirable in their essence or influence.",
  "1515": "خَبِيرٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ب-ر, with the root verb خَبَرَ meaning \"he knew or had knowledge of.\" ٱلْخَبِيرُ, one of Allah's (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The All-Aware,\" signifying His complete and thorough knowledge of all things, including the hidden and intricate details of creation. The connection lies in how خَبِيرٌ goes beyond general knowledge to deep, precise awareness. This name emphasizes Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect understanding, encompassing everything seen and unseen, serving as a reminder that nothing escapes His knowledge.",
  "1516": "خَبْءٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ب-أ, with the root verb خَبَأَ meaning \"he concealed,\" \"he hid,\" or \"it became hidden, covered, or obscured from view.\" خَبْءٌ means \"hidden thing\" or \"secret.\" The connection lies in the concept of concealment or things kept unseen. It reminds us that Allah (ﷻ) knows all hidden matters, whether in the heavens or the earth, emphasizing His absolute knowledge and the importance of sincerity in actions.",
  "1517": "خَتَمَ and related words stem from the root خ-ت-م, and as the root verb, it means \"he sealed\" or \"he concluded.\" The root encompasses broader dimensions of finality, completion, and authentication, often symbolizing the act of securely closing or affirming something. This includes physical sealing, as with a document, or metaphorical sealing, such as the conclusion of a process or event. The connection emphasizes the decisive and definitive nature of sealing, whether to indicate authenticity, closure, or irrevocable completion.",
  "1518": "خَتَّارٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ت-ر, with the root verb خَتَرَ meaning \"he acted or behaved with treachery or unfaithfulness.\" خَتَّارٌ, as an intensive form, means \"extremely treacherous.\" The root encompasses themes of betrayal, treachery, and breaking trust, emphasizing the severe and repeated nature of such actions.",
  "1519": "خَدٌّ and related words stem from the root خ-د-د, with the root verb خَدَّ meaning \"he dug\" or \"he furrowed.\" خَدٌّ refers to the \"cheek,\" a prominent part of the face. The root conveys meanings of engraving, marking, and creating visible impressions, often linked to permanence or depth. The connection lies in how the cheek, like a furrow in the ground, can bear visible marks—whether from expressions or from lines formed over time—emphasizing the way impressions, both physical and emotional, leave a lasting impact.",
  "1520": "خَذُولٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ذ-ل, with the root verb خَذَلَ meaning \"he abandoned or deserted,\" or \"he failed or disappointed.\" خَذُولٌ is an intensive form meaning \"one who often deserts\" or \"habitual forsaker.\" The root conveys themes of forsaking, failing to support, and betraying trust. The connection lies in how خَذُولٌ reflects repeated abandonment, emphasizing not just a single act of desertion but a pattern of failing others when they need help. This reinforces the root’s meaning of withholding support, showing the weight of consistent neglect or betrayal.",
  "1521": "خَرابٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ر-ب, with the root verb خَرِبَ meaning \"it became in a state of ruin, uninhabited, or deserted.\" خَرابٌ means \"ruin\" or \"desolation.\" The root conveys themes of destruction, decay, and abandonment, often involving deliberate action. The connection lies in how خَرابٌ results from intentional damage or neglect, leading to desolation.",
  "1522": "خَراجٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ر-ج, with the root verb خَرَجَ meaning \"he went out\" or \"he exited.\" خَراجٌ refers to \"tax\" or \"tribute,\" specifically what is paid out as an obligation, often tied to agricultural yield or land productivity. The root conveys themes of emergence, production, and giving forth. This word reflects something that results from effort or resources, much like how crops emerge from the land through labor. Tribute and taxation represent what is extracted or given as a due outcome, emphasizing the concept of something being brought forth as a result of obligation or natural process.",
  "1523": "خَرَجَ and related words stem from the root خ-ر-ج, and as the root verb, it means \"he went out\" or \"he exited.\" It denotes the action of departing from a place, state, or condition, often implying a movement from an enclosed or confined space into openness or freedom. The root conveys themes of transition, separation, and change, emphasizing an active departure or emergence. This verb forms the basis for numerous derived meanings, such as physical exits, metaphorical departures (e.g., leaving a state of ignorance), or even rebellion and deviation, reflecting the dynamic and multifaceted nature of the root.",
  "1524": "خَرَقَ and related words stem from the root خ-ر-ق, and as the root verb, it means \"he tore,\" \"he pierced,\" or \"he made a hole or opening.\" It also extends metaphorically to mean \"he forged\" or \"he fabricated,\" particularly in reference to lies or falsehoods. The root conveys themes of tearing, piercing, and creating openings. This word reflects both physical destruction and reckless or unjust behavior, as tearing something apart can symbolize recklessness, ignorance, or transgression. The act of fabricating falsehoods mirrors this concept, as it involves breaking truth and creating deception.",
  "1525": "خَرَّاصُونَ and related words stem from the root خ-ر-ص, with the root verb خَرَصَ meaning \"he spoke by opinion or conjecture.\" خَرَّاصُونَ is an intensive form meaning \"habitual conjecturers\" or \"those who constantly speculate falsely.\" The root encompasses broader themes of conjecture, estimation, and fabrication, often tied to speech that lacks certainty or truth. The connection highlights the repetitive and deliberate nature of falsehood or baseless claims, emphasizing the root's focus on the unreliability and harm caused by such actions.",
  "1526": "خَرَّ and related words stem from the root خ-ر-ر, with the root verb خَرَّ meaning \"he or it fell down\" or \"he prostrated.\" The root encompasses broader dimensions of falling, descending, or dropping, often conveying a sudden or intentional act. It symbolizes submission, humility, or the inevitability of being brought down from a higher state. The connection lies in the physical act of falling or prostrating, which also represents spiritual surrender, as in bowing down in reverence or acknowledgment of something greater. This root reflects themes of surrender, humility, and the natural consequence of forces bringing something to a lower state.",
  "1527": "خَرْجٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ر-ج, with the root verb خَرَجَ meaning \"he went out\" or \"he exited.\" خَرْجٌ can mean \"expense\" or \"expenditure,\" referring to what goes out in terms of resources. It also signifies something that comes out, such as produce, revenue, or an amount paid. The root conveys exiting, emerging, and bringing forth. This word emphasizes the outflow of wealth or effort, particularly in the context of tribute or tax. It reflects the idea of departure and loss, highlighting the cost required to fulfill obligations or sustain productivity.",
  "1528": "خَرْدَلٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ر-د-ل, referring to a \"mustard seed.\" The mustard seed, renowned for its minuscule size, is used metaphorically to signify something exceedingly small yet impactful. In the Qur'an, the mustard seed symbolizes the idea that even the smallest actions, deeds, or elements do not escape accountability. It serves as a profound reminder of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect awareness and justice, demonstrating that no matter how hidden or insignificant something may seem, it is fully known and accounted for.",
  "1529": "خَزائِنُ and related words stem from the root خ-ز-ن, with the root verb خَزَنَ meaning \"he stored, preserved, or guarded.\" خَزائِنُ (plural of خَزِينَةٌ) means \"treasuries\" or \"storehouses.\" The root conveys the concepts of storing, preserving, and guarding. It pertains to actions involving the accumulation and safekeeping of items, as well as the places designated for such purposes. It also encompasses the ideas of concealing, hiding, restraining, or withholding. The connection lies in the accumulation and preservation of wealth or resources, directly relating to the root's focus on storage. It highlights abundance and the importance of managing what is valuable.",
  "1530": "خَزَنَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ز-ن, with the root verb خَزَنَ meaning \"he stored, preserved, or guarded.\" خَزَنَةٌ refers to \"appointed keepers\" or \"guardians,\" specifically used for angels who guard Paradise or Hell. The root conveys themes of storing, preserving, and guarding. This word reflects the role of protectors entrusted with significant realms, emphasizing responsibility, control, and the careful management of what is preserved or safeguarded.",
  "1531": "خَسارٌ and related words stem from the root خ-س-ر, with the root verb خَسِرَ meaning \"he lost.\" خَسارٌ refers to \"loss\" or \"ruin,\" representing deprivation or failure. The root conveys themes of destruction and diminishing value, emphasizing the severity of loss. This word highlights the inevitable consequences of being in a state of loss, whether material, moral, or spiritual. It reflects not just temporary setbacks but complete deprivation and irreversible damage, serving as a warning against neglecting truth or responsibility.",
  "1532": "خَسَفَ and related words stem from the root خ-س-ف, with the root verb meaning \"he sank,\" \"he made disappear,\" \"he swallowed up or engulfed,\" or \"it (the moon) was eclipsed.\" The term specifically refers to the sinking of the earth or the obscuring of celestial bodies, particularly the sun and the moon losing their light. The root pertains to actions causing something to subside or vanish, often associated with natural phenomena like eclipses or calamities leading to destruction. The connection lies in the act of vanishing or being consumed, reflecting the root's emphasis on complete removal from sight. It symbolizes acts of divine retribution or cosmic events associated with the Day of Resurrection. ",
  "1533": "خَسِرَ and related words stem from the root خ-س-ر, and as the root verb, it means \"he lost.\" It refers to experiencing loss, failing to achieve gain, or being deprived of something valuable. The root conveys themes of deprivation, ruin, and failure, extending beyond material setbacks to spiritual or moral consequences. This word emphasizes the weight of loss as a result of neglect, poor choices, or missed opportunities. It highlights the reality of accountability, where actions lead to regret and deprivation, reinforcing the lasting impact of failure.",
  "1534": "خَشَعَتْ and related words stem from the root خ-ش-ع, with the root verb خَشَعَ meaning \"he was humble or submissive,\" or \"he was still or motionless.\" خَشَعَتْ means \"she or it became humble\" or \"it became subdued.\" The root conveys stillness, reverence, and subdued quietness, implying an attitude of deep humility or submission. The connection lies in the state of being reduced to humility, whether through physical stillness or spiritual surrender. This reflects the root's emphasis on awe, deference, and the surrender of pride.",
  "1535": "خَشِيَ and related words stem from the root خ-ش-ي, and as the root verb, it means \"he feared\" or \"he dreaded,\" often implying fear with reverence. This fear is not merely of harm but arises from deep respect and awareness of the magnitude of what is feared. The connection highlights profound consciousness and awe of Allah (ﷻ), where fear is intertwined with love and understanding, motivating one to act righteously.",
  "1536": "خَشْيَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ش-ي, with the root verb خَشِيَ meaning \"he feared\" or \"he dreaded,\" often implying fear with reverence. خَشْيَةٌ means \"fear\" or \"awe,\" especially the kind rooted in deep understanding and reverence. This term encapsulates a fear that is informed and conscious, reflecting an awareness of the greatness and majesty of Allah (ﷻ). The connection highlights the importance of possessing a fear that leads to humility and motivates righteous actions.",
  "1537": "خَصاصَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ص-ص, with the root verb خَصَّ meaning \"it was special, distinct, or distinguished from others,\" and خَصَّصَ meaning \"he distinguished, or singled out.\" خَصاصَةٌ refers to a small intervening space or opening, as well as \"need\" or \"poverty.\" The connection lies in how poverty, like an opening, represents a gap or deficiency, exposing vulnerability. It also signifies being distinctly characterized by deprivation, setting one apart due to lack. This emphasizes the duty to recognize and support those in need with mindfulness and compassion.",
  "1538": "خَصِمُونَ and related words stem from the root خ-ص-م, with the root verb خَصَمَ meaning \"he disputed in a valid or sound manner.\" خَصِمُونَ means \"those who are disputants\" or \"argumentative.\" The root conveys contention, opposition, and legal disputation, often marked by sharpness in argument. The connection lies in the tendency to challenge others or engage in conflicts, reflecting a persistent inclination toward verbal contention and opposition in disputes.",
  "1539": "خَصِيمٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ص-م, with the root verb خَصَمَ meaning \"he disputed in a valid or sound manner.\" خَصِيمٌ is an intensive form meaning \"an obstinate disputant,\" \"a strong adversary,\" or \"a litigant,\" referring to someone who engages persistently and intensely in disputes, whether for themselves or on behalf of others. The root conveys contention, opposition, and legal disputation, often marked by sharpness in argument. The connection highlights not just the act of disputing but doing so with persistence and intensity, portraying someone highly argumentative and emphasizing the difficulties such individuals pose in achieving truth or resolution.",
  "1540": "خَصْمٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ص-م, with the root verb خَصَمَ meaning \"he disputed in a valid or sound manner.\" خَصْمٌ means \"adversary,\" \"opponent,\" or \"rival.\" The root conveys contention, opposition, and legal disputation, often involving sharpness in argument. The connection is direct, signifying someone who stands in opposition or engages in conflict against another. It encapsulates the nature of rivalry and dispute, whether in legal matters or personal conflicts.",
  "1541": "خَضِرٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ض-ر, with the root verb اِخْضَرَّ meaning \"it became green\" or \"it was fresh or flourishing.\" خَضِرٌ means \"a place with abundant lush green vegetation\" or \"what is green, such as seed-produce.\" The root encompasses broader dimensions of softness, tenderness, and vitality, reflecting a state of flourishing and abundance. The connection emphasizes the imagery of life, growth, and the nurturing aspects of nature, evoking richness and fertility in the natural world.",
  "1542": "خَطَأٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ط-أ, with the root verb خَطِئَ meaning \"he committed a mistake\" or \"he sinned.\" خَطَأٌ means \"error,\" \"mistake,\" or \"fault,\" often referring to unintentional wrongdoing. The root conveys concepts related to making mistakes, committing errors, and engaging in wrongdoing. It encompasses both unintentional errors and intentional sins or offenses. It reflects human fallibility, emphasizing the need for accountability, correction, and seeking forgiveness, while highlighting the opportunity for guidance and mercy.",
  "1543": "خَطِفَ and related words stem from the root خ-ط-ف, and as the root verb, it means \"he snatched\" or \"he took away swiftly.\" خَطِفَ emphasizes the act of taking something abruptly or swiftly, often with an element of stealth or unexpectedness. The root broadly conveys concepts related to sudden and swift actions of snatching, seizing, or taking away. It describes the act of quickly grabbing something, often with the implication of force or surprise.",
  "1544": "خَطِيئَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ط-أ, with the root verb خَطِئَ meaning \"he committed a mistake\" or \"he sinned.\" خَطِيئَةٌ signifies \"sin\" or \"offense,\" particularly one that is deliberate or intentional. The root conveys moral deviation and wrongdoing, encompassing both conscious and unintentional errors. The connection highlights personal accountability, where deliberate transgressions carry consequences, emphasizing the need for repentance and the pursuit of moral integrity.",
  "1545": "خَطْفَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ط-ف, with the root verb خَطِفَ meaning \"he snatched\" or \"he took away swiftly.\" خَطْفَةٌ means \"a snatching\" or \"a sudden seizing.\" The root conveys concepts of sudden and swift actions, emphasizing quickness, force, and surprise. The connection lies in the abruptness of taking something in an instant, capturing the essence of rapid movement and unexpected seizure.",
  "1546": "خَفِيفٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ف-ف, with the root verb خَفَّ meaning \"he or it was light,\" referring to weight, movement, or manner. خَفِيفٌ means \"light,\" or \"nimble.\" The root conveys concepts of lightness, swiftness, and reduction in weight or intensity. The connection lies in the absence of heaviness, whether physically, in burdens, or in movement. It signifies ease, agility, and a state free from difficulty or excess weight.",
  "1547": "خَفِيٌّ and related words stem from the root خ-ف-ي, with the root verb خَفِيَ meaning \"he or it was hidden or concealed\" or \"he or it became unapparent.\" خَفِيٌّ means \"hidden,\" \"secret,\" or \"concealed,\" emphasizing something that is not apparent or visible. The root encompasses broader themes of invisibility, subtlety, and obscurity, whether in physical, metaphorical, or spiritual contexts. It highlights the idea of things being beyond immediate perception, reflecting the hidden nature of certain realities, intentions, or truths.",
  "1548": "خَفَّتْ and related words stem from the root خ-ف-ف, with the root verb خَفَّ meaning \"he or it was light,\" referring to weight, movement, or manner. خَفَّتْ is the feminine form meaning \"it became light,\" indicating a transition to a state of reduction. The root conveys ease, relief, and lessening in intensity, whether physically, emotionally, or spiritually. The connection lies in the dual nature of lightness—while it can signify relief, it can also represent deficiency and failure. In the context of the Day of Judgment, lightened scales symbolize the absence of good deeds and the weight of accountability, emphasizing the consequences of one’s actions.",
  "1549": "خَفَّفَ and related words stem from the root خ-ف-ف, with the root verb خَفَّ meaning \"he or it was light,\" referring to weight, movement, or manner. خَفَّفَ means \"he lightened,\" \"he alleviated,\" or \"he reduced.\" The root conveys lightness, swiftness, and the reduction of weight or intensity. The connection lies in making something less burdensome, whether physically, emotionally, or in responsibilities. It signifies efforts to ease hardship, reduce difficulties, or simplify matters, reflecting compassion and mercy in alleviating burdens.",
  "1550": "خَلا and related words stem from the root خ-ل-و, and as the root verb, it means \"he was alone,\" \"it became empty,\" \"he withdrew,\" \"he secluded himself,\" \"he passed away or ceased to exist,\" or \"it was past or elapsed.\" The root conveys emptiness, solitude, separation, absence, relief, and the passage of time. It reflects both physical isolation and detachment, where something or someone is removed from others. The term also captures the transition from presence to emptiness, whether in a place, condition, or the fading of something that once existed. This highlights the contrast between fullness and void, reinforcing the root’s essence of solitude, transience, and the passage of time.",
  "1551": "خَلَاقٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ق, with the root verb خَلَقَ meaning \"he created,\" \"he shaped,\" or \"he formed.\" The root conveys precise measurement, formation, and eventual deterioration. خَلَاقٌ means \"portion\" or \"nature and character,\" referring to what one is divinely given, whether in wealth, virtue, or disposition. Just as creation is measured with purpose, one's share in life—both materially and morally—must be valued and used wisely. This highlights the responsibility to take care of what one has, as neglect leads to loss and decay.",
  "1552": "خَلَصُوا and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ص, with the root verb خَلَصَ meaning \"he was pure\" or \"he became sincere.\" خَلَصُوا means \"they became pure\" or \"they were sincere,\" and also \"they withdrew, retired, or set themselves apart.\" The root conveys purity, exclusivity, and separation from what is mixed or impure. The connection lies in how withdrawing or setting oneself apart aligns with purification—by removing external influences, they attain sincerity and unity of purpose. This reflects an intentional distinction, where separation signifies refinement and devotion, embodying the essence of being pure in thought, action, or faith.",
  "1553": "خَلَطُوا and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ط, with the root verb خَلَطَ meaning \"he mixed\" or \"he blended.\" خَلَطُوا means \"they mixed\" or \"they blended,\" reflecting the collective act of combining elements. The root conveys concepts related to mixing, blending, and mingling. It encompasses actions of combining different elements, which can lead to either proper integration or confusion and disorder through improper mixing. In a spiritual sense, it can symbolize the intermingling of good and bad deeds, highlighting the challenge of maintaining clarity and purity in actions.",
  "1554": "خَلَفَ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ف, and as the root verb, it means \"he came after\" or \"he succeeded.\" The root conveys succession, substitution, and contrast, where one follows or replaces another in position, time, or responsibility. خَلَفَ emphasizes the interconnectedness of generations and the duty to preserve what is entrusted. It reflects the natural cycle of taking over from predecessors, highlighting the importance of upholding values, fulfilling responsibilities, and contributing positively to what will be passed on to future generations.",
  "1555": "خَلَقَ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ق, and as the root verb, it means \"he created\" or \"he made.\" It represents the act of bringing something into existence from nothing. This term is foundational in describing Allah’s (ﷻ) role as the Creator of the heavens, the earth, and everything within them. It highlights Allah's (ﷻ) supreme power and complete authority over all creation, emphasizing that nothing exists without His command. خَلَقَ not only signifies the act of creation but also the intricate design, purpose, and balance in everything Allah (ﷻ) brings into existence.",
  "1556": "خَلِيفَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ف, with the root verb خَلَفَ meaning \"he came after\" or \"he succeeded.\" The root conveys succession, substitution, and contrast, where one takes the place of another in position, time, or responsibility. خَلِيفَةٌ means \"successor\" or \"vicegerent,\" signifying someone entrusted with authority to act on behalf of another. This highlights both the honor and accountability of stewardship, emphasizing the duty to uphold justice, fulfill entrusted responsibilities, and act with wisdom in carrying out what has been delegated.",
  "1557": "خَلِيلٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ل, with the root verb خَلَّ meaning \"it penetrated or pierced.\" The root conveys perforation, gaps, mixing, and interweaving, reflecting how things pass through and become intertwined. خَلِيلٌ means \"intimate friend\" or \"close companion,\" emphasizing a bond that deeply permeates one’s heart. Just as something penetrates and weaves through gaps, true friendship is an inseparable connection that intertwines with one's being. In the Qur'an, Prophet Abraham (ﷺ) is called خَلِيلُ الله, highlighting the unmatched depth and sincerity of his relationship with Allah (ﷻ).",
  "1558": "خَلَّاقٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ق, with the root verb خَلَقَ meaning \"he created,\" \"he shaped,\" or \"he formed.\" خَلَّاقٌ is an intensive form, meaning \"Supreme Creator,\" referring to Allah (ﷻ) as the One who continuously creates without limitation. The term highlights not only Allah’s (ﷻ) ability to create from nothing but also His infinite capacity to bring new forms into existence and sustain them. This intensification emphasizes Allah's (ﷻ) boundless, ongoing creative power and mastery over the universe, reinforcing His unique attribute as the Creator of all things.",
  "1559": "خَلُّوا and related words stem from the root خ-ل-و, with the root verb خَلا meaning \"he was alone\" or \"it became empty.\" خَلَّى means \"he released (something) from burden or obligation\" or \"he withdrew from or made (something) empty or vacant.\" خَلُّوا means \"they left alone,\" emphasizing the deliberate act of leaving or abandoning. The root conveys emptiness, solitude, and separation, reflecting a transition from presence to absence. خَلُّوا highlights intentional withdrawal or allowing another to leave, reinforcing the themes of detachment and isolation.",
  "1560": "خَلْفٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ف, with the root verb خَلَفَ meaning \"he came after\" or \"he succeeded.\" The root conveys succession, substitution, and contrast, where one follows another in time, position, or responsibility. خَلْفٌ means \"behind\" in multiple senses—spatially, referring to something physically at the back; temporally, indicating what has passed or been left in the past; and in terms of what remains, signifying what is left behind or left over. This layered meaning highlights the relationship between what follows and what was, emphasizing the impact of what is left behind and how it shapes the future.",
  "1561": "خَلْقٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ق, with the root verb خَلَقَ meaning \"he created,\" \"he shaped,\" or \"he formed.\" خَلْقٌ means \"creation\" or \"creature.\" This term captures both the process and the product of creation, embodying the act of bringing something into existence as well as the created being itself. The word خَلْقٌ reflects on the marvels of the universe, encouraging contemplation of the intricate design and purpose behind all created things. It invites reflection on the Creator’s wisdom, power, and precision, highlighting the awe-inspiring nature of existence itself.",
  "1562": "خَمْرٌ and related words stem from the root خ-م-ر, with the root verb خَمَرَ meaning \"he or it covered or concealed\" or \"he or it veiled or obscured.\" The root revolves around covering, concealing, veiling, and fermentation. خَمْرٌ means \"wine,\" which alters perception by clouding judgment, much like a veil that conceals what lies beneath. This connection highlights how intoxication metaphorically \"covers\" the mind, aligning with the root’s concept of obscuring, concealing, and transformation.",
  "1563": "خَمْسَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-م-س, with the root verb خَمَسَ meaning \"he took one-fifth.\" خَمْسَةٌ is the cardinal number \"five,\" representing the numerical value associated with division into five parts.",
  "1564": "خَمْسِينَ and related words stem from the root خ-م-س, with the root verb خَمَسَ meaning \"he took one-fifth.\" خَمْسِينَ is the number \"fifty,\" signifying a collective of tens of five.",
  "1565": "خَمْطٌ and related words stem from the root خ-م-ط, with the root verb خَمَطَ meaning \"he struck forcefully\" or \"it (a tree or plant) bore bitter, unwholesome, or bad-tasting fruit.\" The root revolves around forceful taking, striking, and bitterness, conveying harshness, injustice, or unpleasantness in both action and quality. خَمْطٌ refers to a type of bitter or thorny tree, known for its harsh and unyielding nature. The connection to the root lies in the discomfort and severity associated with the tree, whether through its bitter fruit or sharp thorns, symbolizing affliction, difficulty, or the unfavorable consequences tied to the root’s meanings.",
  "1566": "الخَنَّاسُ and related words stem from the root خ-ن-س, with the root verb خَنَسَ meaning \"he withdrew\" or \"he retreated.\" The root revolves around withdrawal, concealment, and receding, conveying the sense of something pulling back, vanishing, or becoming hidden after being present. الخَنَّاسُ specifically refers to Satan, emphasizing his repeated act of whispering evil thoughts to humans before retreating into hiding. This term captures his deceptive and persistent nature, constantly lurking yet withdrawing when resisted. The connection to the root highlights the importance of vigilance and seeking protection through remembrance of Allah (ﷻ) to counter his subtle and concealed attacks.",
  "1567": "خَوَالِفُ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ف, with the root verb خَلَفَ meaning \"he came after\" or \"he succeeded.\" The root conveys succession, substitution, and contrast, where one follows or remains in place of another. خَوَالِفُ (plural of خَالِفَةٌ) means \"those who stay behind,\" referring to those who remain while others advance. This highlights a state of inactivity, exclusion, or reluctance, whether by necessity or choice. It reflects the contrast between those who move forward and those who are left behind, emphasizing the significance of action, responsibility, and engagement.",
  "1568": "خَوَّانٌ and related words stem from the root خ-و-ن, with the root verb خَانَ meaning \"he betrayed.\" The root revolves around betrayal, dishonesty, unfaithfulness, and breach of trust, conveying a failure to uphold responsibility or acting deceitfully. خَوَّانٌ is an emphatic form meaning \"great betrayer,\" intensifying the concept of habitual or extreme betrayal. The connection to the root highlights someone who not only commits betrayal but does so repeatedly and without remorse, emphasizing the depth of treachery and the complete disregard for trust and loyalty.",
  "1569": "خَوْضٌ and related words stem from the root خ-و-ض, with the root verb خَاضَ meaning \"he plunged into\" or \"he indulged in idle talk, or engaged in vain discourse.\" The root highlights themes of immersion, passing through, and engaging deeply, often without direction or purpose. خَوْضٌ means \"indulgence\" or \"vain discourse,\" referring to reckless involvement in speech or actions. The connection to the root emphasizes the tendency to engage thoughtlessly in matters that lack benefit, warning against wasting time and energy on trivial or harmful pursuits instead of meaningful and purposeful engagement.",
  "1570": "خَوْفٌ and related words stem from the root خ-و-ف, with the root verb خَافَ meaning \"he feared.\" خَوْفٌ means \"fear,\" representing the state or feeling of fear, often characterized by a sense of vulnerability or apprehension. The root conveys themes of caution, heightened awareness, and an instinctive response to perceived danger or harm. خَوْفٌ encompasses not just a reaction to immediate threats but also a deeper, reflective fear tied to accountability and the unknown. This term serves as a spiritual reminder to transform fear into positive action, guiding one toward preparedness, humility, and reliance on Allah (ﷻ). ",
  "1571": "خَيْرٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ي-ر, with the root verb خَارَ meaning \"he chose or preferred\" or \"he sought what was best or most beneficial.\" The root revolves around goodness, preference, and choice, conveying the act of selecting what is most beneficial or superior. خَيْرٌ means \"goodness,\" \"better,\" or \"best,\" encompassing both moral virtue and material benefit. The connection to the root highlights how خَيْرٌ extends beyond worldly prosperity to the pursuit of moral excellence, emphasizing that true goodness is found in wise choices that align with righteousness and divine guidance.",
  "1572": "خَيْرَاتٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ي-ر, with the root verb خَارَ meaning \"he chose or preferred\" or \"he sought what was best or most beneficial.\" The root revolves around goodness, preference, and choice, conveying the act of selecting what is most beneficial or superior. خَيْرَاتٌ means \"good things,\" \"benefits,\" or \"blessings,\" encompassing both material and moral goodness. The connection to the root highlights the concept of abundance in goodness, whether in provisions, virtues, or opportunities, emphasizing the value of seeking and embracing what brings the greatest benefit.",
  "1573": "خَيْطٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ي-ط, with the root verb خَاطَ meaning \"he sewed.\" The root revolves around thread, stitching, joining, and thin linear forms, conveying the idea of connecting, fastening, or forming a continuous link between things. خَيْطٌ means \"thread\" or \"string,\" referring to the essential element used in sewing. Just as a thread both separates and connects, it symbolizes how clarity emerges through distinctions, whether in physical structure or in transitions that define boundaries and mark new beginnings.",
  "1574": "خَيْلٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ي-ل, with the root verb خَالَ meaning \"he imagined (something to be in a certain way)\" or \"he perceived (something) in his mind.\" The root revolves around imagination, perception, illusion, and grandeur, conveying both mental perception and physical presence. خَيْلٌ refers to \"horses\" or \"cavalry,\" symbolizing strength, elegance, and dominance. The connection to the root highlights how horses, with their commanding presence and swift movement, evoke an image of power and grandeur, aligning with the broader theme of perception, whether real or imagined.",
  "1575": "خُبْرٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ب-ر, with the root verb خَبَرَ meaning \"he knew or had knowledge of.\" خُبْرٌ means \"knowledge or intelligence,\" or \"skill or expertise,\" conveying deep understanding or mastery gained through experience. The root conveys themes of knowledge, experience, and familiarity. The connection lies in how خُبْرٌ reflects not just awareness but insight acquired through practice and exposure, emphasizing a level of proficiency that comes from direct involvement and thorough understanding.",
  "1576": "خُبْزٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ب-ز, with the root verb خَبَزَ meaning \"he baked bread.\" خُبْزٌ means \"bread.\" The root revolves around baking, cooking, and preparation. It conveys the idea of processing dough by kneading and exposing it to fire to produce bread.",
  "1577": "خُرُوجٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ر-ج, with the root verb خَرَجَ meaning \"he went out\" or \"he exited.\" خُرُوجٌ means \"going out\" or \"departure.\" The root conveys themes of exiting, emerging, and separation. This word emphasizes the act of leaving or moving away from a place, state, or condition, whether physically or figuratively. It reflects a transition, highlighting movement away from what was previously established.",
  "1578": "خُرْطُومٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ر-ط-م, with the root verb خَرْطَمَ meaning \"he struck or hit his nose.\" خُرْطُومٌ specifically refers to the trunk of an elephant or the nose of a man. The root conveys actions related to the nose or snout, including striking, twisting, or elevating it. The nose is often associated with pride and arrogance, making its striking symbolic of humiliation. This word highlights the nose as a prominent feature, whether in human anatomy or the extended trunk of an elephant, emphasizing its function and significance.",
  "1579": "خُسْرٌ and related words stem from the root خ-س-ر, with the root verb خَسِرَ meaning \"he lost.\" خُسْرٌ means \"loss\" or \"perdition.\" The root conveys themes of deprivation, failure, and ruin. This word emphasizes being in a state of loss, often carrying a deeper existential connotation of ultimate failure. It reflects not just material decline but a condition of irreversible deprivation, highlighting the consequences of misguided choices or neglect.",
  "1580": "خُسْرانٌ and related words stem from the root خ-س-ر, with the root verb خَسِرَ meaning \"he lost.\" خُسْرانٌ is an intensive form meaning \"utter loss\" or \"complete ruin.\" The root conveys themes of deprivation, failure, and destruction. This word amplifies the concept of loss to its utmost degree, emphasizing total and irreversible deprivation. It reflects a state where recovery is no longer possible, highlighting the severe consequences of misguided actions or neglect.",
  "1581": "خُشُبٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ش-ب, with the root verb خَشَبَ meaning \"he mixed a thing with another thing,\" and تَخَشَّبَ meaning \"he became like wood, hard or stiff.\" خُشُبٌ (plural of خَشَبٌ) means \"pieces of wood\" or \"planks.\" The connection lies in how wood, once cut, becomes rigid and lifeless, often mixed with other materials for support. In the Qur'an, hypocrites are likened to \"خُشُبٌ مُسَنَّدَةٌ\"—\"propped-up pieces of wood\"—symbolizing their outward uprightness while relying on external reinforcement, exposing their inner emptiness and hypocrisy. This warns against superficiality, where appearance is mixed with deception, masking the absence of true sincerity.",
  "1582": "خُشُوعٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ش-ع, with the root verb خَشَعَ meaning \"he was humble or submissive,\" or \"he was still or motionless.\" خُشُوعٌ means \"humility,\" \"submissiveness,\" or \"reverence.\" The root conveys a state of stillness, awe, and quiet surrender, reflecting deep internal humility. The connection lies in the complete focus and submission that arise from recognizing one's place before Allah (ﷻ), leading to sincerity in worship and an undistracted heart fully attuned to Him.",
  "1583": "خُضْرٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ض-ر, with the root verb اِخْضَرَّ meaning \"it became green\" or \"it was fresh or flourishing.\" خُضْرٌ means \"greens\" or \"green things,\" often referring to green plants or vegetation. The connection emphasizes abundance and the flourishing of life, symbolizing sustenance and the blessings of growth provided by Allah (ﷻ).",
  "1584": "خُطُوَاتٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ط-و, with the root verb خَطَا meaning \"he took a step\" or \"he walked with long strides.\" خَطْوَةٌ refers to \"a single step\" or \"the distance of a step,\" focusing on an individual movement or space covered in one stride. In contrast, خُطُوَاتٌ refers to multiple steps or a sequence of movements, emphasizing progression rather than just the act of stepping itself. The root conveys stepping, pacing, and striding, describing both physical movement and broader notions of advancement. It also extends to overstepping or transgressing boundaries, highlighting how steps can represent either progress toward a goal or deviation from the right path.",
  "1585": "خُلَطَاءُ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ط, with the root verb خَلَطَ meaning \"he mixed\" or \"he blended.\" خُلَطَاءُ means \"associates\" or \"partners,\" referring to people who are closely connected, whether in business, friendship, or shared circumstances. The root conveys mixing and intermingling, where different elements come together, sometimes in harmony and other times in conflict. This blending of interests often blurs ethical boundaries, making it easy for individuals to deceive, betray, or exploit one another. This highlights the tendency for injustice in relationships and the necessity of faith and righteous action in upholding fairness, trust, and accountability.",
  "1586": "خُلُقٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ق, with the root verb خَلَقَ meaning \"he created\" or \"he shaped.\" The root conveys precise measurement, formation, and bringing something into existence. خُلُقٌ means \"character\" or \"moral nature,\" highlighting how a person’s inner disposition is shaped just as their physical form takes shape. The connection reflects that just as Allah (ﷻ) creates with beauty and precision, one’s character should be cultivated with care, embodying good morals and righteousness. This highlights the responsibility to refine one’s nature, ensuring that actions and ethics align with what pleases Allah (ﷻ).",
  "1587": "الْخُلُودُ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-د, with the root verb خَلَدَ meaning \"he remained\" or \"he lasted long.\" الْخُلُودُ refers to \"eternity\" or \"the state of eternal existence,\" emphasizing continuous and unending being. The root conveys permanence, timelessness, and enduring stability, whether physically or spiritually. The connection lies in the concept of an existence without end, reflecting the ultimate reality of the Hereafter. In the Qur'anic context, the \"Day of Eternity\" highlights the everlasting nature of this final abode, where the rewards of Paradise remain without interruption or decline.",
  "1588": "خُلَّةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ل, with the root verb خَلَّ meaning \"it penetrated or pierced.\" The root conveys perforation, gaps, mixing, and interweaving, reflecting how things pass through or become deeply connected. خُلَّةٌ means \"deep affection\" or \"intimate friendship,\" emphasizing a bond that penetrates the heart and intertwines two individuals. Just as something passes through gaps and becomes inseparable, true friendship is marked by unwavering trust and closeness. This highlights the depth of companionship, where hearts are connected in a way that transcends mere association.",
  "1589": "خُلِّفُوا and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ف, with the root verb خَلَفَ meaning \"he came after\" or \"he succeeded.\" The root conveys succession, substitution, and contrast, where one follows another in time, position, or responsibility. خُلِّفُوا is a passive form meaning \"they were left behind,\" indicating a state of exclusion, delay, or abandonment. This can imply being deliberately set apart, failing to keep up, or facing consequences for inaction, highlighting the weight of being left behind—whether by choice, circumstance, or decree.",
  "1590": "خُلْدٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-د, with the root verb خَلَدَ meaning \"he remained\" or \"he lasted long.\" خُلْدٌ means \"eternity,\" focusing on the concept of timeless existence and perpetual permanence. The root encompasses broad meanings of longevity, stability, and unchanging continuity, reflecting the nature of something that endures without end. خُلْدٌ highlights the abstract idea of eternity, reinforcing the lasting and immutable nature of existence beyond the temporal world.",
  "1591": "خُمُرٌ and related words stem from the root خ-م-ر, with the root verb خَمَرَ meaning \"he or it covered or concealed\" or \"he or it veiled or obscured.\" The root centers on the ideas of covering, veiling, concealing, and fermentation, each involving a process of hiding or transformation. خُمُرٌ (plural of خِمَارٌ) means \"head coverings\" or \"veils,\" which shield parts of the body from view. The connection to the root lies in the way these garments serve as a barrier, physically covering what is beneath, just as the root conveys the act of concealing or enclosing something from sight.",
  "1592": "خُمُسٌ and related words stem from the root خ-م-س, with the root verb خَمَسَ meaning \"he took one-fifth.\" خُمُسٌ means \"one-fifth\" or \"a fifth part.\" It directly represents the fractional value associated with the root, often used in contexts of division or allocation.",
  "1593": "خُنَّسٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ن-س, with the root verb خَنَسَ meaning \"he withdrew\" or \"he retreated.\" The root revolves around withdrawal, concealment, and receding, conveying the idea of something pulling back or vanishing. خُنَّسٌ refers to celestial bodies, particularly stars or planets, that retreat or become concealed. This includes stars disappearing at setting, becoming invisible in daylight, or the five planets—Saturn, Jupiter, Mars, Venus, and Mercury—that exhibit retrograde motion, appearing to pause, move backward, and resume course. The connection highlights their shifting visibility and seeming withdrawal, aligning with disappearance and reemergence.",
  "1594": "خُوارٌ and related words stem from the root خ-و-ر, with the root verb خَارَ meaning \"it uttered a low, faint, or weak sound\" or \"it (a bull or a cow) lowed or bellowed.\" The root revolves around weakness, faintness, and low sounds, carrying the sense of something lacking force or strength. خُوارٌ means \"lowing\" or \"bellowing,\" typically referring to the deep vocal sound of a cow. The connection to the root lies in how such sounds, though loud, often lack power or stability, reflecting a state of weariness, distress, or vulnerability.",
  "1595": "خِتامٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ت-م, with the root verb خَتَمَ meaning \"he sealed\" or \"he concluded.\" خِتامٌ means \"conclusion\" or \"end\" or \"last portion,\" referring to the final part or end of something. The connection lies in the concept of sealing or completing, where خِتامٌ represents the culmination or final touch that perfects the whole, much like a seal authenticates and finalizes a document. This term emphasizes completeness and perfection, directly relating to the root's meaning.",
  "1596": "خِزْيٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ز-ي, with the root verb خَزِيَ meaning \"he was ashamed\" or \"he was disgraced.\" خِزْيٌ translates as \"disgrace\" or \"humiliation,\" referring to the state of being shamed or dishonored. The root conveys themes of shame, loss of dignity, and embarrassment. The connection lies in the profound consequences of actions that result in dishonor, reflecting the state of being stripped of respect and left in a condition of shame or humiliation.",
  "1597": "خِطَابٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ط-ب, with the root verb خَطَبَ meaning \"he delivered a speech\" or \"he addressed an assembly or congregation.\" خِطَابٌ means \"speech,\" referring to words directed toward someone. The root conveys themes of delivering messages, engaging in formal discussions, and addressing matters of importance. The connection highlights the role of speech in communication, emphasizing its function in building relationships, conveying intent, and resolving conflicts through clear and purposeful dialogue.",
  "1598": "خِطْءٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ط-أ, with the root verb خَطِئَ meaning \"he committed a mistake\" or \"he sinned.\" خِطْءٌ refers to \"sin,\" \"error,\" or \"fault,\" emphasizing an act of wrongdoing or deviation from what is correct. It encompasses both deliberate transgressions and unintentional errors, highlighting the failure to meet a standard or ideal. The root conveys themes of missing the mark, falling short in judgment or action, and bearing responsibility for one's missteps, whether intentional or accidental.",
  "1599": "خِطْبَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ط-ب, with the root verb خَطَبَ meaning \"he delivered a speech,\" \"he addressed an assembly or congregation,\" and \"he proposed (to a woman in marriage).\" خِطْبَةٌ can mean \"sermon\" or \"oration,\" as well as \"marriage proposal.\" The root conveys themes of formal address, public speaking, and significant communication. The connection lies in the structured and purposeful nature of these acts, whether addressing an audience in a sermon or initiating a marriage proposal. Both reflect moments of importance that mark the beginning of social or religious proceedings.",
  "1600": "خِلَافٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ف, with the root verb خَلَفَ meaning \"he came after\" or \"he succeeded.\" خِلَافٌ means \"behind,\" or \"opposite,\" often emphasizing a spatial or relational contrast. The root reflects themes of succession, positioning, and contrast, highlighting the relationship between what precedes and what follows, or what aligns and what opposes. خِلَافٌ captures the interplay between proximity and separation, whether in physical space, moral stance, or temporal sequence, highlighting the balance between following, opposing, or standing apart.",
  "1601": "خِلَالٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ل, with the root verb خَلَّ meaning \"it penetrated or pierced\" or \"it passed through or moved between things.\" The root conveys perforation, gaps, mixing, and interweaving, reflecting how things pass through spaces or become interconnected. خِلَالٌ means \"intervals,\" \"spaces between,\" or \"amidst,\" emphasizing the presence of gaps or openings within a structure or context. This connects to the root by highlighting the concept of penetration and interweaving, symbolizing moments, elements, or relationships that thread through a larger whole, shaping how things come together or remain apart.",
  "1602": "خِلْفَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ف, with the root verb خَلَفَ meaning \"he came after\" or \"he succeeded.\" The root conveys succession, substitution, and contrast, where one thing follows another in time, position, or responsibility. خِلْفَةٌ means \"alternation\" or \"succession,\" referring to cyclical patterns such as the alternation of day and night. This highlights the natural order of continuous change, where one state replaces another, emphasizing the rhythm of time, renewal, and the inevitability of transitions.",
  "1603": "خِنزِيرٌ stems from the quadriliteral root خ-ن-ز-ر, with some linguists linking it to خ-ز-ر (distortion, crookedness) or خ-ن-ز (foulness, corruption). خِنزِيرٌ means \"pig\" or \"swine,\" reflecting its association with filth and impurity in Islamic teachings. These roots broadly convey themes of harm and uncleanness, aligning with the pig’s nature and unsanitary habits. Scientifically, pigs are known carriers of pathogens like Hepatitis E and parasitic infections due to their exposure to fecal matter. This connection reinforces the importance of avoiding physical and spiritual corruption, emphasizing the wisdom in maintaining purity and well-being.",
  "1604": "خِيَاطٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ي-ط, with the root verb خَاطَ meaning \"he sewed.\" خِيَاطٌ means \"needle,\" signifying the tool essential for sewing. The root revolves around thread, stitching, joining, and thin linear forms, conveying the idea of connecting, fastening, or forming a continuous link between things. While the needle serves as a means of precision and connection, it also represents narrowness and restriction, emphasizing how passage through a confined space can be nearly impossible, reinforcing the contrast between what can be joined and what remains beyond reach.",
  "1605": "خِيَامٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ي-م, with the root verb خَامَ meaning \"he set up a tent\" or \"he remained.\" The root revolves around dwelling, camping, staying, and setting up tents, conveying the ideas of residence, settlement, and temporary habitation. خِيَامٌ is the plural of خَيْمَةٌ, meaning \"tents,\" referring to shelters traditionally used in open or desert-like environments. The connection to the root highlights both the physical structure of tents and the transient nature of dwelling in them, symbolizing movement, impermanence, and adaptation to changing surroundings.",
  "1606": "خِيَانَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-و-ن, with the root verb خَانَ meaning \"he betrayed.\" The root revolves around betrayal, dishonesty, unfaithfulness, and breach of trust, conveying a failure to uphold responsibility or acting deceitfully. خِيَانَةٌ means \"betrayal\" or \"treachery,\" encapsulating the act of breaking trust or being unfaithful. The connection to the root highlights how خِيَانَةٌ extends beyond personal relationships to include oaths, contracts, and societal obligations, emphasizing the gravity of betrayal and its far-reaching moral and ethical consequences.",
  "1607": "خِيفَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-و-ف, with the root verb خَافَ meaning \"he feared.\" خِيفَةٌ means \"fear\" or \"apprehension,\" referring to a cautious and vigilant fear characterized by an acute awareness of potential harm or danger. The root conveys themes of heightened alertness, protective caution, and emotional sensitivity to perceived risks. خِيفَةٌ reflects a fear that inspires careful consideration and foresight, prompting one to avoid harm or wrongdoing. It highlights the positive role of fear as a guide to mindfulness, encouraging thoughtful actions and reliance on Allah (ﷻ). This term highlights the balance between fear and wisdom.",
  "1608": "خِيَرَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ي-ر, with the root verb خَارَ meaning \"he chose or preferred\" or \"he sought what was best or most beneficial.\" The root revolves around goodness, preference, and choice, conveying the act of selecting what is most beneficial or superior. خِيَرَةٌ means \"choice\" or \"selection,\" emphasizing the deliberate act of choosing the best or most excellent. The connection to the root highlights the idea of discernment and wisdom in making choices, reflecting the pursuit of what is truly valuable, whether in decisions, qualities, or outcomes.",
  "1609": "دَائِبَيْنِ and related words stem from the root د-أ-ب, with the root verb دَأَبَ meaning \"he labored persistently\" or \"he continued tirelessly.\" دَائِبَيْنِ is the dual form of دَائِبٌ, meaning \"both constantly moving\" or \"both persisting,\" often referring to the sun and moon in their ceaseless courses. The root reflects themes of perseverance, continuity, and unrelenting effort, symbolizing the harmony and reliability of natural processes.",
  "1610": "دَائِرَةٌ and related words stem from the root د-و-ر, with the root verb دَارَ meaning \"he or it turned, revolved, or rotated.\" دَائِرَةٌ means \"circle,\" \"turn,\" or \"calamity,\" emphasizing something that revolves or returns upon itself. The root reflects cyclical motion and repetition. Just as a circle continuously loops back to its starting point, this word symbolizes cycles in life, including the recurrence of events or the way misfortunes encircle people, highlighting the inevitability of fate and the ever-turning nature of circumstances.",
  "1611": "دَائِمٌ and related words stem from the root د-و-م, with the root verb دَامَ meaning \"he lasted,\" \"he remained,\" or \"he continued.\" دَائِمٌ means \"everlasting\" or \"continuous.\" The connection lies in the concept of something enduring without interruption, reflecting permanence and stability. This word conveys the idea of a state or condition that persists over time, without change or cessation. Whether in physical, emotional, or abstract contexts, دَائِمٌ emphasizes constancy and unbroken continuity, directly tying into the root’s meaning of lasting and enduring over an indefinite period.",
  "1612": "دَابِرٌ and related words stem from the root د-ب-ر, with the root verb دَبَرَ meaning \"it came after or followed\" or \"he turned his back or went away.\" The root revolves around sequential occurrence, management, and decline, conveying the idea of things following one another, planning, and retreat over time. دَابِرٌ means \"the last part\" or \"last remnant,\" often implying utter destruction or finality. The connection to the root highlights the concept of something reaching its ultimate end, whether as the final trace of existence, the complete removal of something, or the conclusion of a sequence, reinforcing themes of succession, disappearance, and downfall.",
  "1613": "دَابَّةٌ and related words stem from the root د-ب-ب, with the root verb دَبَّ meaning \"he or it crawled\" or \"he or it moved slowly.\" The root revolves around gradual movement, creeping, subtle spreading, and continuous progression. دَابَّةٌ refers to \"a creature\" or \"beast\" that moves upon the earth, encompassing all living beings that crawl, walk, or traverse the ground. The connection to the root highlights the slow, steady nature of movement found in creatures, emphasizing persistence, progression, and the way life spreads and sustains itself across the earth.",
  "1614": "دَاحِضَةٌ and related words stem from the root د-ح-ض, with the root verb دَحَضَ meaning \"it slipped, slided, or became unstable\" or \"it became null, void, or baseless,\" often describing arguments or claims that lack a solid foundation. The root conveys themes of instability and failure, emphasizing the inability to hold firm or sustain credibility. Just as something that slips loses its footing and collapses, this word highlights the fragility of a position that cannot withstand scrutiny, reinforcing the idea of weakness and ultimate invalidation.",
  "1615": "دَاخِرُونَ and related words stem from the root د-خ-ر, with the root verb دَخَرَ meaning \"he subdued or humbled\" or \"he overpowered or suppressed.\" دَاخِرُونَ means \"humbled,\" \"subdued,\" or \"humiliated,\" reflecting a state of being brought low. The root revolves around humiliation, submission, and overpowering, emphasizing the act of forcing someone into subjugation or rendering them helpless. Just as one who is overpowered has no choice but to yield, this word conveys an enforced submission, highlighting a condition where resistance is futile, and one is left with no option but to accept defeat.",
  "1616": "دَاخِلُونَ and related words stem from the root د-خ-ل, with the root verb دَخَلَ meaning \"he entered.\" دَاخِلُونَ refers to \"ones who enter\" or \"inside,\" emphasizing the act of entering or being within. The root revolves around entry, penetration, mixture, and involvement, conveying both physical entry and metaphorical engagement. Just as something that enters becomes part of a space or condition, this word reflects the state of inclusion, whether in a place, circumstance, or connection, highlighting both movement into something and presence within it.",
  "1617": "دَارٌ and related words stem from the root د-و-ر, with the root verb دَارَ meaning \"he or it turned, revolved, or rotated.\" دَارٌ means \"house\" or \"dwelling,\" emphasizing a space where people reside. The root reflects themes of circular motion, movement, and repetition. Just as turning follows a set path, this word conveys the idea of an enclosed, structured space, highlighting a place of settlement, stability, and continuity. It also reflects an intrinsic aspect of human nature—to build homes, form families, and establish communities, repeating this cycle across generations as part of humanity’s essence and innate creation.",
  "1618": "دَاعٍ and related words stem from the root د-ع-و, with the root verb دَعَا meaning \"he called or invited\" or \"he supplicated or prayed.\" دَاعٍ means \"caller\" or \"inviter,\" emphasizing the act of summoning or urging others. The root conveys communication, appeal, and urging toward something. Just as calling involves extending an invitation or making a request, this word reflects the role of one who actively directs or encourages others, whether toward guidance, supplication, or a cause, highlighting the root’s emphasis on outreach and engagement. It is often used in a general sense, focusing on the act of calling itself.",
  "1619": "دَاعِيَ and related words stem from the root د-ع-و, with the root verb دَعَا meaning \"he called or invited\" or \"he supplicated or prayed.\" دَاعِيَ means \"caller\" or \"one who invites,\" emphasizing the role of someone actively summoning others. The root conveys communication, appeal, and urging toward something. Just as a call seeks a response, this word reflects the act of guiding, inviting, or encouraging others, particularly toward beneficial matters. It is often used when specifying what the caller is inviting toward, highlighting the purpose and direction of the call rather than just the act itself.",
  "1620": "دَافِعٌ and related words stem from the root د-ف-ع, with the root verb دَفَعَ meaning \"he repelled or pushed away\" or \"he prevented or averted.\" دَافِعٌ means \"defender\" or \"one who repels,\" emphasizing the act of resisting or preventing something. The root conveys both physical movement (pushing, resisting) and figurative actions (defense, payment, or preventing harm). Just as pushing something away removes it from causing harm, this word reflects the role of someone who actively wards off danger or opposition, highlighting protection, resistance, and the effort to prevent undesirable outcomes.",
  "1621": "دَافِقٌ and related words stem from the root د-ف-ق, with the root verb دَفَقَ meaning \"it poured forth or gushed,\" or \"it was ejected or expelled.\" دَافِقٌ means \"gushing\" or \"pouring forth,\" describing a forceful and abundant flow. The root conveys broader meanings associated with energetic and dynamic movement, emphasizing the idea of forceful ejection or rapid streaming. These meanings extend to various contexts, including natural processes like the gushing of water, signifying vitality and vigor. This highlights the powerful and purposeful nature of processes tied to this root, reflecting themes of strength, abundance, and dynamic activity.",
  "1622": "دَامُوا and related words stem from the root د-و-م, with the root verb دَامَ meaning \"he lasted,\" \"he remained,\" or \"he continued.\" دَامُوا means \"they last\" or \"they remain\" and is often used in the expression ما داموا, meaning \"as long as they remain.\" The verb emphasizes continuity and duration, highlighting a steady and unbroken presence over time. Just as something that lasts remains unchanged, this word reflects persistence, endurance, and the sustained nature of states or actions.",
  "1623": "دَانٍ and related words stem from the root د-ن-و, with the root verb دَنَا meaning \"he or it drew near\" or \"he approached.\" دَانٍ means \"near,\" \"close,\" or \"imminent,\" referring to nearness in a general or abstract sense. The term emphasizes proximity, whether in time, space, or occurrence, and in the Qur'an, it is used to highlight the closeness of the rewards in the hereafter.",
  "1624": "دَانِيَةٌ and related words stem from the root د-ن-و, with the root verb دَنَا meaning \"he or it drew near\" or \"he approached.\" دَانِيَةٌ means \"near\" or \"drawing near.\" The connection lies in the concept of nearness, directly reflecting the root's meaning. This term often describes fruits in Paradise within easy reach, symbolizing abundance and accessible blessings.",
  "1625": "دَاوُدُ refers to Prophet David (ﷺ), a revered prophet and king known for his piety, wisdom, and leadership. His name means \"beloved\" in Hebrew, reflecting his status as a beloved servant of Allah (ﷻ). In the Qur'an, Allah (ﷻ) describes him as a devoted servant, endowed with wisdom and just judgment. He was granted the Psalms, kingship, strength, and the skill of making armor. Prophet David (ﷺ) is known for defeating the giant Goliath, his beautiful recitation of the Qur'an, and his fair and just rule.",
  "1626": "دَأَبَ and related words stem from the root د-أ-ب, and as the root verb, it means \"he labored continuously\" or \"he persisted.\" دَأَبَ reflects the concept of tireless effort and steadfast work, embodying the human capacity to endure challenges through consistent action. The root emphasizes themes of diligence and persistence, encouraging a disciplined approach to life that mirrors the unceasing labor observed in natural phenomena, such as the sun and moon.",
  "1627": "دَأْبٌ and related words stem from the root د-أ-ب, with the root verb دَأَبَ meaning \"he labored persistently\" or \"he continued tirelessly.\" دَأْبٌ refers to \"habit,\" \"custom,\" or \"persistent effort,\" emphasizing actions marked by regularity and perseverance. The root conveys themes of continuity and tireless exertion, reflecting the human capacity for sustained effort. دَأْبٌ highlights how consistent actions, whether noble or detrimental, shape outcomes and reflect the underlying values of one’s persistence. ",
  "1628": "دَحَا and related words stem from the root د-ح-و, and as the root verb, it means \"he spread or extended out\" or \"he leveled, smoothed, or flattened.\" The root revolves around spreading, leveling, casting, and clearing, conveying the idea of expansion and preparation. Just as something is spread or smoothed to make it suitable for use, this word reflects the act of making space, removing obstacles, or setting a foundation, emphasizing readiness and openness.",
  "1629": "دَخَلٌ and related words stem from the root د-خ-ل, with the root verb دَخَلَ meaning \"he entered.\" دَخَلٌ refers to \"deceit,\" \"dishonesty,\" or \"defect,\" focusing on subtle infiltration or corruption. The root revolves around entry, penetration, mixture, and involvement, conveying both physical entry and metaphorical engagement. Just as something that enters can blend unnoticed, this word reflects the idea of hidden flaws or deceitful interference, where corruption seeps in gradually, altering integrity and undermining trust.",
  "1630": "دَخَلَ and related words stem from the root د-خ-ل, and as the root verb, it means \"he entered,\" denoting the act of moving into a place or state. The root revolves around entry, penetration, mixture, and involvement, conveying both physical entry and metaphorical engagement. Just as entering a space signifies transition and inclusion, this word reflects becoming part of something, whether a location, condition, or circumstance, highlighting movement, integration, and interaction.",
  "1631": "دَرَاهِمُ and related words stem from the root د-ر-ه-م, referring to \"dirhams,\" units of silver currency historically used as a medium of exchange. The word signifies value, trade, and economic transactions, reflecting the role of dirhams in commerce and daily life. Just as currency facilitates exchange and movement of wealth, this term represents both material value and the broader system of trade and financial dealings that sustain economies.",
  "1632": "دَرَجَةٌ and related words stem from the root د-ر-ج, with the root verb دَرَجَ meaning \"he proceeded gradually\" or \"he ascended or advanced step by step.\" This root conveys structured advancement. دَرَجَةٌ refers to \"degree,\" \"rank,\" or \"level,\" emphasizing elevation within a system. Just as دَرَجَ describes steady progress, this word reflects how ranks or statuses are achieved gradually. The root revolves around progression, movement, and aging, reinforcing that rising in status, knowledge, or capability occurs step by step.",
  "1633": "دَرَسُوا and related words stem from the root د-ر-س, with the root verb دَرَسَ meaning \"he studied or learned\" or \"he examined through repetition.\" دَرَسُوا means \"they studied\" or \"they learned,\" emphasizing repeated engagement with knowledge. The root revolves around study, learning, repetition, and the fading of inscriptions or writings over time. Just as studying involves repeated review to reinforce knowledge, marks and writings exposed to time gradually wear away. This word reflects both the persistence of learning through repetition and the eventual erasure of what is left unpreserved, highlighting the contrast between intellectual retention and physical fading.",
  "1634": "دَرَكٌ and related words stem from the root د-ر-ك, with the root verb دَرَكَ meaning \"it reached or attained\" or \"it overtook or caught up with.\" The root revolves around reaching, comprehension, and consequences, conveying both physical arrival and intellectual realization. دَرَكٌ refers to \"the act of attaining, reaching, or overtaking,\" emphasizing the certainty of arrival at a destination or result. Just as something pursued is eventually caught, this word reflects the idea of inevitable attainment, whether in physical pursuit, understanding, or the full consequences of one's actions.",
  "1635": "دَرْكٌ and related words stem from the root د-ر-ك, with the root verb دَرَكَ meaning \"it reached or attained\" or \"it overtook or caught up with.\" The root revolves around reaching, comprehension, and consequences, conveying both physical arrival and intellectual realization. دَرْكٌ specifically refers to the \"lowest depth\" or \"level,\" describing the deepest level of Hell. The connection to the root lies in the idea of reaching an ultimate state, but in a downward progression. Just as something overtaken cannot escape its final destination, this word reflects an inescapable descent into punishment, marking the culmination of a degrading progression with severe consequences.",
  "1636": "دَسَّىٰ and related words stem from the root د-س-و, with the root verb دَسَّ meaning \"he concealed, hid, or buried\" or \"he inserted, placed, or put (something) secretly or stealthily.\" The root conveys the idea of hiding, suppressing, or deceitfully placing something out of view. دَسَّىٰ is the elongated form with intensification, meaning \"he deeply concealed, buried, or suppressed something intensely.\" Just as something hidden is removed from sight and awareness, this word reflects an act of deliberate suppression, whether of truth, emotions, or actions, emphasizing a deep and intentional covering, often with a sense of secrecy or denial.",
  "1637": "دَعَا and related words stem from the root د-ع-و, and as the root verb, it means \"he called or invited\" or \"he supplicated or prayed.\" The root revolves around calling, summoning, requesting, naming, and invoking, conveying the ideas of communication, appeal, and urging toward something. Just as a call seeks attention or a response, this word reflects an intentional effort to reach out—whether by inviting, requesting, or seeking assistance—emphasizing connection, engagement, and the act of directing words or appeals toward others.",
  "1638": "دَعٌّ and related words stem from the root د-ع-ع, with the root verb دَعَّ meaning \"he pushed back forcefully\" or \"he repelled.\" دَعٌّ means \"repulsion\" or \"violent rejection,\" reflecting a deliberate and forceful act of pushing away. The root revolves around forceful actions, both physical (pushing, striking) and verbal (rebuking, scolding). Just as something repelled is driven away with strength, this word conveys an intense act of dismissal or expulsion, emphasizing a harsh and decisive rejection.",
  "1639": "دَعْ and related words stem from the root و-د-ع, with the root verb وَدَعَ meaning \"he left,\" \"he abandoned,\" or \"he let alone.\" دَعْ means \"leave,\" \"let be,\" or \"dismiss,\" often conveying an action of intentional detachment or release. The root encompasses the idea of ceasing interaction or involvement, reflecting themes of separation or relinquishment. This connection emphasizes the deliberate act of leaving something undisturbed, symbolizing the ability to refrain, let go, or disengage when necessary.",
  "1640": "دَعْوَةٌ and related words stem from the root د-ع-و, with the root verb دَعَا meaning \"he called or invited\" or \"he supplicated or prayed.\" دَعْوَةٌ means \"supplication,\" \"call,\" or, in some contexts, \"claim,\" emphasizing the act of summoning or appealing for something. The root revolves around calling, summoning, requesting, naming, and invoking, conveying the ideas of communication and urging toward something. Just as a call is made to attract attention or seek a response, this word reflects an intentional appeal—whether in the form of prayer, invitation, or assertion—highlighting the active effort in seeking engagement or acknowledgment.",
  "1641": "دَفَعْتُمْ and related words stem from the root د-ف-ع, with the root verb دَفَعَ meaning \"he repelled or pushed away,\" \"he prevented or averted,\" or \"he paid, gave, or delivered money or an obligation.\" دَفَعْتُمْ means \"you repelled\" or \"you warded off,\" emphasizing pushing something away, whether physically or metaphorically. It also means \"you paid\" or \"you delivered,\" reflecting the act of transferring something, such as money or goods. The root conveys defense, prevention, resistance, and transfer. Just as repelling prevents harm, payment removes a burden, settles a claim, or fulfills an obligation, making it a way to avert consequences or secure peace.",
  "1642": "دَفْعٌ and related words stem from the root د-ف-ع, with the root verb دَفَعَ meaning \"he repelled or pushed away\" or \"he prevented or averted.\" دَفْعٌ means \"pushing\" or \"repelling,\" emphasizing the act of resisting or warding off something. The root conveys both physical movement (pushing, resisting) and figurative actions (defense, payment, or preventing harm). Just as pushing removes an obstacle, this word reflects efforts to avert harm, fulfill obligations, or resist negative forces, highlighting active prevention and protection.",
  "1643": "دَكٌّ and related words stem from the root د-ك-ك, with the root verb دَكَّ meaning \"he crushed\" or \"he leveled.\" دَكٌّ means \"crushing\" or \"leveling,\" emphasizing complete breakdown and destruction. The root revolves around crushing, flattening, and demolishing, conveying forceful destruction that reduces something to fragments or dust. Just as leveling removes all resistance, this word reflects overwhelming force that leaves nothing standing. It is used to describe the flattening of the earth and mountains, symbolizing the absolute and unimaginable power of Allah (ﷻ), demonstrating how nothing can withstand His will.",
  "1644": "دَكَّاءُ and related words stem from the root د-ك-ك, with the root verb دَكَّ meaning \"he crushed\" or \"he leveled.\" دَكَّاءُ means \"leveled to the ground\" or \"flattened,\" emphasizing complete destruction. The root revolves around crushing, flattening, and demolishing, conveying the overwhelming force that reduces something to dust. Just as crushing removes all form and resistance, this word reflects absolute devastation, leaving no trace of what once stood. It vividly illustrates utter desolation, highlighting the might of Allah (ﷻ) and His power to erase and reshape as He wills.",
  "1645": "دَكَّةٌ and related words stem from the root د-ك-ك, with the root verb دَكَّ meaning \"he crushed\" or \"he leveled.\" دَكَّةٌ refers to the act of \"crushing\" or \"leveling,\" emphasizing the transformation of something solid or elevated into a flattened state. The root conveys themes of breaking down, reducing to fragments, and rendering something uniform through forceful action. Just as crushing eliminates resistance, this word reflects the overwhelming power that reshapes or erases what once stood firm. It highlights the transitory nature of creation and the ultimate submission of all things to Allah (ﷻ), demonstrating His absolute authority over existence.",
  "1646": "دَلِيلٌ and related words stem from the root د-ل-ل, with the root verb دَلَّ meaning \"he indicated, pointed to, or showed\" or \"he guided or directed.\" دَلِيلٌ means \"guide\" or \"evidence,\" emphasizing something that leads to clarity or confirms a truth. The root revolves around guidance, direction, indication, and clarity, conveying both the act of leading toward something and making it unmistakably clear. Just as a guide provides direction and evidence confirms reality, this word reflects the role of showing the way, proving a point, or illuminating understanding.",
  "1647": "دَلَّ and related words stem from the root د-ل-ل, and as the root verb, it means \"he indicated, pointed to, or showed\" or \"he guided or directed.\" The root revolves around guidance, direction, indication, and clarity, emphasizing the act of making something known or leading toward it. Just as a sign or gesture provides direction, this word reflects the role of showing the way, revealing truth, or making something evident, highlighting both physical guidance and intellectual or spiritual illumination.",
  "1648": "دَلْوٌ and related words stem from the root د-ل-و, with the root verb دَلَا meaning \"he lowered, let down, or extended\" or \"he drew out, pulled up, or retrieved.\" دَلْوٌ means \"bucket,\" referring to a container used for drawing water from a well. The root revolves around lowering, extending, and retrieving, emphasizing the action of sending something down to extract or bring something up. Just as a bucket is lowered into a well to collect water, this word reflects the process of reaching down to obtain something of value, highlighting both the act of lowering and the purpose of retrieval.",
  "1649": "دَمٌ and related words stem from the root د-م-و, with the root verb دَمِىَ meaning \"it bled.\" دَمٌ refers to \"blood,\" the essential fluid that sustains life. The root conveys the idea of blood flowing from a wound, indicating physical harm or the natural process of bleeding. Just as blood flow is vital for life, its presence outside the body often signifies injury or sacrifice, highlighting the dual nature of blood as both a source of sustenance and a sign of vulnerability.",
  "1650": "دَمَّرَ and related words stem from the root د-م-ر, with the root verb دَمَرَ meaning \"it perished\" or \"he intruded without permission.\" دَمَّرَ, as the intensified form, means \"he utterly destroyed\" or \"he annihilated,\" signifying complete and deliberate obliteration. The intensified form builds on the root verb’s concept of perishing and intrusion, where destruction arrives unexpectedly and is unavoidable. The broader themes of erasure and overwhelming force highlight the thoroughness of this action, reflecting the severity of Allah’s (ﷻ) punishment for persistent wrongdoing and the inevitability of His justice.",
  "1651": "دَمْدَمَ and related words stem from the root د-م-د-م, and as the root verb, it means \"he destroyed or annihilated\" or \"he leveled to the ground.\" The word دَمْدَمَ emphasizes an intense, repetitive action, reflecting complete and deliberate annihilation. The repetition of the root letters conveys forcefulness and thoroughness, highlighting destruction that is not random but systematic and overwhelming. Broader meanings tied to the root include notions of crushing, subduing, or obliterating, often with a sense of finality and totality. The connection to the root lies in the depiction of destruction as a relentless, overpowering force, symbolizing ultimate judgment or decisive action that leaves no trace behind.",
  "1652": "دَمْعٌ and related words stem from the root د-م-ع, with the root verb دَمَعَ meaning \"his eyes shed tears.\" دَمْعٌ means \"tears.\" The connection lies in the physical act of tears flowing, directly reflecting the root's meaning. This term symbolizes deep emotions such as sorrow or compassion, highlighting the capacity for profound feelings.",
  "1653": "دَنَا and related words stem from the root د-ن-و, and as the root verb, it means \"he or it drew near\" or \"he approached.\" This verb emphasizes the action of moving closer, whether in a physical, relational, or spiritual sense. The root conveys themes of proximity, nearness, and connection, symbolizing both literal closeness and metaphorical approaches, such as drawing near to truth, guidance, or Allah’s (ﷻ) mercy. The connection is intrinsic, as the verb inherently represents the act of reducing distance or achieving intimacy. This highlights the dual dimensions of the root: physical nearness and spiritual closeness.",
  "1654": "دَهْرٌ and related words stem from the root د-ه-ر, with the root verb دَهَرَ meaning \"it befell.\" دَهْرٌ refers to \"time,\" \"age,\" or \"eternity,\" signifying an extended or indefinite period. The root revolves around the concept of time, encompassing eternity, long durations, and the passage of ages. Just as time unfolds continuously, this word reflects the unfolding of events and experiences that befall individuals. It also conveys ideas of fate and destiny, emphasizing the inevitable flow of time and its role in shaping circumstances.",
  "1655": "دَوَائِرُ and related words stem from the root د-و-ر, with the root verb دَارَ meaning \"he or it turned, revolved, or rotated.\" دَوَائِرُ is the plural of دَائِرَةٌ, meaning \"circles,\" \"calamities,\" or \"cycles of misfortune.\" The root conveys the idea of turning and revolving, emphasizing repetition and the return of events. Just as circles symbolize continuous motion without a fixed endpoint, this word reflects how misfortunes and hardships can come back around, highlighting the unpredictable and inevitable shifts in life’s circumstances.",
  "1656": "دَيَّارٌ and related words stem from the root د-و-ر, with the root verb دَارَ meaning \"he or it turned, revolved, or rotated.\" دَارٌ means \"house\" or \"dwelling,\" while دَيَّارٌ refers to an \"inhabitant\" or \"dweller.\" The root conveys the idea of turning, revolving, and repetition, reflecting the continuous cycle of human settlement and habitation. Just as movement and cycles define existence, this word highlights the natural human tendency to reside, establish homes, and sustain communities, emphasizing stability and the ongoing rhythm of life.",
  "1657": "دَيْنٌ and related words stem from the root دَيَن, with the root verb دَانَ meaning \"he obeyed\" or \"he borrowed.\" دَيْنٌ means \"debt\" or \"obligation,\" emphasizing a binding duty. The root revolves around obedience, judgment, and indebtedness, encompassing faith, legal rulings, and financial commitments. Just as debt creates an obligation to repay, this word reflects the structured nature of responsibilities, whether financial, moral, or religious, highlighting accountability and commitment.",
  "1658": "دُبُرٌ and related words stem from the root د-ب-ر, with the root verb دَبَرَ meaning \"it came after or followed\" or \"he turned his back or went away.\" The root revolves around sequence, positioning, and retreat, emphasizing what follows or is left behind. دُبُرٌ means \"the back,\" \"rear,\" or \"end,\" referring to the physical part of something that is opposite the front. The connection to the root highlights the idea of what is behind in both movement and structure, reinforcing the concept of turning away, being positioned at the rear, or what remains as the last part of something.",
  "1659": "دُحُورٌ and related words stem from the root د-ح-ر, with the root verb دَحَرَ meaning \"he drove away\" or \"he expelled.\" دُحُورٌ refers to \"expulsion\" or \"repulsion,\" emphasizing the act of forcefully driving something away. The root revolves around repulsion, expulsion, subjugation, and rejection, conveying the forceful removal or suppression of something, often with an element of defeat or humiliation. The connection highlights not just removal but also overpowering and casting away with force, reinforcing the idea of subjugation and rejection.",
  "1660": "دُخَانٌ and related words stem from the root د-خ-ن, with the root verb دَخَنَ meaning \"it (smoke) rose, spread, or became visible\" or \"it became smoky or unclear.\" The root revolves around smoke, cloudiness, impurity, and deceit. دُخَانٌ means \"smoke,\" directly reflecting the root’s focus on the emission of vapor or particles. Just as smoke rises and spreads, obscuring vision and creating an atmosphere of uncertainty, this word conveys the idea of concealment, lack of clarity, or an impure state, emphasizing both its physical and metaphorical implications.",
  "1661": "دُرِّيٌّ and related words stem from the root د-ر-ر, with the root verb دَرَّ meaning \"he was generous, bountiful, or abundant in giving,\" or \"it became plentiful, abundant, or full.\" This root conveys abundance, flowing, generosity, and preciousness. دُرِّيٌّ is derived from دُرٌّ (pearl) and signifies radiance, brilliance, or a shining quality. The connection lies in something gleaming and luminous, reflecting purity and value. Just as pearls emerge through refinement with natural brilliance, this word conveys clarity and continuous radiance, often likened to celestial light that dispels darkness, offering beauty and guidance.",
  "1662": "دُسُرٌ and related words stem from the root د-س-ر, with the root verb دَسَرَ meaning \"he drove in or fixed firmly\" or \"he pushed or forced (something into place).\" دُسُرٌ refers to \"pegs\" or \"nails,\" often used in ship construction. The root conveys strength, forceful insertion, and securing something in place. Just as pegs or nails hold structures together by being driven in with force, this word reflects stability and reinforcement, emphasizing the role of firmly fixing or fastening things to ensure strength and durability.",
  "1663": "دُعَاءٌ and related words stem from the root د-ع-و, with the root verb دَعَا meaning \"he called or invited\" or \"he supplicated or prayed.\" دُعَاءٌ means \"supplication\" or \"prayer,\" emphasizing an appeal for assistance or response. The root revolves around calling, summoning, requesting, naming, and invoking, conveying the ideas of communication and seeking. Just as a call reaches out for attention, this word reflects the act of earnestly requesting, whether in prayer, invocation, or seeking help, highlighting a direct and intentional appeal.",
  "1664": "دُكَّتْ and related words stem from the root د-ك-ك, with the root verb دَكَّ meaning \"he crushed\" or \"he leveled.\" دُكَّتْ is a passive form meaning \"it was crushed\" or \"it was leveled,\" emphasizing complete destruction or flattening. The root revolves around crushing, demolishing, and reducing something to dust. Just as forceful destruction leaves nothing standing, this word reflects a total transformation where what once stood firm is reduced to nothing. It is often used to describe the leveling of mountains or the earth, highlighting the immense power and control of Allah (ﷻ) over creation.",
  "1665": "دُلُوكٌ and related words stem from the root د-ل-ك, with the root verb دَلَكَ meaning \"he rubbed or massaged an object\" or \"he polished or smoothed.\" دُلُوكٌ refers to the \"decline\" or \"setting\" of the sun, describing its transition as it sinks below the horizon. The root revolves around rubbing, pressing, polishing, and removing by friction, conveying both physical action (massaging, scrubbing) and metaphorical refinement (smoothing over time). Just as rubbing gradually wears down or polishes a surface, this word reflects the steady motion of the sun’s descent, as if being drawn across the sky, emphasizing its gradual fading and transition.",
  "1666": "دُنْيَا and related words stem from the root د-ن-و, with the root verb دَنَا meaning \"he or it drew near\" or \"he approached.\" دُنْيَا means \"the world\" or \"this life,\" emphasizing its nearness and immediacy compared to the hereafter. The connection to the root lies in the proximity of this life in time and space, as well as its lower, temporary nature. This term highlights the contrast between the fleeting attraction of the present world and the enduring significance of the hereafter, urging a focus on higher priorities.",
  "1667": "دُهْنٌ and related words stem from the root د-ه-ن, with the root verb دَهَنَ meaning \"he anointed\" or \"he oiled.\" دُهْنٌ means \"oil\" or \"fat,\" directly referring to a substance that is oily or fatty. The root revolves around smoothness and enrichment, emphasizing oil’s role in nourishment and utility. Just as oil provides sustenance and enhances well-being, this word reflects the blessings of provision and natural resources, highlighting its essential role in sustaining life and offering physical benefit.",
  "1668": "دُولَةٌ and related words stem from the root د-و-ل, with the root verb دَالَ meaning \"he went round or revolved\" or \"he alternated or took turns.\" دُولَةٌ refers to \"a state,\" \"an empire,\" or \"wealth that circulates.\" The root revolves around turning, alternating, and changing states. The connection lies in circulation and change, reflecting how power, wealth, or fortune shifts between people over time. This term highlights the transient nature of worldly possessions and authority, emphasizing that dominance and wealth are temporary, constantly shifting as part of life's trials.",
  "1669": "The preposition and adverb دُونَ means \"without,\" \"apart from,\" \"other than,\" \"besides,\" or \"instead of.\" It conveys exclusion, distinction, proximity, or contrast, depending on context. دُونَ can indicate lower status, a barrier, or contrast between levels. In Qur'anic usage, it often highlights taking others \"besides\" Allah (ﷻ), emphasizing misplaced allegiance or prioritizing lesser things over what is higher. This term highlights misguided choices, the separation from truth, and the ultimate contrast between what is lesser and what is divine.",
  "1670": "دِرَاسَةٌ and related words stem from the root د-ر-س, with the root verb دَرَسَ meaning \"he studied or learned\" or \"he examined through repetition.\" دِرَاسَةٌ refers to \"study\" or \"learning,\" highlighting the active pursuit of knowledge. The root revolves around study, learning, repetition, and the fading of inscriptions or writings over time. Just as learning requires repeated effort to reinforce understanding, written records and marks exposed to time gradually wear away. This word reflects both the persistence of knowledge through continuous study and the gradual disappearance of what is not maintained, emphasizing the effort and repetition needed to attain and preserve understanding.",
  "1671": "دِفْءٌ and related words stem from the root د-ف-أ, with the root verb دَفِئَ meaning \"he became warm,\" or \"he felt a sense of warmth.\" دِفْءٌ means \"warmth.\" The root conveys the idea of feeling warmth and security. The connection is direct, referring to the state or sensation of warmth, which is comforting and protective, reflecting the root's meaning.",
  "1672": "دِهَاقٌ and related words stem from the root د-ه-ق, with the root verb دَهَقَ meaning \"it was full or abundant.\" دِهَاقٌ means \"full to the brim,\" emphasizing complete fullness. The root revolves around filling or being full, especially in the context of liquids and containers, conveying abundance and completeness. Just as a vessel filled to the top leaves no emptiness, this word reflects the concept of overflowing generosity and provision. It describes generously filled cups in Paradise, symbolizing Allah’s (ﷻ) kindness and the limitless nature of His blessings.",
  "1673": "دِهَانٌ and related words stem from the root د-ه-ن, with the root verb دَهَنَ meaning \"he anointed\" or \"he oiled.\" دِهَانٌ refers to \"oil\" or substances with a smooth, shiny, or fluid quality. The root revolves around smoothness, enrichment, sheen, and pliability, emphasizing the reflective and malleable nature of oil. Just as oil spreads easily and enhances luster, this word conveys fluidity and transformation, often evoking shimmering or molten-like imagery that reflects movement, adaptability, and dynamic change.",
  "1674": "دِينٌ and related words stem from the root د-ي-ن, with the root verb دَانَ meaning \"he obeyed\" or \"he borrowed.\" دِينٌ means \"religion,\" \"judgment,\" or \"way of life,\" reflecting a system of beliefs and practices to which one is bound. The root revolves around obedience, judgment, and indebtedness, encompassing faith, legal rulings, and financial obligations. The connection lies in submission and accountability, as religion entails a commitment to Allah’s (ﷻ) commands, just as a debtor is bound to repayment. This highlights how faith is not just belief but a responsibility, guiding one’s actions and shaping a person’s way of life toward the most honorable, dignified, and morally upright way of living.",
  "1675": "دِينَارٌ and related words stem from the root د-ن-ر, with the root verb دَنَّرَ meaning \"it (a man's face) glistened,\" emphasizing brightness and luster. دِينَارٌ refers to a gold coin, a term borrowed from the Persian phrase دِينْ آرْ, meaning \"the law brought it [into circulation].\" The connection lies in the shining quality of gold, aligning with the root’s meaning of radiance. Just as glistening things attract admiration, this word reflects how gold captivates people, symbolizing wealth, status, and desire. The root conveys not only physical brilliance but also the joy and allure of valuable possessions. Its rarity and lasting worth have also made it a standard of value and a medium of exchange.",
  "1676": "دِيَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-د-ي, with the root verb وَدَى meaning \"it flowed\" or \"he perished.\" دِيَةٌ refers to \"blood money,\" compensation given for loss of life. The root conveys the idea of flowing, such as the flow of blood, or perishing, linking the concept of دِيَةٌ to the life lost and the recompense offered as a means of restoring balance or addressing the consequence of the act. This connection highlights the gravity of life and the act of making amends for its loss, reflecting notions of justice and reparation.",
  "1677": "ذا is used to indicate \"the one\" or \"the one with,\" particularly in phrases like ذا المال (\"the one with wealth\"). It signifies possession or association with a specific quality or attribute. While ذا can function as a standalone demonstrative, it is often used to specify or emphasize an individual or entity that possesses particular traits or characteristics. It serves as an important tool for expressing ownership, association, or qualities, making it versatile in various contexts.",
  "1678": "ذَائِقَةٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-و-ق, with the root verb ذَاقَ meaning \"he tasted.\" ذَائِقَةٌ means \"tasting,\" \"sense of taste,\" or \"one who tastes.\" The term embodies the act or faculty of tasting, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on experiencing flavor or sensation. It can symbolize the experience of life or death, as in the Qur'anic phrase \"every soul shall taste death,\" highlighting the inevitability of certain experiences and the importance of awareness.",
  "1679": "ذَائِقُوا and related words stem from the root ذ-و-ق, with the root verb ذَاقَ meaning \"he tasted.\" ذَائِقُوا means \"those who taste\" or \"tasters.\" The term refers to individuals experiencing something firsthand, directly connecting to the root's emphasis on tasting or experiencing. This concept often alludes to the inevitability of certain experiences, such as death or the consequences of actions, reminding individuals of shared destinies and the importance of preparedness.",
  "1680": "الذَّارِيَاتُ and related words stem from the root ذ-ر-و, with the root verb ذَرَا meaning \"he scattered\" or \"he winnowed.\" الذَّارِيَاتُ means \"those that scatter,\" referring to winds that disperse dust or seeds. The connection lies in the act of dispersal, reflecting the root’s emphasis on scattering and spreading. It symbolizes the forces of nature that distribute elements across the earth, reminding us of Allah’s (ﷻ) power in controlling and orchestrating the natural world.",
  "1681": "ذَاقُوا and related words stem from the root ذ-و-ق, with the root verb ذَاقَ meaning \"he tasted.\" ذَاقُوا means \"they tasted.\" The term indicates that a group has experienced something, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on tasting or experiencing. It often conveys the idea that people have undergone certain events or consequences, emphasizing the collective experience and the lessons that can be drawn from it.",
  "1682": "ذَاكِرِينَ and related words stem from the root ذ-ك-ر, with the root verb ذَكَرَ meaning \"he remembered\" or \"he mentioned.\" ذَاكِرِينَ means \"ones who remember\" or \"remembering,\" describing someone engaged in the act of remembrance. The connection emphasizes ongoing mindfulness and recollection, reflecting the root's focus on memory and mention. It highlights the virtue of constantly remembering Allah (ﷻ) and His guidance, fostering a state of spiritual awareness.",
  "1683": "ذَاكِرَاتِ stems from the root ذ-ك-ر, with the root verb ذَكَرَ meaning \"he remembered\" or \"he mentioned.\" ذَاكِرَاتِ means \"women who remember\" or \"women who mention,\" highlighting active mindfulness and acknowledgment. The term emphasizes the importance of remembrance, particularly of Allah (ﷻ), reflecting devotion and spiritual awareness.",
  "1684": "ذاهِبٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ه-ب, with the root verb ذَهَبَ meaning \"he went\" or \"he departed.\" ذاهِبٌ means \"going,\" \"departing,\" or \"one who goes.\" The connection is direct, signifying someone in the act of leaving or moving away, reflecting the root's emphasis on movement or departure. This term can symbolize transience or the impermanence of worldly things, reminding one of the ever-changing nature of life.",
  "1685": "ذَرَأَ and related words stem from the root ذ-ر-أ, with the root verb meaning \"he created,\" \"he brought into being,\" or \"he multiplied.\" ذَرَأَ specifically means \"he created\" or \"he propagated,\" often referring to Allah’s (ﷻ) act of creation. The connection lies in the emergence and multiplication of life, emphasizing the root’s focus on bringing forth and proliferating. This term highlights the divine power behind creation and the abundance of life as a manifestation of Allah’s (ﷻ) majesty.",
  "1686": "ذَرَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ر-ر, with the root verb ذَرَّ meaning \"he scattered\" or \"he spread.\" ذَرَّةٌ means \"particle,\" \"speck,\" or \"atom,\" referring to the smallest possible unit or a minute amount. The connection lies in the idea of scattering into tiny particles, reflecting the root's emphasis on dispersion and minuteness. It highlights the notion that even the smallest deeds are known to Allah (ﷻ) and will be accounted for, emphasizing meticulous justice.",
  "1687": "ذَرْعٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ر-ع, with the root verb ذَرَعَ meaning \"he measured,\" \"he spanned,\" or \"he extended.\" ذَرْعٌ means \"measure,\" \"capacity,\" or \"extent,\" referring to the length or capability of something. The connection lies in the act of measuring or extending, reflecting the root's emphasis on assessing size or capacity.",
  "1688": "ذَرْوٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ر-و, with the root verb ذَرَا meaning \"he scattered\" or \"he winnowed.\" ذَرْوٌ means \"scattering\" or \"dispersal,\" referring to the act of spreading or separating particles, such as grains from chaff. The connection emphasizes the process of separation and distribution, reflecting the root's focus on scattering.",
  "1689": "ذَكَرٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ك-ر, with the root verb ذَكَرَ meaning \"he remembered\" or \"he mentioned.\" ذَكَرٌ means \"male,\" referring to the masculine gender. The connection to the root lies in the historical emphasis on remembrance and mention of male lineage, which often carried implications for inheritance, family continuity, and familial identity. This association reflects the societal focus on the role of male descendants in preserving familial and cultural legacy.",
  "1690": "ذَكَرَ and related words stem from the root ذ-ك-ر, and as the root verb, it means \"he remembered\" or \"he mentioned.\" It indicates the action of recalling or mentioning something or someone. The connection lies in bringing to mind or articulating thoughts, reflecting the root's emphasis on memory and speech. It highlights the importance of remembrance in worship and communication, highlighting the act of mentioning Allah's (ﷻ) names and attributes as a form of devotion.",
  "1691": "ذَكَّىٰ and related words stem from the root ذ-ك-و, with the root verb ذَكَا meaning \"he burned brightly\" or \"he was intelligent.\" ذَكَّىٰ means \"he slaughtered properly,\" referring to the act of ritual slaughter in a prescribed manner. The connection lies in the concepts of purification and making something lawful, reflecting the root's emphasis on purity and brightness.",
  "1692": "ذَلُولٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ل-ل, with the root verb ذَلَّ meaning \"he was lowly, humbled, or became submissive.\" ذَلُولٌ means \"tamed,\" \"tractable,\" or \"submissive,\" often used to describe an animal that is easily guided or controlled. The connection lies in the root's emphasis on being subdued or made easy, reflecting the state of being compliant or yielding. This term highlights the virtues of meekness and the ease that comes with openness to guidance, both literally and metaphorically",
  "1693": "ذَنْبٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ن-ب, with the root verb ذَنَبَ meaning \"he followed.\" ذَنْبٌ literally means \"tail\" but metaphorically refers to \"sin\" or \"offense,\" as sins are seen to follow a person like a tail follows an animal. The connection lies in the idea that one's misdeeds trail behind them, leading to consequences that are inescapable. This term emphasizes personal accountability, reminding individuals that their actions have lasting effects that accompany them, reinforcing the importance of seeking forgiveness.",
  "1694": "ذَنُوبٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ن-ب, with the root verb ذَنَبَ meaning \"he followed.\" ذَنُوبٌ can mean \"a large bucket\" used for drawing water, symbolizing a significant portion or measure, or it can be the plural of ذَنْبٌ meaning \"sins.\" The connection lies in the concept of a measure that follows one's actions, much like sins that trail behind a person or the abundant water drawn from a well. This term highlights that one's deeds, whether good or bad, accumulate and have consequential outcomes, emphasizing the importance of mindful actions.",
  "1695": "ذَهابٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ه-ب, with the root verb ذَهَبَ meaning \"he went\" or \"he departed.\" ذَهابٌ means \"going,\" \"departure,\" or \"leaving.\" The term encapsulates the concept of movement away from a place or state, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on going. It can symbolize the passage of time or the fleeting nature of life and experiences, highlighting the importance of appreciating the present.",
  "1696": "ذَهَبٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ه-ب, with the root verb ذَهَبَ meaning \"he went\" or \"he departed.\" ذَهَبٌ means \"gold,\" and the connection lies in the notion that gold is transient or easily goes away, perhaps due to its high value and the ease with which it is spent or lost. This reflects the root's emphasis on going or departing, symbolizing the fleeting nature of wealth and material possessions. It serves as a reminder of the impermanence of worldly riches and the importance of focusing on lasting values.",
  "1697": "ذَهَبَ and related words stem from the root ذ-ه-ب, meaning \"he went\" or \"he departed.\" This root verb establishes the foundational meaning of movement away from a place or state. It encapsulates the concept of transience and change inherent in life, emphasizing the continuous flow and the inevitability of departure. The simplicity of this verb highlights the fundamental human experiences of moving on and the passage of time.",
  "1698": "ذُبَابٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ب-ب, with the root verb ذَبَّ meaning \"he repelled,\" \"he warded off,\" or \"he defended.\" ذُبَابٌ refers to \"a fly.\" The connection lies in the act of constantly warding off flies due to their persistent buzzing and annoyance, reflecting the root's emphasis on repelling or driving away. This highlights the fly's nuisance nature, prompting continuous efforts to defend against its disturbance.",
  "1699": "ذُبِحَ and related words stem from the root ذ-ب-ح, with the root verb ذَبَحَ meaning \"he slaughtered\" or \"he sacrificed.\" ذُبِحَ is a passive form meaning \"he was slaughtered\" or \"it was sacrificed.\" The connection emphasizes the act of slaughtering or sacrificing, reflecting the root's focus on offering or killing in a ritualistic manner. It highlights themes of submission and obedience.",
  "1700": "ذُرِّيَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ر-ر, with the root verb ذَرَّ meaning \"he scattered\" or \"he spread.\" ذُرِّيَّةٌ means \"offspring,\" \"progeny,\" or \"descendants,\" representing one's children and future generations. The connection lies in the concept of scattering seed, reflecting the root's emphasis on dispersion leading to growth and multiplication. It highlights the continuity of life through successive generations and the importance of legacy and lineage.",
  "1701": "ذُكِّرَ and related words stem from the root ذ-ك-ر, with the root verb ذَكَرَ meaning \"he remembered\" or \"he mentioned,\" and the verb ذَكَّرَ meaning \"he reminded\" or \"he admonished.\" ذُكِّرَ is a passive form meaning \"he was reminded,\" indicating that someone caused him to remember. The connection emphasizes the reception of a reminder, reflecting the root's focus on memory and mention. It highlights the importance of being receptive to reminders and guidance, which can lead to reflection and positive change.",
  "1702": "ذُلُلٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ل-ل, with the root verb ذَلَّ meaning \"he was lowly, humbled, or became submissive.\" ذُلُلٌ is the plural form of ذَلُول, meaning \"tamed ones\" or \"tractable ones.\" This term refers to multiple entities that are submissive or easy to manage, directly connecting to the root's concept of being subdued or made easy. It emphasizes the collective nature of submission or tractability, perhaps in the context of a group receptive to guidance or instruction",
  "1703": "ذُلٌّ and related words stem from the root ذ-ل-ل, with the verb ذَلَّ meaning \"he was lowly, humbled, or submissive.\" ذُلٌّ means \"humiliation,\" \"abasement,\" or \"lowliness,\" reflecting the root's emphasis on humility and submission. The name ٱلْمُذِلُّ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect attributes, means \"The Humiliator\" or \"The One Who Disgraces,\" highlighting His power to humble the arrogant and unjust. This name signifies divine justice, reminding us that pride leads to disgrace and urging us to embrace humility and submission to Allah (ﷻ).",
  "1704": "ذُو means \"possessor of,\" \"owner of,\" or \"having.\" In the Qur'an, ذُو is frequently used to describe attributes, possessions, or qualities associated with a subject, as seen in phrases like ذُو الْعَرْشِ الْمَجِيدُ (\"Owner of the Glorious Throne\"). It emphasizes possession, highlighting a particular trait or quality that defines the subject. ذُو can be used for both tangible and intangible qualities, indicating physical ownership, authority, or inherent characteristics, and is often used to signify the greatness or majesty of Allah (ﷻ), such as ذُو الْقُوَّةِ (\"Possessor of Power\").",
  "1705": "ذِئْبٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-أ-ب, with the root verb ذَأَبَ meaning \"he frightened him (as does a wolf),\" \"he despised him,\" or \"he drove him away.\" ذِئْبٌ means \"a wolf,\" directly reflecting the root’s meanings of fear, hostility, and expulsion. Just as a wolf instills fear and drives away prey, this word conveys themes of aggression, isolation, and relentless pursuit, emphasizing the wolf’s nature as both a feared predator and a symbol of cunning and ruthlessness.",
  "1706": "ذِبْحٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ب-ح, with the root verb ذَبَحَ meaning \"he slaughtered\" or \"he sacrificed.\" ذِبْحٌ means \"slaughter\" or \"sacrifice,\" referring to the act of killing an animal in a prescribed manner. The connection lies in the ritualistic and purposeful nature of the act, reflecting obedience, devotion, or atonement. It highlights the significance of sacrifice in spiritual practices and the symbolism of offering something valuable to attain closeness to Allah (ﷻ).",
  "1707": "ذِرَاعٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ر-ع, with the root verb ذَرَعَ meaning \"he measured\" or \"he extended.\" ذِرَاعٌ means \"arm\" or \"cubit,\" representing both a limb and a unit of measurement based on the length of the forearm. The connection lies in the use of the arm as a measure of length, reflecting the root's emphasis on extension and measurement.",
  "1708": "ذِكْرٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ك-ر, with the root verb ذَكَرَ meaning \"he remembered\" or \"he mentioned.\" ذِكْرٌ means \"remembrance,\" \"mention,\" or \"recollection,\" referring to the act or state of remembering. The connection lies in the centrality of memory and mention in maintaining awareness and connection.",
  "1709": "ذِكْرَىٰ and related words stem from the root ذ-ك-ر, with the root verb ذَكَرَ meaning \"he remembered\" or \"he mentioned.\" ذِكْرَىٰ means \"remembrance\" or \"reminder,\" often signifying a significant memory or commemoration. The connection emphasizes the act of recalling important events or lessons, reflecting the root's focus on memory and mention. It highlights the role of significant reminders in shaping beliefs and actions, serving as milestones in one's spiritual journey.",
  "1710": "ذِلَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ل-ل, with the root verb ذَلَّ meaning \"he was lowly, humbled, or became submissive.\" ذِلَّةٌ means \"humiliation,\" \"abasement,\" or \"lowliness.\" It denotes the state of being humiliated or in disgrace, reinforcing the root's focus on humility and subjugation.",
  "1711": "ذِمَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-م-م, with the root verb ذَمَّ meaning \"he blamed\" or \"he censured.\" ذِمَّةٌ means \"covenant,\" \"protection,\" \"obligation,\" or \"trust,\" referring to agreements or responsibilities that must be upheld. The root's connection to blame highlights the seriousness of violating such covenants, as breaking them leads to censure and dishonor. This term highlights mutual responsibility, trust, and accountability in social and moral dealings. In an Islamic context, ذِمَّةٌ also refers to the protection and rights granted to non-Muslims under Muslim governance, emphasizing the values of trust, justice, and the sanctity of upholding agreements.",
  "1712": "رَابِطُوا and related words stem from the root ر-ب-ط, with the root verb رَبَطَ meaning \"he tied\" or \"he bound.\" رَابِطُوا means \"stand firm,\" \"hold fast,\" or \"be steadfast.\" The connection lies in the act of binding or tying, symbolizing firmness and stability, reflecting the root's emphasis on fastening. This term encourages perseverance and resilience, especially in the face of adversity, highlighting the importance of unity and steadfastness in maintaining strength.",
  "1713": "رابِيٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ب-و, with the root verb رَبَا meaning \"it increased\" or \"it grew.\" رابِيٌ means \"growing\" or \"increasing.\" The connection lies in the continuous process of growth or elevation, embodying the root's focus on natural increase. This term captures the essence of flourishing and development, whether in nature, wealth, or personal growth.",
  "1714": "رابِيَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ب-و, with the root verb رَبَا meaning \"it increased\" or \"it grew.\" رابِيَةٌ means \"a hill\" or \"an elevated place.\" The connection lies in the concept of rising or elevation, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on growth. This term symbolizes prominence and elevation, both physically in landscapes and metaphorically in status or virtue.",
  "1715": "راجِعٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-ع, with the root verb رَجَعَ meaning \"he returned\" or \"he went back.\" راجِعٌ means \"returning\" or \"one who returns.\" The connection is direct, embodying the action of returning, reflecting the root's emphasis on reversal or going back. This term highlights themes of repentance, reflection, and the cyclical nature of life, emphasizing the importance of returning to one's origin or correcting one's path.",
  "1716": "الرَّاجِفَةُ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-ف, with the verb رَجَفَ meaning \"to shake,\" \"to convulse,\" or \"to agitate.\" الرَّاجِفَةُ means \"the quaking one\" or \"the shaker,\" referring to a catastrophic event or upheaval. The root emphasizes intense commotion and upheaval, often tied to divine intervention or cosmic disruption. Specifically, الرَّاجِفَةُ refers to the first blast of the horn on the Day of Resurrection, marking the initiation of the final events and profound transformation of existence.",
  "1717": "الرَّاحِمِينَ and related words stem from the root ر-ح-م, with the root verb رَحِمَ meaning \"he showed mercy\" or \"he had compassion.\" الرَّاحِمِينَ means \"those who show mercy\" or \"merciful.\" The connection lies in actively embodying the root’s essence of compassion, extending kindness and care to others. This term highlights the importance of mercy as a defining trait in human interactions, fostering love and understanding in personal and communal relationships.",
  "1718": "رَادِفَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-د-ف, with the root verb رَدِفَ meaning \"he followed closely\" or \"he came after.\" رَادِفَةٌ means \"the follower\" or \"that which follows.\" The connection lies in the idea of something coming immediately after another, reflecting the root's essence of following closely. In the Qur'anic context, it may refer to the impending event that follows as a consequence, emphasizing the certainty and sequence of occurrences.",
  "1719": "رادٌّ and related words stem from the root ر-د-د, with the root verb رَدَّ meaning \"he returned,\" \"he repelled,\" or \"he rejected.\" رادٌّ means \"one who returns\" or \"one who repels.\" The connection lies in the role of someone who causes something to return or repels it, reflecting the root's essence of returning or rejecting. It emphasizes the action of sending back or refusing, highlighting agency in the process of return.",
  "1720": "رَدٌّ and related words stem from the root ر-د-د, with the root verb رَدَّ meaning \"he returned,\" \"he repelled,\" or \"he rejected.\" رَدٌّ means \"return,\" \"repulsion,\" or \"rejection.\" The connection emphasizes the act or process of returning something to its original place or rejecting it. It reflects the root's essence of sending back or refusing, highlighting the dynamics of acceptance and rejection in interactions.",
  "1721": "رازِقٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ز-ق, with the root verb رَزَقَ meaning \"he provided sustenance\" or \"he bestowed provisions.\" رازِقٌ means \"provider\" or \"sustainer.\" The connection lies in describing one who grants sustenance, reflecting the root's essence of providing. In Islamic theology, it is often attributed to Allah (ﷻ) as \"The Provider,\" emphasizing His role in sustaining all creation.",
  "1722": "راسِخٌ and related words stem from the root ر-س-خ, with the root verb رَسَخَ meaning \"he was firm,\" \"he was rooted,\" or \"he was steadfast.\" راسِخٌ means \"firm,\" \"deep-rooted,\" or \"steadfast.\" The connection reflects stability and firmness, embodying the root's essence of being firmly established. In the Qur'an, it may refer to those firmly grounded in knowledge, highlighting the importance of solid understanding and unwavering faith.",
  "1723": "رَاشِدٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ش-د, with the root verb رَشَدَ meaning \"he was rightly guided\" or \"he proceeded correctly.\" رَاشِدٌ means \"rightly guided,\" \"mature,\" or \"possessing sound judgment.\" The connection lies in embodying guidance, wisdom, and correctness in action and thought, reflecting the root's emphasis on proper direction and enlightenment. It highlights the importance of following the right path and making wise decisions in accordance with Allah's (ﷻ) guidance.",
  "1724": "رَاضِيَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ض-و, with the root verb رَضِيَ meaning \"he was pleased\" or \"he was content.\" رَاضِيَةٌ means \"pleased\" or \"content,\" often used to describe a soul or individual who is satisfied. The connection lies in the state of inner peace and contentment, directly reflecting the root's focus on pleasure and acceptance. In the Qur'anic context, it describes souls that are content with Allah (ﷻ) and with whom He is pleased, highlighting a profound spiritual fulfillment.",
  "1725": "رَاعِي and related words stem from the root ر-ع-ي, with the root verb رَعَىٰ meaning \"he tended\" or \"he cared for.\" رَاعِي means \"shepherd\" or \"guardian.\" The connection lies in the role of tending to and caring for livestock, embodying the root's emphasis on guardianship and care. This term symbolizes leadership and responsibility, reflecting the duty to guide and protect those under one's care, often used metaphorically for leaders or caretakers.",
  "1726": "رَاعِنَا and related words stem from the root ر-ع-ي, with the root verb رَعَىٰ meaning \"he tended,\" \"he cared for,\" or \"he guarded.\" رَاعٍ means \"shepherd\" or \"guardian,\" emphasizing care and responsibility. In the context of رَاعِنَا, it means \"hear us,\" but at the time of the Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ), the Jewish community mockingly used it with a twist of their tongues as an insult in Hebrew to ridicule Islam. To avoid ambiguity and disrespect, believers were instructed to use انْظُرْنَا, meaning \"make us understand,\" ensuring clarity and maintaining respect in communication.",
  "1727": "رَاغِبٌ and related words stem from the root ر-غ-ب, with the root verb رَغِبَ meaning \"he desired\" or \"he wished for.\" رَاغِبٌ means \"one who desires\" or \"seeker.\" The connection lies in the active pursuit of something, embodying the root's emphasis on desire and inclination. This term reflects the motivation and intent behind actions, highlighting the importance of aspiration and purposeful seeking.",
  "1728": "رَافِعٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ف-ع, with the root verb رَفَعَ meaning \"he raised,\" \"he lifted,\" or \"he elevated.\" رَافِعٌ means \"one who raises\" or \"uplifter,\" embodying the root's emphasis on elevation. The name الرَّافِعُ refers to \"The Exalter\" or \"The One Who Elevates,\" signifying Allah’s (ﷻ) power to raise the ranks, status, or positions of His servants. The root conveys themes of empowerment, honor, and elevation, reminding us that true dignity and elevation come from Allah (ﷻ) alone, and to seek His favor in all matters.",
  "1729": "رَافِعَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ف-ع, with the root verb رَفَعَ meaning \"he raised\" or \"he lifted.\" رَافِعَةٌ means \"that which raises\" or \"elevator.\" The connection lies in the instrument or means by which something is elevated, embodying the root's emphasis on raising. In the Qur'anic context, it can refer to an event that elevates some and lowers others, highlighting the transformative nature of certain occurrences.",
  "1730": "رَاقٍ and related words stem from the root ر-ق-ي, with the root verb رَقِىَ meaning \"he ascended\" or \"he recited incantations.\" رَاقٍ means \"healer\" or \"one who recites incantations.\" The connection lies in the act of performing a ritual or recitation to heal or protect, directly relating to the root's meaning. In the Qur'anic phrase \"وَقِيلَ مَنْ رَاقٍ\" (\"And it is said, 'Who can heal him?'\"), it emphasizes the search for someone who can provide remedy or relief.",
  "1731": "رَاكِعٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ك-ع, with the root verb رَكَعَ meaning \"he bowed (in prayer).\" رَاكِعٌ means \"one who bows\" or \"bowing,\" emphasizing the act of bowing in worship. The connection lies in the physical act of bending in humility, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term highlights submission and devotion in a spiritual context, representing obedience to divine commands.",
  "1732": "رَانَ and related words stem from the root ر-ي-ن, with the root verb رَانَ meaning \"it covered\" or \"it overwhelmed.\" رَانَ means \"it settled heavily\" or \"it enveloped,\" often used metaphorically to describe how sin covers or seals the heart. The connection lies in the idea of something overwhelming and all-encompassing, as if it blocks or conceals. This reflects the root’s theme of dominance or suffocation, showing how sin can cloud one’s inner state, preventing clarity and hindering spiritual growth. It illustrates how wrong actions can build up and overpower, creating a barrier between the individual and higher understanding.",
  "1733": "رَاوَدُوا and related words stem from the root ر-و-د, with the root verb رَادَ meaning \"he sought\" or \"he went about in quest of.\" رَاوَدُوا means \"they enticed\" or \"they attempted to seduce.\" The connection lies in persistently seeking or coaxing someone, emphasizing a continuous effort to achieve a goal, often through subtlety or persuasion. This term reflects the root's focus on striving toward an objective, with the act of coaxing or enticing representing a more indirect and persistent form of pursuit. It highlights the effort and intention behind influencing or guiding someone toward a desired outcome.",
  "1734": "رَءُوفٌ and related words stem from the root ر-أ-ف, with the root verb رَأَفَ meaning \"he had compassion\" or \"he pitied.\" رَءُوفٌ means \"most compassionate\" or \"kind,\" embodying the highest degree of tender care and mercy. The name ٱلرَّءُوفُ, meaning \"The Most Compassionate\" or \"The All-Pitying,\" highlights Allah’s (ﷻ) boundless mercy and care for His creation, even in their weaknesses and faults. This reminds us to embody compassion and kindness in our dealings, reflecting Allah’s (ﷻ) attribute of deep and constant mercy.",
  "1735": "رَأَىٰ and related words stem from the root ر-أ-ي, with the root verb رَأَىٰ meaning \"he saw\" or \"he perceived.\" This root verb signifies the act of perceiving with the eyes, discerning with the mind, or comprehending a matter. It carries broader meanings of sight, observation, insight, and reflection, emphasizing awareness and understanding. The connection highlights the central role of perception—both physical and intellectual—in gaining clarity, forming judgments, and navigating human experience. This root highlights themes of observation, comprehension, and insight, reflecting the importance of clear vision and thoughtful understanding in grasping truths.",
  "1736": "رَأْسٌ and related words stem from the root ر-أ-س, meaning \"head\" or \"chief.\" The term رَأْسٌ signifies the uppermost or foremost part of something, whether literally as in the head of a body or metaphorically as a leader or principal figure. The connection lies in the notion of primacy and leadership, reflecting the root's emphasis on being at the forefront. This term underscores the importance of guidance and direction, as the head governs the body's actions.",
  "1737": "رَأْفَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-أ-ف, with the root verb رَأَفَ meaning \"he had compassion\" or \"he pitied.\" رَأْفَةٌ means \"compassion,\" \"pity,\" or \"mercy.\" The term embodies the quality of deep kindness and tender care, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on compassionate feelings. It highlights the moral virtue of empathy and the importance of showing mercy towards others, reinforcing the values of compassion in personal and social contexts.",
  "1738": "رَأْيٌ and related words stem from the root ر-أ-ي, with the root verb رَأَىٰ meaning \"he saw\" or \"he perceived.\" رَأْيٌ means \"opinion,\" \"view,\" or \"consideration,\" extending the concept of seeing to encompass mental perception, judgment, and contemplation. The root broadly relates to sight, insight, and discernment, emphasizing clarity and awareness in both physical and intellectual contexts. This term highlights the process of forming beliefs, decisions, or judgments through careful observation and thought, highlighting the importance of critical thinking, reflection, and discernment in shaping opinions and understanding truths.",
  "1739": "رَبَائِبُ and related words stem from the root ر-ب-ب, with the root verb رَبّ meaning \"he reared, fostered, brought up, fed, or nourished,\" or \"he put the affair into a right, or proper, state,\" or \"he possessed or had authority over.\" رَبَائِبُ (plural of رَبِيبَةٌ) means \"stepdaughters.\" The connection lies in the root’s emphasis on nurturing and care, reflecting the upbringing and moral responsibility extended to children through marriage. This term highlights the compassion, mercy, and familial bonds formed beyond biological ties, emphasizing the importance of care and responsibility in maintaining family unity.",
  "1740": "رَبَتْ and related words stem from the root ر-ب-و, with the root verb رَبَا meaning \"it increased\" or \"it grew.\" رَبَتْ means \"it swelled\" or \"it rose.\" The connection lies in the action of swelling or rising, reflecting the root's emphasis on natural growth. This term can describe phenomena like dough rising or land swelling after rainfall, highlighting the inherent capacity for increase within creation.",
  "1741": "رَبِحَتْ and related words stem from the root ر-ب-ح, with the root verb رَبِحَ meaning \"he gained\" or \"he profited.\" رَبِحَتْ means \"she gained\" or \"she profited.\" The connection lies in the attainment of gain or benefit, reflecting the root's emphasis on profit. This term can symbolize successful endeavors or the rewards of righteous actions, emphasizing the positive outcomes that come from wise choices and diligent efforts.",
  "1742": "رَبٌّ and related words stem from the root ر-ب-ب, with the root verb رَبّ meaning \"he reared, fostered, brought up, fed, or nourished,\" or \"he put the affair into a proper state\" or \"he possessed authority.\" رَبٌّ generally means \"master\" or one with authority. In reference to Allah (ﷻ), it means \"Lord,\" encompassing His absolute authority, perfect governance, and ability to nurture, sustain, and complete all affairs. This term includes all of Allah's (ﷻ) attributes and names, as He alone nurtures creation with mercy, wisdom, and care while maintaining supreme control and perfection. The root highlights رَبٌّ as the Sustainer and Governor of all existence with unmatched authority and order.",
  "1743": "رَبَّانِيِّينَ and related words stem from the root ر-ب-ب, with the root verb رَبّ meaning \"he reared, fostered, brought up, fed, or nourished,\" or \"he put the affair into a right, or proper, state,\" or \"he possessed or had authority over.\" رَبَّانِيِّينَ refers to \"learned scholars\" or \"those deeply devoted to Allah (ﷻ),\" describing individuals of profound knowledge and piety. The root’s themes of nurturing, authority, and proper upbringing highlight their role in teaching and guiding others through divine knowledge. This term highlights their devotion to Allah (ﷻ) and their leadership in cultivating faith, wisdom, and uprightness within their communities.",
  "1744": "رَبَّى and related words stem from the root ر-ب-و, with the root verb رَبَا meaning \"it increased\" or \"it grew.\" رَبَّى means \"he nurtured\" or \"he raised.\" The connection lies in facilitating growth and development in others, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on increase. This term embodies the act of nurturing, whether in raising children or cultivating virtues, highlighting the role of guidance and care in fostering growth.",
  "1745": "رَتْقٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ت-ق, with the root verb رَتَقَ meaning \"he sewed up\" or \"he joined together.\" رَتْقٌ means \"joining\" or \"mending.\" The connection lies in the act of uniting or repairing, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on bringing together. In the Qur'an, this term describes the initial state of the heavens and the earth before their separation, symbolizing the profound interconnectedness and unity of creation.",
  "1746": "رَجَعَ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-ع, with the root verb meaning \"he returned\" or \"he went back.\" The connection lies in the act of returning to a previous state or place, reflecting the root's emphasis on reversal. This term conveys themes of repentance and the natural cycles of departure and return, often highlighting the importance of reflection and the opportunity to amend one's actions.",
  "1747": "رَجَمَ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-م, and as the root verb, it means \"he stoned\" or \"he hurled stones.\" The connection lies in the act of casting stones as a form of punishment or expulsion, reflecting the root's emphasis on condemnation. This term conveys themes of judgment and the physical act of repelling wrongdoing, highlighting societal measures against transgressions.",
  "1748": "رَجُلٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-ل, with the root verb رَجَلَ meaning \"he walked on foot.\" رَجُلٌ means \"man.\" The connection lies in the traditional role of men as walkers or travelers on foot, reflecting the root's emphasis on movement. This term symbolizes activity, responsibility, and participation in societal affairs.",
  "1749": "رَجِلٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-ل, with the root verb رَجِلَ meaning \"he walked on foot\" or \"he was disheveled.\" رَجِلٌ means \"pedestrian\" or \"on foot.\" The connection lies in the act of moving by foot, reflecting the root's emphasis on walking. This term highlights simplicity and humility, emphasizing the basic means of movement without reliance on mounts or vehicles.",
  "1750": "رَجِيمٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-م, with the root verb رَجَمَ meaning \"he stoned\" or \"he cursed.\" رَجِيمٌ means \"accursed\" or \"expelled.\" The connection lies in being cast out or condemned, reflecting the root's emphasis on rejection. This term notably describes Satan as \"الشَّيْطَانُ الرَّجِيمُ\" (\"the accursed Satan\"), emphasizing his expulsion from divine mercy and the consequences of defiance.",
  "1751": "رَجٌّ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-ج, with the root verb رَجَّ meaning \"he shook\" or \"he jolted.\" رَجٌّ means \"shaking\" or \"tremor.\" The connection lies in the action of shaking or quaking, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on movement and disturbance. This term evokes imagery of powerful forces causing upheaval, highlighting themes of instability and the formidable power inherent in natural phenomena.",
  "1752": "رَجْعٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-ع, with the root verb رَجَعَ meaning \"he returned\" or \"he went back.\" رَجْعٌ means \"return\" or \"echo.\" The connection lies in the concept of returning or being sent back, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on reversal. This term can refer to the act of returning or the repetition of sound, symbolizing the cyclical patterns in nature and the concept of resurrection or revival.",
  "1753": "الرَّجْفَةُ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-ف, with the root verb رَجَفَ meaning \"it shook,\" \"it trembled,\" or \"it was in tumult.\" الرَّجْفَةُ means \"the tremor\" or \"the earthquake,\" highlighting a violent and significant seismic event. The root conveys agitation and disruption, symbolizing divine warnings or acts of judgment. الرَّجْفَةُ often denotes a monumental disturbance, reflecting both physical and metaphorical upheaval, serving as a sign of divine power and momentous change.",
  "1754": "رَجْمٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-م, with the root verb رَجَمَ meaning \"he stoned\" or \"he hurled stones.\" رَجْمٌ means \"stoning\" or \"act of stoning.\" The connection lies in the physical act of throwing stones as as in making guesses",
  "1755": "رَحُبَتْ and related words stem from the root ر-ح-ب, with the root verb رَحُبَ meaning \"it was spacious\" or \"it became vast.\" رَحُبَتْ means \"it was spacious.\" The connection lies in describing spaciousness or breadth, reflecting the root's emphasis on expansion. This term conveys openness and abundance, highlighting themes of hospitality and the capacity to accommodate.",
  "1756": "رَحِمَ and related words stem from the root ر-ح-م, and as the root verb, it means \"he showed mercy\" or \"he had compassion.\" The root conveys tenderness, nurturing, and profound care, reflecting the fundamental act of being merciful. رَحِمَ highlights the fostering of close, caring relationships, extending to familial and social bonds. It emphasizes mercy as an essential principle in human connections, encouraging mutual care and understanding as a cornerstone of harmonious relationships.",
  "1757": "رَحِيقٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ح-ق, with the root verb رَحَقَ meaning \"he drank deeply.\" رَحِيقٌ means \"pure wine\" or \"nectar.\" The connection lies in the idea of a pure, unadulterated drink, reflecting the root's emphasis on essence. This term symbolizes the finest sustenance, often describing the pure drinks of Paradise, highlighting themes of reward and divine bounty.",
  "1758": "الرَّحِيمُ and related words stem from the root ر-ح-م, with the root verb رَحِمَ meaning \"he showed mercy\" or \"he had compassion.\" The root conveys tenderness, care, and nurturing, often linked to the womb (رَحِم) as a symbol of profound connection and mercy. الرَّحِيمُ, one of Allah's (ﷻ) beautiful names, means \"The Most Compassionate\" and signifies Allah’s (ﷻ) specific and enduring mercy toward the believers. While الرَّحْمَـٰنُ reflects Allah’s (ﷻ) mercy encompassing all creation, الرَّحِيمُ emphasizes His intimate and continuous care for the faithful. This perfect name highlights Allah’s (ﷻ) nurturing compassion and inspires believers to embody kindness and mercy in their lives.",
  "1759": "رَحْلٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ح-ل, with the root verb رَحَلَ meaning \"he departed\" or \"he journeyed.\" رَحْلٌ means \"saddle\" or \"equipment.\" The connection lies in items associated with travel, reflecting the root's emphasis on journeying. This term denotes the tools necessary for a journey, highlighting themes of mobility and preparedness.",
  "1760": "رَحْمَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ح-م, with the root verb رَحِمَ meaning \"he showed mercy\" or \"he had compassion.\" رَحْمَةٌ means \"mercy\" or \"compassion,\" encapsulating the attribute of mercy as a guiding principle in human actions. The root emphasizes nurturing, kindness, and tenderness, making رَحْمَةٌ a reflection of the care and benevolence that should characterize interpersonal relationships. It highlights the transformative power of compassion in building understanding and alleviating suffering.",
  "1761": "الرَّحْمَـٰنُ and related words stem from the root ر-ح-م, with the root verb رَحِمَ meaning \"he showed mercy\" or \"he had compassion.\" الرَّحْمَـٰنُ, one of Allah's (ﷻ) beautiful names, means \"The Most Merciful,\" signifying the most profound and all-encompassing mercy that extends to all creation without distinction. The root conveys nurturing and boundless care, reflected in Allah’s (ﷻ) provision, forgiveness, and sustenance. This name serves as a reminder for believers to seek Allah’s mercy and emulate His compassion by showing kindness and forgiveness in their lives.",
  "1762": "رَدِفَ and related words stem from the root ر-د-ف and is the root verb meaning \"he followed closely\" or \"he came after.\" This verb embodies the action of following immediately behind or succeeding something. The connection reflects the root's fundamental concept of close succession or attachment, highlighting the inevitability of certain events or the closeness of relationships.",
  "1763": "رَدَّ and related words stem from the root ر-د-د and is the root verb meaning \"he returned,\" \"he repelled,\" or \"he rejected.\" This verb embodies the action of sending something back, refusing, or causing it to return to its origin. The connection lies in the root's fundamental concept of returning or rejecting, highlighting the importance of discernment and the consequences of acceptance or refusal in various contexts.",
  "1764": "رَدْمٌ and related words stem from the root ر-د-م, with the root verb رَدَمَ meaning \"he filled up,\" \"he dammed,\" or \"he blocked.\" رَدْمٌ means \"barrier,\" \"dam,\" or \"mound.\" The connection lies in the act of filling a gap or building a barrier, reflecting the root's essence of obstructing or fortifying. It symbolizes protection or separation, highlighting the importance of barriers in defense or containment.",
  "1765": "رَزَقَ and related words stem from the root ر-ز-ق and is the root verb meaning \"he provided sustenance\" or \"he bestowed provisions.\" This verb embodies the action of granting sustenance or livelihood to others. The connection reflects the root's fundamental concept of providing and sustaining life, highlighting the dependence of all creatures on the provisions granted by Allah (ﷻ).",
  "1766": "رَزَّاقٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ز-ق, with the verb رَزَقَ meaning \"he provided\" or \"he bestowed sustenance.\" رَزَّاقٌ is an intensive form meaning \"The Great Provider\" or \"The All-Provider,\" emphasizing abundant and continuous provision. The perfect name الرَّزَّاقُ reflects Allah’s (ﷻ) role as the ultimate source of all sustenance, ensuring every creation’s needs are met. The root conveys themes of provision and generosity, reminding us to trust in Allah’s (ﷻ) care, show gratitude for His blessings, and share with those in need.",
  "1767": "رَسُولٌ and related words stem from the root ر-س-ل, with the root verb رَسَلَ meaning \"he sent.\" رَسُولٌ means \"messenger.\" The connection lies in one who is sent with a message, embodying the root's essence of sending. In Islam, it refers to prophets sent by Allah (ﷻ) to guide humanity, emphasizing the importance of Allah's (ﷻ) guidance and communication.",
  "1768": "رَسٌّ and related words stem from the root ر-س-س, with the root verb رَسَّ meaning \"he dug,\" \"he sank,\" or \"he buried.\" رَسٌّ refers to \"a well\" or \"a pit,\" and in the Qur'an, it is associated with an ancient people—referred to as \"the dwellers of the Rass\"—who rejected their prophet. The connection lies in the root’s themes of sinking or burying, symbolizing both physical and metaphorical consequences. This imagery reflects the fate of those who deny divine guidance, emphasizing the ultimate outcomes of disbelief and rejection of the truth.",
  "1769": "رَشادٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ش-د, with the root verb رَشَدَ meaning \"he was rightly guided\" or \"he was sensible.\" رَشادٌ means \"guidance\" or \"right direction.\" The connection lies in the concept of being guided correctly, reflecting the root's essence of guidance and righteousness. It highlights the importance of seeking and following true guidance for success in life.",
  "1770": "رَشَدٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ش-د, with the root verb رَشَدَ meaning \"he was rightly guided\" or \"he was sensible.\" رَشَدٌ means \"right guidance,\" \"maturity,\" or \"sound judgment.\" The connection emphasizes the state of being rightly guided or possessing mature understanding, reflecting the root's essence of guidance and wisdom.",
  "1771": "رَشِيدٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ش-د, with the root verb رَشَدَ meaning \"he was rightly guided\" or \"he was sensible.\" رَشِيدٌ means \"rightly guided,\" \"wise,\" or \"mature.\" The connection reflects a person possessing wisdom and sound judgment. ٱلرَّشِيد refers to \"The Guide to the Right Path\" or \"The Wise,\" indicating Allah’s (ﷻ) role in guiding His servants to the path of wisdom, righteousness, and success. This name signifies that Allah (ﷻ) is the source of all correct guidance and wisdom, leading His creation toward what is best for them.",
  "1772": "رَصَدَ and related words stem from the root ر-ص-د, with the root verb رَصَدَ meaning \"he watched,\" \"he observed,\" \"he guarded,\" or \"he lay in wait.\" رَصَدَ means \"he watched\" or \"he lay in ambush.\" The connection is direct, as the word itself embodies the root's fundamental meanings of vigilant observation and readiness. It conveys the idea of someone deliberately positioning themselves to observe, guard, or ambush, reflecting the root's emphasis on strategic watchfulness.",
  "1773": "رَضِيَ and related words stem from the root ر-ض-و, with the root verb رَضِيَ meaning \"he was pleased\" or \"he was content.\" رَضِيَ means \"he was pleased\" or \"he approved.\" The connection is direct, as the word itself embodies the root's fundamental meaning of contentment and satisfaction. It conveys the state of being pleased with something or someone, reflecting acceptance and approval.",
  "1774": "رَضِيٌّ and related words stem from the root ر-ض-و, with the root verb رَضِيَ meaning \"he was pleased\" or \"he was content.\" رَضِيٌّ means \"well-pleasing\" or \"accepted.\" The connection lies in describing someone who is pleasing or acceptable, embodying the root's emphasis on contentment and approval. This term often refers to individuals who are pleasing to Allah (ﷻ), highlighting their righteousness and the divine approval they receive.",
  "1775": "رَطْبٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ط-ب, with the root verb رَطَبَ meaning \"it was fresh,\" \"it was moist,\" or \"it became ripe.\" رَطْبٌ means \"fresh dates\" or \"ripe fruit.\" The connection lies in the state of freshness and juiciness, embodying the root's emphasis on moistness and ripeness. This term reflects the delight and nourishment found in fresh fruits, symbolizing abundance and the blessings of provision.",
  "1776": "رَعَ and related words stem from the root ر-ع-ي, with the root verb رَعَىٰ meaning \"he tended\" or \"he cared for.\" رَعَ is a shortened form of رَعَى, meaning \"he tended\" or \"he pastured.\" The connection is direct, as it embodies the act of caring for and overseeing, reflecting the root's emphasis on guardianship and responsibility. This term highlights the role of providing care and guidance, whether in tending livestock or in broader contexts of stewardship.",
  "1777": "رَعْدٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ع-د, with the root verb رَعَدَ meaning \"it thundered\" or \"he trembled.\" رَعْدٌ means \"thunder.\" The connection lies in the powerful and awe-inspiring natural phenomenon that causes trembling, embodying the root's emphasis on shaking or trembling. This term reflects the might of natural forces and often symbolizes divine power and majesty, evoking a sense of reverence and humility.",
  "1778": "رَغَبَ and related words stem from the root ر-غ-ب, with the root verb رَغِبَ meaning \"he desired\" or \"he wished for.\" رَغَبَ means \"he desired\" or \"he inclined towards.\" The connection is direct, as it embodies the act of desiring or showing inclination, reflecting the root's emphasis on yearning and preference. This term highlights the human tendency to seek and prefer certain things, influencing choices and actions.",
  "1779": "رَغَدٌ and related words stem from the root ر-غ-د, with the root verb رَغَدَ meaning \"it was ample\" or \"it was plentiful.\" رَغَدٌ means \"abundance\" or \"ease of living.\" The connection lies in the state of plentiful provision and comfortable sustenance, embodying the root's emphasis on abundance and ease. This term reflects the blessings of ample resources and the comfort that comes with them, often symbolizing divine favor and generosity.",
  "1780": "رَفَثَ and related words stem from the root ر-ف-ث, with the root verb رَفَثَ meaning \"he spoke indecently\" or \"he used obscene language.\" It refers to both verbal and physical expressions of indecency, including intimate relations within marriage. The term often conveys the need for restraint, especially during sacred occasions, highlighting the importance of self-control and maintaining dignity in contexts requiring elevated moral conduct.",
  "1781": "رَفَعَ and related words stem from the root ر-ف-ع, with the root verb رَفَعَ meaning \"he raised\" or \"he lifted.\" رَفَعَ means \"he raised\" or \"he elevated.\" The connection is direct, embodying the act of lifting or elevating, reflecting the root's fundamental meaning. This term emphasizes the action of raising in various contexts, whether physical elevation or raising status.",
  "1782": "رَفِيعٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ف-ع, with the root verb رَفَعَ meaning \"he raised\" or \"he lifted.\" رَفِيعٌ means \"high,\" \"exalted,\" or \"lofty.\" The connection lies in the state of being elevated or high, embodying the root's emphasis on raising. This term often describes elevated status or rank, highlighting honor and nobility, and can refer to the exalted nature of Allah (ﷻ) or His attributes.",
  "1783": "رَفِيقٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ف-ق, with the root verb رَفَقَ meaning \"he was kind\" or \"he was gentle.\" رَفِيقٌ means \"companion\" or \"friend.\" The connection lies in the qualities of kindness and companionship, embodying the root's emphasis on gentleness. This term reflects the importance of friendly relations and the comfort found in gentle companionship, highlighting social bonds based on kindness.",
  "1784": "رَفْرَفٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ف-ف, which relates to \"spreading\" or \"fluttering.\" رَفْرَفٌ means \"spread-out canopy\" or \"a fluttering cloth.\" The connection lies in the imagery of something spreading or fluttering gently, embodying the root's emphasis on movement and expansion. In the Qur'anic context, it is used to describe luxurious furnishings in paradise, highlighting the beauty and comfort awaiting the righteous.",
  "1785": "رَقَبَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ق-ب, with the root verb رَقَبَ meaning \"he watched\" or \"he observed.\" رَقَبَةٌ means \"neck.\" The connection lies in the neck being a symbol of life and vulnerability, and in some contexts, it represents a person. The term embodies the root's emphasis on observation and oversight, as one might keep watch over someone by metaphorically holding their neck. In Islamic jurisprudence, freeing a \"رَقَبَةٌ\" refers to emancipating a slave, highlighting themes of liberation and mercy.",
  "1786": "رَقِيبٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ق-ب, with the root verb رَقَبَ meaning \"he watched,\" \"he observed,\" or \"he guarded.\" رَقِيبٌ means \"watcher\" or \"guardian,\" emphasizing vigilance and close observation. In a divine context, ٱلرَّقِيبُ refers to \"The Watchful\" or \"The Observer,\" highlighting Allah’s (ﷻ) constant and all-encompassing awareness. This reflects the root’s emphasis on careful oversight and protection, signifying that nothing escapes Allah’s (ﷻ) notice.",
  "1787": "رَقِيمٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ق-م, with the root verb رَقَمَ meaning \"he wrote\" or \"he inscribed.\" رَقِيمٌ refers to \"an inscription\" or \"a written tablet.\" The connection lies in the act of writing or inscribing, directly relating to the root's meaning. In the story of the People of the Cave, الرَّقِيمُ is associated with the inscription or tablet that bore their names or story, symbolizing the preservation of their account through writing.",
  "1788": "رَقٌّ and related words stem from the root ر-ق-ق, with the root verb رَقَّ meaning \"he was thin, fine, or delicate.\" رَقٌّ refers to \"parchment\" or \"fine paper,\" emphasizing its thin and delicate nature. The connection lies in the material's fineness and softness, directly relating to the root's meaning of thinness and delicacy. In the Qur'an, it symbolizes the recording of deeds or divine messages inscribed on delicate scrolls, highlighting the preciousness of the written word.",
  "1789": "رَكُوبٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ك-ب, with the root verb رَكِبَ meaning \"he rode\" or \"he mounted.\" رَكُوبٌ refers to \"riding\" or \"a mount,\" emphasizing the act of traveling by mounting an animal or vehicle. The connection lies in the action of getting onto something for transportation, directly relating to the root's meaning. It can also symbolize embarking on a journey or undertaking a path toward a goal.",
  "1790": "رَكِبَ and related words stem from the root ر-ك-ب, and as the root verb, it means \"he rode\" or \"he mounted.\" This verb denotes the action of climbing onto something for travel or transportation. The connection lies in the physical act of mounting, directly relating to the root's meaning. It can metaphorically represent undertaking a course of action or engaging in an endeavor.",
  "1791": "رَكَّبَ and related words stem from the root ر-ك-ب, with the root verb رَكِبَ meaning \"he rode\" or \"he mounted.\" رَكَّبَ means \"he assembled\" or \"he put together.\" The connection lies in bringing elements together, much like mounting parts onto each other, directly relating to the root's concept of joining or combining. This action can refer to assembling objects or composing complex structures or ideas.",
  "1792": "رَكْبٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ك-ب, with the root verb رَكِبَ meaning \"he rode\" or \"he mounted.\" رَكْبٌ refers to \"a caravan\" or \"a group of riders,\" emphasizing a collective traveling together. The connection lies in the group being mounted on animals or vehicles, directly relating to the root's meaning. Historically, a رَكْبٌ would be a convoy journeying across distances, symbolizing unity and shared purpose.",
  "1793": "رَمَادٌ and related words stem from the root ر-م-د, with the root verb رَمِدَ meaning \"it burned\" or \"it was reduced to ashes.\" رَمَادٌ refers to \"ashes,\" the residue left after something has been burned. The connection lies in the result of combustion, directly relating to the root's meaning. Metaphorically, it can symbolize destruction, impermanence, or the ephemeral nature of worldly things.",
  "1794": "رَمَضَانُ and related words stem from the root ر-م-ض, with the root verb رَمَضَ meaning \"it was intensely hot\" or \"it scorched.\" رَمَضَانُ refers to the Islamic month of fasting, \"Ramadan.\" The connection lies in the scorching heat, as Ramadan originally fell during the hottest time of the year. This root conveys the intensity and purification associated with the month, symbolizing burning away sins through fasting and devotion.",
  "1795": "رَمَىٰ and related words stem from the root ر-م-ي, and as the root verb, it means \"he threw\" or \"he cast.\" This verb denotes the action of projecting something through the air. It conveys the act of throwing or casting, directly relating to the root's meaning. In various contexts, it can symbolize accusation, confrontation, or initiating an action.",
  "1796": "رَمِيمٌ and related words stem from the root ر-م-م, with the root verb رَمَّ meaning \"he repaired\" or \"he restored.\" Paradoxically, رَمِيمٌ refers to \"decayed remains\" or \"rotten bones,\" emphasizing complete disintegration. The connection lies in the contrast between restoration and decay, directly relating to the root's meaning. In the Qur'an, it highlights Allah’s (ﷻ) power to resurrect decayed remains, emphasizing His ability to restore life from death.",
  "1797": "رَمْزٌ and related words stem from the root ر-م-ز, with the root verb رَمَزَ meaning \"he signaled\" or \"he gestured.\" رَمْزٌ refers to \"a sign,\" \"symbol,\" or \"gesture,\" emphasizing non-verbal communication. The connection lies in conveying meaning through indications rather than words, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term highlights the importance of subtlety and understanding beyond spoken language.",
  "1798": "رَهَبٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ه-ب, with the root verb رَهِبَ meaning \"he feared\" or \"he was in awe.\" رَهَبٌ refers to \"fear\" or \"awe,\" emphasizing a profound sense of reverence or apprehension. The connection lies in the emotional response of fear or respect, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term often denotes fear of Allah (ﷻ), highlighting the importance of reverence and consciousness of the divine in one's actions.",
  "1799": "رَهَقًا and related words stem from the root ر-ه-ق, with the root verb رَهِقَ meaning \"he overtook,\" \"he oppressed,\" or \"he approached with force.\" رَهَقًا means \"oppression,\" \"injustice,\" or \"being overwhelmed by something harmful.\" The connection lies in the root’s focus on forceful action or an overwhelming effect. The word suggests a state of being burdened or overtaken by negative forces, often reflecting the consequences of oppression or excessive burden. It emphasizes the impact of being consumed by something detrimental.",
  "1800": "رَهِينٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ه-ن, with the root verb رَهَنَ meaning \"he pledged\" or \"he mortgaged.\" رَهِينٌ refers to \"one who is pledged\" or \"bound,\" emphasizing being held as security or guarantee. The connection lies in the state of being obligated or confined due to a pledge, directly relating to the root's meaning. In the Qur'an, it can symbolize being accountable for one's deeds, metaphorically \"mortgaged\" by one's actions.",
  "1801": "رَهِينَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ه-ن, with the root verb رَهَنَ meaning \"he pledged\" or \"he mortgaged.\" رَهِينَةٌ refers to \"a pledge\" or \"security,\" an item or person held as collateral. The connection lies in the concept of being held in guarantee for a debt or obligation, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term highlights accountability and the seriousness of commitments.",
  "1802": "رَهْبٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ه-ب, with the root verb رَهِبَ meaning \"he feared\" or \"he was in awe.\" رَهْبٌ also refers to \"fear\" or \"awe,\" emphasizing a deep emotional response to something formidable. The connection lies in the feeling of apprehension or reverence, directly relating to the root's meaning. It underscores the significance of being mindful of that which inspires fear or respect.",
  "1803": "رَهْبَانِيَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ه-ب, with the root verb رَهِبَ meaning \"he feared\" or \"he was in awe.\" رَهْبَانِيَّةٌ refers to \"monasticism\" or \"asceticism,\" emphasizing a lifestyle dedicated to spiritual pursuits, often involving withdrawal from worldly affairs. The connection lies in the intense reverence and fear of God that leads one to adopt such practices, directly relating to the root's meaning. In the Qur'an, it discusses how monasticism was instituted by followers seeking closeness to Allah (ﷻ), though it was not prescribed.",
  "1804": "رَهْبَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ه-ب, with the root verb رَهِبَ meaning \"he feared\" or \"he was in awe.\" رَهْبَةٌ refers to \"fear\" or \"dread,\" emphasizing a profound sense of apprehension. The connection lies in the emotional state of fearing something significant, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term often conveys the appropriate fear of Allah (ﷻ), motivating ethical conduct and humility.",
  "1805": "رَهْطٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ه-ط, which refers to \"a group\" or \"band\" of people, typically numbering between three and ten. The connection lies in the idea of a small company bound together, possibly by kinship or common purpose. In the Qur'an, رَهْطٌ can refer to a confederate or a group involved in collective action, highlighting themes of unity or shared intent.",
  "1806": "رَهْوٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ه-و, which conveys the meaning of \"calmness\" or \"stillness.\" رَهْوٌ refers to \"tranquility\" or \"a calm state,\" emphasizing the absence of disturbance. The connection lies in the state of being undisturbed or serene, directly relating to the root's meaning. In classical Arabic, it can describe a calm sea or a still environment, symbolizing peace and quietude.",
  "1807": "رَواحٌ and related words stem from the root ر-و-ح, with the root verb رَاحَ meaning \"he departed\" or \"he went in the evening.\" رَواحٌ refers to \"evening departure\" or \"the time of going in the evening.\" The connection lies in the transition from the labor of the day to the restfulness of evening, embodying the root's emphasis on moving toward relaxation and respite.",
  "1808": "رَواسِيَ and related words stem from the root ر-س-و, with the root verb رَسَا meaning \"it was firm,\" \"it was fixed,\" or \"it was anchored.\" رَواسِيَ means \"firmly set mountains.\" The connection lies in mountains being established firmly in the earth, reflecting the root's essence of firmness and stability. It symbolizes the power and precision of Allah’s (ﷻ) creation, highlighting the mountains as stabilizers for the earth.",
  "1809": "رَوَاكِدُ and related words stem from the root ر-ك-د, with the root verb رَكَدَ meaning \"he was still\" or \"he was motionless.\" رَوَاكِدُ is the plural of رَاكِدَةٌ, meaning \"motionless\" or \"stagnant,\" often used to describe waters or winds that are still. The connection lies in the state of inactivity or lack of movement, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term emphasizes the absence of motion, symbolizing calmness or, alternatively, stagnation.",
  "1810": "رَوْحٌ and related words stem from the root ر-و-ح, with the root verb رَاحَ meaning \"he found rest\" or \"he was comforted.\" رَوْحٌ means \"relief,\" \"comfort,\" or \"mercy.\" The connection lies in the shift from hardship to ease, much like moving from exhaustion to rest. Just as the soul finds solace after struggle, رَوْحٌ embodies the soothing comfort that follows distress. It reflects divine mercy, offering peace and respite from life's burdens. This word evokes a shift from difficulty to renewal, reminding us of the comfort and calm that emerge when relief comes.",
  "1811": "رَوْضَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-و-ض, with the root verb رَاضَ meaning \"he trained\" or \"he cultivated.\" رَوْضَةٌ means \"meadow\" or \"garden.\" The connection lies in the process of cultivating and nurturing land to create a flourishing, fertile space. This reflects the root's focus on training, refining, and fostering growth, both in the physical world and metaphorically. The term emphasizes the beauty and vitality that arise from careful nurturing, symbolizing not just the growth of plants, but the nurturing of potential or character to bring about fruitful results.",
  "1812": "رَوْعٌ and related words stem from the root ر-و-ع, with the root verb رَاعَ meaning \"he frightened\" or \"he alarmed.\" رَوْعٌ means \"fear\" or \"terror.\" The connection lies in the intense emotion that arises from sudden fright or shock, directly linking to the root's focus on causing alarm or disturbance. This term captures the overwhelming sense of fear that shakes or unsettles, illustrating how sudden fear can affect a person deeply, disrupting their sense of calm and bringing about a heightened state of awareness or distress.",
  "1813": "رَيْبٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ي-ب, with the root verb رَابَ meaning \"he doubted\" or \"he suspected.\" رَيْبٌ means \"doubt,\" \"suspicion,\" or \"uncertainty.\" The connection lies in the emotional and mental state of being unsure or skeptical, directly reflecting the root’s concept of doubt. رَيْبٌ represents the feeling of uncertainty that arises when the truth is not clear, creating confusion and hesitation. It embodies the obstruction of judgment, where doubt undermines trust and clarity.",
  "1814": "رُءْيَا and related words stem from the root ر-أ-ي, with the root verb رَأَىٰ meaning \"he saw\" or \"he perceived.\" رُءْيَا means \"vision\" or \"dream,\" referring to sights or images perceived during sleep or through visionary experiences. The root encompasses themes of sight, perception, and insight, bridging the physical act of seeing with the mental or spiritual act of receiving visions. This term highlights the connection between the seen and the unseen, as dreams and visions often carry profound meanings or revelations that transcend ordinary perception, reflecting deeper insights or symbolic realities.",
  "1815": "The particle رُبَّمَا combines رُبَّ (\"perhaps\" or \"often\") and مَا (\"what\"), forming an adverb meaning \"perhaps.\" It indicates possibility or uncertainty regarding an event or outcome. In the Qur'an, رُبَّمَا is used to express potential situations or results, often carrying a sense of remoteness or doubt. It suggests outcomes that are less certain than those implied by لَعَلَّ or عَسَى, reflecting a lower degree of expectation or hope.",
  "1816": "رُباعٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ب-ع, with the root verb رَبَعَ meaning \"he became four\" or \"it became quadruple.\" رُباعٌ means \"in fours\" or \"fourfold.\" The connection lies in grouping or multiplying by four.",
  "1817": "رُبُعٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ب-ع, with the root verb رَبَعَ meaning \"he became four\" or \"it became quadruple.\" رُبُعٌ means \"a quarter\" or \"one-fourth.\"",
  "1818": "رُجُومٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-م, with the root verb رَجَمَ meaning \"he stoned\" or \"he hurled stones.\" رُجُومٌ means \"missiles\" or \"projectiles.\" The connection lies in multiple objects used for casting, reflecting the root's emphasis on repelling. In a celestial context, it refers to meteors used to drive away devils, symbolizing divine protection and the thwarting of evil forces.",
  "1819": "رُجَّتِ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-ج, with the root verb رَجَّ meaning \"he shook\" or \"he jolted.\" رُجَّتِ is a passive form meaning \"it was shaken.\" The connection lies in experiencing disturbance or upheaval, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on movement. This term often describes significant events like earthquakes, emphasizing the vulnerability of worldly structures and the awe-inspiring power of divine forces.",
  "1820": "رُجْزٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-ز, with the root verb رَجَزَ meaning \"he was in a state of shaking\" or \"he recited improvised poetry.\" رُجْزٌ means \"punishment\" or \"torment.\" The connection lies in the concept of disturbance or agitation, reflecting the root's emphasis on shaking. This term signifies afflictions meant to warn or correct, highlighting the moral implications of actions and the divine response to human behavior.",
  "1821": "رُجْعَى and related words stem from the root ر-ج-ع, with the root verb رَجَعَ meaning \"he returned\" or \"he went back.\" رُجْعَى means \"return\" or \"reversion.\" The connection emphasizes the act of returning to an original state, reflecting the root's focus on reversal. This term often carries spiritual connotations of returning to Allah (ﷻ), highlighting themes of accountability and the ultimate return of all souls to their Creator.",
  "1822": "رُحْمٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ح-م, with the root verb رَحِمَ meaning \"he showed mercy\" or \"he had compassion.\" رُحْمٌ refers to \"mercy\" or \"compassion\" in a collective sense, emphasizing communal care and widespread kindness. The root reflects tenderness and mutual support, highlighting the importance of mercy as a foundation for a harmonious and compassionate society. This term highlights the collective responsibility to foster care and understanding among individuals.",
  "1823": "رُخَاءٌ and related words stem from the root ر-خ-و, with the root verb رَخَا meaning \"it was gentle,\" \"it was soft,\" or \"it was easy.\" رُخَاءٌ means \"ease,\" \"gentleness,\" or \"prosperity.\" The connection lies in the idea of things being smooth and untroubled, reflecting the root's essence of softness and ease. In the Qur'an, رُخَاءٌ can describe a favorable wind or a state of comfort granted by Allah (ﷻ), symbolizing blessings and tranquility in life's journey.",
  "1824": "رُشْدٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ش-د, with the root verb رَشَدَ meaning \"he was rightly guided\" or \"he was sensible.\" رُشْدٌ means \"right guidance,\" \"maturity,\" or \"sound judgment.\" The connection lies in the state of being on the correct path and possessing mature understanding, reflecting the root's essence of guidance and wisdom.",
  "1825": "رُطَبٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ط-ب, with the root verb رَطَبَ meaning \"it was fresh\" or \"it became ripe.\" رُطَبٌ is the plural of رَطْبٌ, meaning \"fresh dates\" or \"ripe fruits.\" The connection lies in the collection of fresh produce, embodying the root's emphasis on abundance of moist and ripe fruits. This term highlights the bounty of nature and the blessings bestowed upon people, often symbolizing prosperity and sustenance.",
  "1826": "رُعْبٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ع-ب, with the root verb رَعِبَ meaning \"he was terrified\" or \"he was frightened.\" رُعْبٌ means \"fear,\" \"terror,\" or \"dread.\" The connection lies in the intense feeling of fear or anxiety, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on fright. This term captures the profound emotional response to perceived threats, highlighting the human experience of fear and its impact on behavior.",
  "1827": "رُفَاتٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ف-ت, with the root verb رَفَتَ meaning \"he broke into pieces\" or \"he crumbled.\" رُفَاتٌ means \"fragments,\" \"dust,\" or \"decayed remains.\" The connection lies in the state of being broken down into tiny particles, embodying the root's emphasis on fragmentation. This term often refers to the remains of the dead, highlighting the transient nature of life and the inevitability of physical decay, invoking reflections on resurrection and the hereafter.",
  "1828": "رُقُودٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ق-د, with the root verb رَقَدَ meaning \"he slept\" or \"he lay down.\" رُقُودٌ means \"sleep\" or \"slumber.\" The connection emphasizes a state of rest or dormancy, reflecting the root's concept of lying down or being motionless. In the Qur'anic story of the People of the Cave, رُقُودٌ describes their prolonged sleep, symbolizing divine protection and suspension of normal life processes.",
  "1829": "رُقِيٌّ and related words stem from the root ر-ق-ي, with the root verb رَقِىَ meaning \"he ascended\" or \"he recited incantations.\" رُقِيٌّ means \"ascension\" or \"incantation.\" The connection lies in the act of rising or elevating in status or spirit, directly relating to the root's meaning. In spiritual contexts, رُقِيٌّ refers to protective prayers or recitations used for healing, symbolizing a means of elevating one's state through divine words.",
  "1830": "رُكَامٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ك-م, with the root verb رَكَمَ meaning \"he heaped up\" or \"he piled.\" رُكَامٌ refers to \"a heap,\" \"pile,\" or \"mass,\" emphasizing accumulated or clustered objects. The connection lies in the gathering and stacking of items, directly relating to the root's meaning. In the Qur'an, it describes piled-up clouds that lead to heavy rain, symbolizing how accumulation can result in significant outcomes.",
  "1831": "رُكْبَانٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ك-ب, with the root verb رَكِبَ meaning \"he rode\" or \"he mounted.\" رُكْبَانٌ refers to \"riders\" or \"mounted troops,\" emphasizing a group of people who are riding animals or conveyances. The connection lies in the collective action of riding, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term can symbolize mobility, readiness, or the strength of a mounted group in travel or battle.",
  "1832": "رُكْنٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ك-ن, with the root verb رَكَنَ meaning \"he inclined\" or \"he leaned.\" رُكْنٌ refers to \"pillar,\" \"corner,\" or \"support,\" emphasizing something that provides strength or stability. The connection lies in the concept of leaning upon something strong, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term symbolizes foundational elements that uphold structures or principles in a moral or spiritual context.",
  "1833": "رُمَّانٌ and related words stem from the root ر-م-ن, which refers specifically to \"pomegranates.\" The connection lies in the fruit itself, celebrated for its beauty and abundance of seeds. In the Qur'an, رُمَّانٌ is mentioned as one of the fruits of Paradise, symbolizing sustenance, prosperity, and the blessings of Allah (ﷻ).",
  "1834": "رُهْبَانٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ه-ب, with the root verb رَهِبَ meaning \"he feared\" or \"he was in awe.\" رُهْبَانٌ is the plural of رَاهِبٌ, meaning \"monks.\" The connection lies in individuals who embody fear or awe of God, dedicating themselves to spiritual practices. This term highlights those who choose a life of devotion and asceticism, directly relating to the root's meaning.",
  "1835": "رُوحٌ and related words stem from the root ر-و-ح, with the root verb رَاحَ meaning \"he departed\" or \"he found rest.\" رُوحٌ means \"spirit\" or \"soul,\" representing the vital force that gives life to the body. The connection lies in the root's idea of movement and change, where the spirit is like breath or wind, constantly in motion, bringing life and energy. Just as breath makes the difference between being alive and lifeless, the soul is what transitions us from mere existence to living with purpose and vitality. It’s the essence that fuels our actions, emotions, and growth, reminding us of the power of transformation and the deeper life and higher purpose that resides within us.",
  "1836": "الرُّومُ and related words stem from the root ر-و-م, with the root verb رَامَ meaning \"he intended,\" \"he desired,\" or \"he sought.\" الرُّومُ refers to \"the Romans\" or \"Byzantines,\" a people mentioned in the Qur'an. The connection lies in the Romans being a nation that sought expansion, power, and influence, reflecting the root's meaning of seeking or desiring. In the Qur'an, their mention serves as a sign of Allah's (ﷻ) control over the rise and fall of empires, reminding believers that worldly power is transient and ultimately subject to His will.",
  "1837": "رُوَيْدٌ and related words stem from the root ر-و-د, with the root verb رَادَ meaning \"he sought\" or \"he moved about.\" رُوَيْدٌ means \"slowly,\" \"gently,\" or \"a little.\" The connection lies in the idea of moving or progressing with care and deliberation. The root emphasizes movement or striving toward a goal, but رُوَيْدٌ introduces nuance by highlighting a restrained or measured pace. This term conveys a sense of gentle progression, where the movement is intentional and careful, reflecting the broader root meanings of steady pursuit or gradual advancement, whether in physical motion, personal growth, or even emotional states.",
  "1838": "رِئْيٌ and related words stem from the root ر-أ-ي, with the root verb رَأَىٰ meaning \"he saw\" or \"he perceived.\" رِئْيٌ means \"appearance\" or \"outward show,\" focusing on the visual or external perception of something. The root extends to encompass themes of sight, perception, and observation, highlighting the distinction between what is outwardly visible and what lies beneath the surface. This term highlights the contrast between external appearances and internal realities, emphasizing the importance of sincerity, substance, and authenticity over superficial display or mere embellishment.",
  "1839": "رِئَاءٌ and related words stem from the root ر-أ-ي, with the root verb رَأَىٰ meaning \"he saw\" or \"he perceived.\" رِئَاءٌ means \"ostentation\" or \"the act of seeking to be seen,\" referring to actions performed with the intention of being observed by others rather than out of sincerity. The root's emphasis on sight and perception extends here to a deliberate focus on external appearances, where actions are carried out to gain visibility or approval. This term highlights the emptiness of deeds done for recognition, emphasizing the contrast between outward display and true, internal sincerity.",
  "1840": "رِبًا and related words stem from the root ر-ب-و, with the root verb رَبَا meaning \"it increased,\" \"it grew,\" or \"it exceeded its proper bounds.\" رِبًا means \"usury,\" referring to an unjust increase in wealth through exploitative financial practices, often involving excessive or unearned gains. The root conveys themes of unnatural growth or excess, highlighting the harmful consequences of greed and imbalance. رِبًا highlights the ethical principles in economic transactions, warning against practices that disrupt social equity and fairness.",
  "1841": "الرِّبَا and related words stem from the root ر-ب-و, with the root verb رَبَا meaning \"it increased,\" \"it grew,\" or \"it exceeded proper limits.\" الرِّبَا, meaning \"the usury,\" emphasizes the act of gaining wealth through unjust and exploitative means, particularly in financial dealings. The root reflects growth that is disproportionate or unnatural, symbolizing excess that leads to societal harm. The concept of الرِّبَا warns against practices that foster inequality and injustice, advocating for fairness and mutual benefit in all transactions.",
  "1842": "رِبَاطٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ب-ط, with the root verb رَبَطَ meaning \"he tied\" or \"he bound.\" رِبَاطٌ means \"bond,\" \"tie,\" \"fortress,\" or \"garrison.\" The term signifies a place where horses are tied, hence a military post or means of defense, reflecting the root's emphasis on binding. It symbolizes unity, strength, and preparedness, highlighting the importance of being firmly connected and ready to defend one's principles or community.",
  "1843": "رِبِّيُّونَ and related words stem from the root ر-ب-ب, with the root verb رَبّ meaning \"he reared, fostered, brought up, fed, or nourished,\" or \"he put the affair into a right, or proper, state,\" or \"he possessed or had authority over.\" رِبِّيُّونَ refers to \"a group devoted to Allah (ﷻ)\" or \"devout followers,\" describing people who are steadfast and sincere in their faith and actions. The root’s themes of nurturing and proper cultivation connect to the spiritual and moral development of these individuals under Allah’s (ﷻ) guidance. This term highlights their steadfast devotion, collective strength, and commitment to truth, highlighting the nurturing process of being sustained by faith and divine knowledge.",
  "1844": "رِجَالٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-ل, with the root verb رَجَلَ meaning \"he walked on foot.\" رِجَالٌ is the plural form of رَجُلٌ, meaning \"men.\" The connection is direct, denoting multiple adult males. This term emphasizes collective strength, responsibility, and the active role of men within society.",
  "1845": "رِجْزٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-ز, with the root verb رَجَزَ meaning \"he trembled\" or \"he shook.\" رِجْزٌ means \"impurity\" or \"torment.\" The connection lies in the state of agitation or disturbance, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on shaking. This term conveys the idea of moral defilement or the consequences of sin, emphasizing the need for purification and the avoidance of actions that lead to spiritual corruption.",
  "1846": "رِجْسٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-س, with the root verb رَجَسَ meaning \"he was impure\" or \"he was defiled.\" رِجْسٌ means \"abomination\" or \"impurity.\" The connection lies in the concept of moral or physical defilement, reflecting the root's emphasis on impurity. This term denotes detestable actions or things that corrupt the soul, emphasizing the importance of purity and adherence to Allah's (ﷻ) guidance.",
  "1847": "رِجْلٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-ل, with the root verb رَجَلَ meaning \"he walked on foot.\" رِجْلٌ means \"foot.\" The connection is direct, as the foot enables walking, reflecting the root's emphasis on movement. This term signifies mobility and support, highlighting the foundational role of the foot in facilitating life's journey.",
  "1848": "رِحْلَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ح-ل, with the root verb رَحَلَ meaning \"he departed\" or \"he journeyed.\" رِحْلَةٌ means \"journey\" or \"expedition.\" The connection is direct, denoting the act of traveling, reflecting the root's emphasis on movement. This term embodies the concept of embarking on a voyage, highlighting themes of exploration, change, and the pursuit of new horizons.",
  "1849": "رِدْءٌ and related words stem from the root ر-د-أ, with the root verb رَدَأَ meaning \"he assisted,\" \"he supported,\" or \"he strengthened.\" رِدْءٌ means \"assistant\" or \"supporter.\" The connection lies in the role of someone who provides support or reinforcement, reflecting the root's essence of aiding and strengthening others. It emphasizes the importance of mutual assistance and solidarity in overcoming challenges.",
  "1850": "رِزْقٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ز-ق, with the root verb رَزَقَ meaning \"he provided sustenance\" or \"he bestowed provisions.\" رِزْقٌ means \"sustenance\" or \"provision.\" The connection lies in the sustenance and livelihood granted to creatures, reflecting the root's essence of providing. It encompasses all forms of provision, both material and spiritual, highlighting dependence on divine generosity.",
  "1851": "رِسالَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-س-ل, with the root verb رَسَلَ meaning \"he sent.\" رِسالَةٌ means \"message\" or \"mission.\" The connection reflects the content or purpose of what is sent, embodying the root's essence of sending. It emphasizes the significance of the message conveyed by prophets, highlighting the importance of the divine message in guiding humanity.",
  "1852": "رِضْوَانٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ض-و, with the root verb رَضِيَ meaning \"he was pleased\" or \"he was content.\" رِضْوَانٌ means \"great pleasure\" or \"supreme satisfaction.\" The connection lies in the heightened state of divine approval and immense satisfaction, expanding upon the root's focus on contentment. In the Qur'anic context, it represents the ultimate pleasure of Allah (ﷻ), a reward greater than all others for the believers, emphasizing the profound spiritual fulfillment found in divine acceptance.",
  "1853": "رِعَاءٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ع-ي, with the root verb رَعَىٰ meaning \"he tended\" or \"he cared for.\" رِعَاءٌ means \"pasturing\" or \"grazing.\" The connection lies in the activity of allowing livestock to feed on pasture, embodying the root's emphasis on tending and nurturing. This term reflects the sustenance provided through grazing, highlighting the relationship between the caretaker and the cared-for in the natural cycle of provision.",
  "1854": "رِعَايَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ع-ي, with the root verb رَعَىٰ meaning \"he tended\" or \"he cared for.\" رِعَايَةٌ means \"care,\" \"protection,\" or \"guardianship.\" The connection lies in the act of overseeing and providing for others, embodying the root's emphasis on care and responsibility. This term highlights the importance of attentiveness and stewardship, reflecting moral and social obligations to care for others.",
  "1855": "رِفْدٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ف-د, with the root verb رَفَدَ meaning \"he assisted\" or \"he supported.\" رِفْدٌ means \"aid,\" \"support,\" or \"gift.\" The connection lies in the act of providing help or assistance, embodying the root's emphasis on support and generosity. This term reflects the importance of helping others and the value of generosity, emphasizing moral virtues of compassion and charity.",
  "1856": "رِكَابٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ك-ب, with the root verb رَكِبَ meaning \"he rode\" or \"he mounted.\" رِكَابٌ refers to \"riding animals\" or \"mounts,\" such as camels or horses used for transportation. It can also mean \"stirrups,\" the device used to support the rider's feet. The connection lies in the equipment or animals associated with riding, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term highlights the means by which one travels or embarks on a journey.",
  "1857": "رِكْزٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ك-ز, with the root verb رَكَزَ meaning \"he fixed,\" \"he planted,\" or \"he inserted.\" رِكْزٌ refers to \"a faint sound\" or \"a whisper,\" emphasizing something subtle or barely audible. The connection lies in the subtlety and hidden nature of both the act of embedding and the faintness of the sound, directly relating to the root's meaning. In the Qur'an, it denotes the absence of any sound or movement, highlighting absolute stillness or silence.",
  "1858": "رِمَاحٌ and related words stem from the root ر-م-ح, with the root verb رَمَحَ meaning \"he pierced\" or \"he stabbed.\" رِمَاحٌ is the plural of رُمْحٌ, meaning \"spears.\" The connection lies in the weapon used for piercing, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term emphasizes implements of warfare or defense, symbolizing strength or aggression in battle contexts.",
  "1859": "رِهَانٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ه-ن, with the root verb رَهَنَ meaning \"he pledged\" or \"he mortgaged.\" رِهَانٌ refers to \"a wager\" or \"bet,\" involving stakes or pledges on an outcome. The connection lies in the act of placing something at risk based on uncertainty, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term underscores the aspects of risk and commitment inherent in competitive or uncertain situations.",
  "1860": "رِيبَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ي-ب, with the root verb رَابَ meaning \"he doubted\" or \"he suspected.\" رِيبَةٌ means \"suspicion\" or \"doubt.\" The connection lies in internal distrust or unease about something, emphasizing the root’s focus on doubt and skepticism. رِيبَةٌ conveys the emotional discomfort of being unsure, leading to a lack of trust or confidence in others or in a situation. It embodies the internal unease that leads to questioning the truth or motives behind actions.",
  "1861": "رِيحٌ and related words stem from the root ر-و-ح, with the root verb رَاحَ meaning \"he found rest\" or \"he was comforted.\" رِيحٌ means \"wind\" or \"breeze,\" representing the natural movement of air. The connection lies in the calming and refreshing nature of both rest and the wind. Just as rest brings comfort and relief, a gentle breeze provides tranquility and ease. Both have the ability to bring about a sense of renewal, whether through physical relaxation or the soothing effects of the breeze. The root emphasizes the peaceful, comforting, and sometimes transformative qualities of both wind and rest, symbolizing a shift toward calmness and renewal.",
  "1862": "رِيشٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ي-ش, with the verb رَاشَ meaning \"he furnished,\" \"he supplied,\" or \"he repaired.\" رِيشٌ specifically refers to \"feathers,\" which beautify and protect birds, and by extension, it signifies \"clothing\" or \"adornments\" for humans, serving a similar purpose. The root conveys functionality and enhancement, reflecting provision, repair, and improvement. رِيشٌ symbolizes both utility and beauty, emphasizing Allah’s (ﷻ) provision of means for protection, dignity, and adornment, highlighting His wisdom and care for His creation.",
  "1863": "رِيعٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ي-ع, with the root verb رَاعَ meaning \"he increased\" or \"he rose.\" رِيعٌ refers to \"profit,\" \"increase,\" or \"elevated ground.\" The connection lies in the concept of rising or growing, whether in wealth or in physical height. Just as something increases or ascends, رِيعٌ symbolizes the results of growth, whether it's the accumulation of wealth, improvement, or advancement. It embodies the idea of rising to a higher state, whether in material or metaphorical terms, reflecting the root's emphasis on expansion and elevation.",
  "1864": "الزَّاجِرَاتُ stems from the root ز-ج-ر, with زَجَرَ meaning \"he rebuked,\" \"he restrained,\" or \"he admonished.\" الزَّاجِرَاتُ refers to \"those who admonish,\" \"restrain,\" or \"urge,\" emphasizing a role of firm guidance and redirection to prevent deviation. This term conveys a sense of authority and purpose, reflecting actions that enforce restraint, drive motion, or maintain order. It symbolizes issuing stern admonitions or exerting influence to deter from error or compel forward action. The connection lies in the deliberate and corrective nature of these actions, embodying the root’s essence of rebuke, restraint, and purposeful redirection for a beneficial outcome.",
  "1865": "زَادَ and related words stem from the root ز-و-د, with the root verb زَادَ meaning \"he increased\" or \"he augmented.\" زَادٌ is also a noun meaning \"provision\" or \"supply.\" The connection lies in the concept of increase and providing more, reflecting the root's emphasis on augmentation. It signifies both material provisions and the spiritual increase needed for life's journey.",
  "1866": "زَادَ and related words stem from the root ز-ي-د, with the root verb زَادَ meaning \"he increased,\" \"he grew,\" or \"he added.\" زَادَ means \"he increased\" or \"he added,\" often describing a natural or spontaneous increase without necessarily implying compounding or reflexivity. This term embodies the fundamental act of addition or augmentation, highlighting the inherent potential for growth and improvement in various contexts. The root’s dimensions include themes of abundance, sufficiency, and enhancement, highlighting how growth can occur naturally or through divine providence.",
  "1867": "زَارِعٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ر-ع, with the root verb زَرَعَ meaning \"he sowed\" or \"he planted.\" زَارِعٌ means \"sower\" or \"farmer,\" referring to one who engages in planting and cultivation. The connection lies in the individual's role in nurturing the earth to bring forth produce, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on sowing seeds and fostering growth.",
  "1868": "زَاغَ and related words stem from the root ز-ي-غ, with the root verb زَاغَ meaning \"he deviated,\" \"he swerved,\" or \"he turned aside.\" زَاغَ means \"he deviated\" or \"he strayed.\" The connection lies in the susceptibility to diverge from the right course, embodying the root's concept of deviation. زَاغَ serves as a caution against the distractions and temptations that can lead one away from truth and righteousness.",
  "1869": "زَالَ and related words stem from the root ز-و-ل, with the root verb زَالَ meaning \"he ceased,\" \"he moved away,\" or \"he departed.\" زَالَ means \"he ceased\" or \"he vanished.\" The connection lies in the concept of impermanence and the transient nature of worldly things. زَالَ reflects the root's emphasis on movement away or cessation, reminding us that nothing remains unchanged and everything is subject to end or transformation.",
  "1870": "زَالَتْ and related words stem from the root ز-ي-ل, with the root verb زَالَ meaning \"he ceased,\" \"he departed,\" or \"he moved away from a fixed position.\" زَالَتْ means \"it ceased\" or \"it departed,\" referring specifically to a feminine noun. The root encompasses themes of transience, impermanence, and change.",
  "1871": "زَانٍ stems from the root ز-ن-ي, with the root verb زَنَى meaning \"he committed adultery\" or \"he fornicated.\" زَانٍ means \"adulterer\" or \"fornicator,\" referring to a male who engages in unlawful intimate relations. The root also encompasses broader meanings related to deviation, moral corruption, and improper conduct, emphasizing the departure from purity and lawful behavior. The connection between زَانٍ and its root reflects the severe consequences of unlawful acts, both individually and societally, highlighting the gravity of maintaining moral boundaries.",
  "1872": "زَانِيَةٌ stems from the root ز-ن-ي, with the root verb زَنَى meaning \"he committed adultery\" or \"he fornicated.\" زَانِيَةٌ means \"adulteress\" or \"fornicatress,\" specifically describing a female engaged in unlawful intimate acts. The root also ties to notions of disgrace and moral decline, indicating the societal harm caused by violating established ethical codes. The word زَانِيَةٌ emphasizes the Qur'anic injunctions against immorality and the spiritual and social repercussions of straying from chastity.",
  "1873": "زَاهِدٌ stems from the root ز-ه-د, with the root verb زَهَدَ meaning \"he abstained\" or \"he renounced worldly pleasures.\" زَاهِدٌ means \"one who abstains,\" or \"one who does not desire.\" The root conveys meanings of detachment, minimalism, and refraining from excessive indulgence. The connection lies in the practice of renunciation, where one focuses on spiritual growth over material desires. This word emphasizes the virtues of simplicity and prioritizing the eternal over the transient.",
  "1874": "زَاهِقٌ stems from the root ز-ه-ق, with the root verb زَهَقَ meaning \"it perished, passed away,\" or \"it became null, void, or of no effect.\" زَاهِقٌ means \"perishing,\" \"dying.\" The root highlights notions of disappearance, futility, and nullification. The connection lies in the inevitability of falsehood and worldly distractions vanishing, reflecting the root’s focus on the transient nature of untruths. This word highlights the ultimate triumph of truth over falsehood. ",
  "1875": "الزَّبَانِيَةُ and related words stem from the root ز-ب-ن, with the root verb زَبَنَ meaning \"he pushed,\" \"he repelled,\" or \"he drove forcefully.\" The term الزَّبَانِيَةُ refers to the \"Angels of Hell,\" specifically those entrusted with punishing the wicked. The root encompasses the act of forcefully driving or repelling, implying power, control, and authority in restraining or expelling. This aligns with the role of these angels in administering divine punishment, ensuring justice by driving evildoers into torment. The imagery inherent in the root enhances the understanding of their function as beings of immense strength and severity, tasked with a role of profound accountability.",
  "1876": "زَبَدٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ب-د, which refers to \"foam\" or \"froth,\" the light and airy substance that accumulates on the surface of liquids such as water or milk. This foam, while visible and seemingly tangible, is inherently transient and insubstantial, forming quickly and vanishing with ease. The root reflects this impermanence and lack of durability, emphasizing how زَبَدٌ can symbolize things that initially appear impressive or significant but ultimately prove to be without true value or substance.",
  "1877": "زَبُورٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ب-ر, with the root verb زَبَرَ meaning \"he wrote,\" \"he inscribed,\" or \"he engraved.\" زَبُورٌ means \"Psalms,\" referring to the divine revelations given to Prophet David (ﷺ). The root emphasizes themes of recording, engraving, and permanence, highlighting the act of preserving messages of profound significance. The connection lies in the written nature of the Psalms, reflecting its role as a sacred and enduring scripture.",
  "1878": "زَجْرٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ج-ر, with the verb زَجَرَ meaning \"he rebuked,\" \"he restrained,\" or \"he admonished.\" زَجْرٌ refers to \"rebuke,\" \"stern admonition,\" or \"a strong act of restraint.\" The root emphasizes authoritative correction, combining firmness with the intent to redirect or restrain behavior. This reflects the purposeful act of preventing deviation through forceful yet guiding intervention, embodying the root’s concept of control, discipline, and the imposition of order.",
  "1879": "زَحْفٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ح-ف, with the verb زَحَفَ meaning \"he crawled\" or \"he advanced slowly.\" زَحْفٌ refers to \"march\" or \"advancement,\" particularly describing the slow and deliberate movement of an army. The root conveys the concept of steady, intentional progress, which is directly reflected in زَحْفٌ as it highlights methodical and purposeful advancement toward a goal. This connection signifies the root's emphasis on slow, determined movement, often in challenging or deliberate circumstances.",
  "1880": "زَرَابِيُّ and related words stem from the root ز-ر-ب, with the root verb زَرَبَ meaning \"he enclosed\" or \"he confined.\" زَرَابِيُّ is the plural of زَرْبِيَّةٌ, meaning \"luxurious carpets\" or \"sumptuous rugs.\" The connection lies in carpets covering and adorning spaces, creating an enclosed and intimate environment, reflecting the root's concept of enclosing or surrounding. These richly decorated carpets symbolize opulence and comfort, transforming a place much like an enclosure provides security and definition.",
  "1881": "زَرْعٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ر-ع, with the root verb زَرَعَ meaning \"he sowed\" or \"he planted.\" زَرْعٌ refers to \"crop,\" \"sown field,\" or \"produce.\" The connection lies in the result of the act of sowing—what has been planted and cultivated—embodying the root's focus on agriculture and the cycle of growth from seed to harvest.",
  "1882": "زَعَمَ and related words stem from the root ز-ع-م, with the root verb زَعَمَ meaning \"he claimed,\" \"he alleged,\" or \"he asserted.\" The connection lies in the act of making a statement or assertion, whether true or false, reflecting the root's emphasis on speech and declaration. It often carries a connotation of dubiousness or unfounded claims, highlighting the importance of truthfulness in speech.",
  "1883": "زَعِيمٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ع-م, with the root verb زَعَمَ meaning \"he claimed\" or \"he asserted.\" زَعِيمٌ means \"leader,\" \"chief,\" or \"guarantor.\" The connection lies in someone who takes responsibility or makes assertions on behalf of others, reflecting the root's concept of claiming or undertaking. This word embodies leadership by standing as a spokesperson or guarantor, highlighting accountability and representation.",
  "1884": "زَعْمٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ع-م, with the root verb زَعَمَ meaning \"he claimed\" or \"he alleged.\" زَعْمٌ means \"claim,\" \"assertion,\" or \"allegation.\" The connection lies in the act of making a statement or assertion, whether valid or not, reflecting the root's emphasis on claims and declarations. It highlights the significance of substantiating one's statements with truth and evidence.",
  "1885": "زَفِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ف-ر, with the root verb زَفَرَ meaning \"he sighed\" or \"he exhaled heavily.\" زَفِيرٌ means \"sigh,\" \"gasp,\" or \"moan,\" often associated with intense sorrow or distress. The connection lies in the act of releasing a heavy breath due to overwhelming emotion, reflecting the root's concept of deep exhalation. It evokes imagery of anguish and despair, emphasizing the physical manifestation of inner turmoil.",
  "1886": "زَقُّومٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ق-م, with the root verb زَقَمَ meaning \"he swallowed something harmful\" or \"he ate greedily.\" زَقُّومٌ refers to a tree in Hell bearing bitter and painful fruit. The connection lies in the act of consuming something that causes harm or distress, embodying the root's concept of harmful ingestion. The tree symbolizes torment and the consequences of one's actions, serving as a stark warning of the fate awaiting those who reject guidance.",
  "1887": "زَكَاةٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ك-و, with the root verb زَكَا meaning \"he was pure\" or \"he grew.\"  زَكَاةٌ refers to \"almsgiving,\" \"charity,\" or \"purification.\" The root also signifies enhancement, blessing, and purification. The connection lies in the act of giving wealth to purify one's soul and wealth, reflecting the root's emphasis on growth and purity. It represents both a social duty and a means of spiritual cleansing, promoting generosity, reducing greed, and fostering social equity.",
  "1888": "زَكَرِيَّا is the name of Prophet Zechariah (ﷺ). While the name doesn't have a direct Arabic root, in ancient Hebrew it combines Zakar (remembrance) and Yah (the Lord), translating to \"remembrance of God.\" This name reflects Prophet Zechariah's (ﷺ) constant remembrance and supplication to Allah (ﷻ), especially in his prayers for a righteous offspring. His story exemplifies unwavering faith and the blessings that come from sincere devotion, emphasizing the importance of remembering Allah (ﷻ) and placing trust in His wisdom.",
  "1889": "زَكَى and related words stem from the root ز-ك-و, with the root verb زَكَا meaning \"he was pure\" or \"he grew.\" زَكَى means \"he purified\" or \"he caused to grow.\" The root also conveys meanings of flourishing, thriving, and increasing in goodness or blessing. The connection lies in the act of purifying something or promoting growth, embodying the root's concepts of cleanliness, improvement, and increase. It emphasizes deliberate actions that lead to moral refinement, spiritual development, or the enhancement of goodness.",
  "1890": "زَكِيٌّ and related words stem from the root ز-ك-و, with the root verb زَكَا meaning \"he was pure\" or \"he grew.\" The root also encompasses meanings of thriving, being free from impurity, and growing in goodness or virtue. زَكِيٌّ means \"pure,\" \"innocent,\" or \"righteous.\" The connection lies in the state of being morally clean, free from sin, or virtuous, reflecting the root's emphasis on purity and goodness. It highlights qualities of innocence, ethical integrity, and moral excellence in a person.",
  "1891": "زَكِيَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ك-و, with the root verb زَكَا meaning \"he was pure\" or \"he grew.\" زَكِيَّةٌ means \"pure,\" \"innocent,\" or \"righteous.\" The root also includes dimensions of blessing, refinement, and growth in purity. The connection lies in embodying purity, growth, and moral excellence, reflecting the root's focus on cleanliness and virtue. It denotes a state of innocence and ethical refinement.",
  "1892": "زَكَّى and related words stem from the root ز-ك-و, with the root verb زَكَا meaning \"he was pure\" or \"he grew.\" زَكَّى means \"he purified\" or \"he extolled,\" intensifying the root’s emphasis on purification and growth. The root also conveys meanings of flourishing, thriving, increasing in goodness, and attaining blessing.The connection lies in the deliberate act of cleansing or praising someone, reflecting the root's focus on enhancing moral or spiritual purity and promoting growth. It highlights actions that elevate a person's ethical or spiritual stature through purification or commendation.",
  "1893": "زَلَقٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ل-ق, with the root verb زَلَقَ meaning \"he slipped,\" \"he slid,\" or \"he lost footing.\" زَلَقٌ means \"slippery,\" emphasizing surfaces or conditions that lead to instability and difficulty in maintaining a firm position. The root also conveys meanings of smoothness, instability, and the loss of control or balance. The connection lies in the act of slipping or losing footing, reflecting the root's focus on smoothness that disrupts stability. It highlights situations where a lack of grip leads to vulnerability or error.",
  "1894": "زَلَلْتُمْ and related words stem from the root ز-ل-ل, with the root verb زَلَّ meaning \"he slipped\" or \"he erred.\" زَلَلْتُمْ means \"you slipped\" or \"you erred.\" The root also conveys notions of falling, faltering, or making unintentional mistakes, often due to a loss of footing or judgment. The connection lies in the human propensity to falter, reflecting the root's emphasis on unintentional error. It serves as a reminder of human fallibility and the importance of seeking correction and guidance to avoid further missteps.",
  "1895": "زَلْزَلَةٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ل-ز-ل, a reduplicated root conveying intensity and repetition, with the root verb زَلْزَلَ meaning \"he shook violently\" or \"he caused to tremble.\" زَلْزَلَةٌ means \"earthquake\" or \"severe shaking.\" The root also encompasses meanings of instability, agitation, and repetitive motion, emphasizing the violent and continuous nature of the action. The connection lies in the intense, repetitive shaking motion, embodying the root's concept of instability and upheaval. It symbolizes moments of great turmoil or divine warning, highlighting the profound impact of such events as a reminder or test.",
  "1896": "زَمْهَرِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ز-م-ه-ر, conveying the meaning of extreme cold. زَمْهَرِيرٌ means \"intense cold,\" \"hurting cold,\" or \"bitter cold.\" The root also encompasses notions of harshness, severity, and piercing intensity, particularly in reference to chilling sensations. The connection lies in the extreme sensation of coldness, reflecting the root's emphasis on harsh, piercing cold. In descriptions of Hell, it refers to a place of unbearable cold, contrasting with scorching heat, highlighting the various forms of punishment and emphasizing the diversity of suffering.",
  "1897": "زَنْجَبِيلٌ is of Persian origin, derived from the Middle Persian word šangavīr, meaning \"ginger.\" In the Qur'an, زَنْجَبِيلٌ is mentioned as a flavoring for a refreshing drink in Paradise, symbolizing the invigorating and delightful experiences awaiting the righteous. The use of ginger reflects its rich and stimulating qualities, representing the refined pleasures and unparalleled sensory delights of the afterlife. This alludes to the idea that in Paradise, the joys provided to believers will far surpass those known in the worldly life, offering exquisite rewards in every aspect.",
  "1898": "زَنِيمٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ن-م, with the root verb زَنَّمَ meaning \"the act of marking with a sign or token.\" زَنِيمٌ refers to someone \"not honorable in character or purpose,\" \"notorious for wickedness,\" or \"infamous for evil deeds.\" The root conveys meanings of being marked, branded, or identified by a distinguishing feature, often denoting dishonor or abnormality. The connection lies in the concept of being marked with dishonor, reflecting the root's focus on an identifying mark. It symbolizes a person infamous for vice and malice, emphasizing moral degradation and shame.",
  "1899": "زَهَقَ and related words stem from the root ز-ه-ق, and as the root verb, it means \"it perished, passed away,\" or \"it became null, void, or of no effect.\" The connection lies in the act of ceasing to exist or disappearing, reflecting the root's emphasis on the end of something. It often refers to falsehood or evil being overcome and rendered void, emphasizing the triumph of truth.",
  "1900": "زَهُوقٌ stems from the root ز-ه-ق, with the root verb زَهَقَ meaning \"it perished, passed away,\" or \"it became null, void, or of no effect.\" زَهُوقٌ means \"perishing,\" \"vanishing,\" or \"doomed to perish.\" The root captures the state of inevitable end or disappearance. The connection lies in the nature of falsehood and deceit, destined to fade and fail in the face of truth. This word emphasizes the transient and futile nature of dishonesty, contrasting it with the enduring nature of truth and righteousness.",
  "1901": "زَهْرَةٌ stems from the root ز-ه-ر, with the root verb زَهَرَ meaning \"it shone\" or \"it blossomed.\" زَهْرَةٌ means \"flower,\" \"bloom,\" or \"blossom.\" The root conveys ideas of brightness, radiance, and flourishing. The connection lies in the beauty and ephemeral nature of flowers, symbolizing both natural splendor and the fleeting nature of worldly life. It serves as a reminder of Allah's (ﷻ) artistry and the transitory beauty of creation.",
  "1902": "زَوَالٌ and related words stem from the root ز-و-ل, with the root verb زَالَ meaning \"he ceased\" or \"he departed.\" زَوَالٌ means \"decline,\" \"cessation,\" or \"the time when the sun begins to decline from its highest point at noon.\" The connection lies in the transition from one state to another, embodying the root's concept of movement and cessation. زَوَالٌ marks a pivotal moment of change, symbolizing the inevitable decline that follows every peak and serving as a reminder of life's transient nature.",
  "1903": "زَوْجٌ and related words stem from the root ز-و-ج, with the root verb زَوَّجَ meaning \"he paired\" or \"he married.\" زَوْجٌ means \"pair,\" \"mate,\" or \"spouse.\" The connection lies in the concept of pairing or coupling, reflecting the root's emphasis on duality and companionship. It signifies the complementary nature of pairs in creation, emphasizing harmony and balance.",
  "1904": "زَيَّلْنَا and related words stem from the root ز-ي-ل, with the root verb زَالَ meaning \"he separated,\" \"he parted,\" or \"he removed.\" زَيَّلْنَا means \"We separated\" or \"We distinguished,\" emphasizing an active and deliberate act of parting or dividing. The connection lies in the root’s focus on creating distinction or separation, whether physical, metaphorical, or situational. This term highlights moments where clarity is brought through division or differentiation, often signifying divine action in distinguishing between groups, states, or outcomes, highlighting accountability and purpose.",
  "1905": "زَيَّنَ and related words also stem from the root ز-ي-ن, with the root verb زَانَ meaning \"he adorned\" or \"he beautified.\" زَيَّنَ means \"he adorned\" or \"he beautified,\" or \"he made appealing,\" describing the act of enhancing or embellishing something to make it more attractive. The root includes dimensions of both genuine and deceptive adornment, as beauty can either highlight truth or mask flaws. زَيَّنَ illustrates how things may be made appealing to the eye or heart, sometimes deceptively, urging discernment to see beyond superficial allure and recognize true value and authenticity.",
  "1906": "زَيْتٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ي-ت, which is associated with oil and its extraction. زَيْتٌ means \"oil,\" particularly \"olive oil.\" The connection lies in the process of extracting and refining, embodying the root's focus on deriving something valuable from a source. زَيْتٌ symbolizes nourishment, illumination, and healing, reflecting the transformative journey from raw material to beneficial substance.",
  "1907": "زَيْتُونَةٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ي-ت, connected to oil and its origins. زَيْتُونَةٌ means \"an olive tree.\" The connection lies in the tree being the origin of olives and oil, embodying the root's focus on a source that provides abundant benefits. زَيْتُونَةٌ represents life, resilience, and prosperity, and is often associated with enduring faith and the continuous provision of blessings.",
  "1908": "زَيْدُ and related words stem from the root ز-ي-د, with the root verb زَادَ meaning \"he increased\" or \"he augmented.\" زَيْدُ is a male name meaning \"increase\" or \"abundance.\" The connection lies in the notion of growth and enhancement. Zayd ibn Harithah (may Allah be pleased with him) was a close companion and adopted son of the Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ), whose life exemplified personal growth and devotion. The name symbolizes blessings and the idea that one's character and good deeds can continuously increase.",
  "1909": "زَيْغٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ي-غ, with the root verb زَاغَ meaning \"he deviated\" or \"he swerved.\" زَيْغٌ means \"deviation,\" \"error,\" or \"straying.\" The connection lies in the state of being misaligned or turned away from the correct path, embodying the root's concept of deviation. زَيْغٌ highlights the importance of vigilance in maintaining faith and the need for constant guidance to prevent falling into error.",
  "1910": "زُبَرٌ and related words also derive from the root ز-ب-ر, with زَبَرَ meaning \"he wrote\" or \"he hewed.\" زُبَرٌ is the plural of زُبْرَةٌ, meaning \"blocks,\" \"sheets,\" or \"pieces,\" particularly of iron. The root’s dimension of engraving extends to shaping solid materials, reflecting effort and precision. زُبَرٌ highlights the strength and permanence associated with carved or shaped objects.",
  "1911": "زُبُرٌ similarly stems from the root ز-ب-ر, with زَبَرَ meaning \"he wrote\" or \"he inscribed.\" زُبُرٌ is the plural of زَبُورٌ, meaning \"books\" or \"scriptures,\" emphasizing the collection of written works. The connection lies in the act of compiling and preserving texts, highlighting the root’s focus on engraving knowledge into a lasting form.",
  "1912": "زُجَاجَةٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ج-ج, with the root verb زَجَّ meaning \"he pushed\" or \"he thrust.\" زُجَاجَةٌ means \"glass\" or \"glass vessel.\" The connection lies in the crafting process where molten glass is shaped by blowing or pushing, directly relating to the root's concept of thrusting or forming materials.",
  "1913": "زُحْزِحَ and related words stem from the root ز-ح-ز-ح, with the verb زَحْزَحَ meaning \"he removed,\" \"he displaced,\" or \"he caused to move away.\" زُحْزِحَ is the passive form, meaning \"he was removed\" or \"he was displaced.\" The root conveys the idea of deliberate removal or shifting from one place or state to another, often implying effort or force. This word reflects this as it emphasizes the state of being moved or distanced, embodying the root's concept of separation or displacement from a position or condition.",
  "1914": "زُخْرُفٌ stems from the root ز-خ-ر-ف, with the verb meaning \"he adorned\" or \"he embellished.\" It refers to \"ornament\" or \"adornment,\" often associated with intricate decoration, such as gold embellishments. The root embodies the idea of beautification and enhancement, reflected in the term as it signifies the act of adding beauty or refinement. This connection highlights the core concept of aesthetic improvement through intricate and ornamental details.",
  "1915": "زُرَّاعٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ر-ع, with the root verb زَرَعَ meaning \"he sowed\" or \"he planted.\" زُرَّاعٌ is the plural of زَارِعٌ, meaning \"farmers\" or \"sowers.\" The connection emphasizes the collective effort of those who cultivate the land, reflecting the root's concept of sowing seeds and nurturing growth on a communal scale.",
  "1916": "زُرْتُمُ and related words stem from the root ز-و-ر, with the root verb زَارَ meaning \"he visited\" or \"he went to see someone.\" زُرْتُمُ means \"you (plural) visited\" or \"you went to see.\" The connection lies in the act of intentionally seeking out a person, place, or thing, reflecting the root’s focus on deliberate visitation."
};
